als %0aalready mentioned, while those that are more aged stay within %0athe hives and work. The bees whose business it is to cany %0athe flowers, with their fore feet load their thighs, which Nature %0ahas made rough for the purpose, and Avith their trunks load %0a%0a2* Or, the "wild man." %0a%0a22 Huber has discovered that there are two kinds of bees of neutral sex, %0aor, as he calls them, unprolific females, tlie workers, which so out, and %0athe nurses, which are smaller, and stay in the hive to tend the larvje. %0a%0a%0a%0aCbap. 10.] %0a%0a%0a%0aBEES. %0a%0a%0a%0a9 %0a%0a%0a%0atheir fore feet : bending beneath their load, they then return %0ato the hive, where there are three or four bees ready to receive %0athem and aid in discharging their burdens. For, within the %0ahive as well, they have their allotted duties to perform : some %0aare engaged in building, others in. smoothing, the combs, while %0aothers again are occupied in passing on the materials, and %0aothers in preparing food'-^ from the provision which has been %0abi'ought ; that there may be no unequal division, either in their %0alabour, their food, or the distribution of their time, they do not %0aeven feed separately. %0a%0aCommencing at the vaulted roof of the hive, they begin %0athe construction of their cells, and, just as we do in the manu- %0afacture of a web, they construct their cells from top to bottom, %0ataking care to leave two passages around each compartment, %0afor the entrance of some and the exit of others. The combs, %0awhich are fastened to the hive in the upper part, and in a %0aslight degree also at the sides, adhere to each other, and are %0athus suspended altogether. They do not touch the floor of the %0ahive, and are either angular or round, according to its shape ; %0asometimes, in fact, they are both angular and round at once, %0awhen two swarms are living in unison, but have dissimilar %0amodes of operation. They prop up the combs that are likely %0ato fall, bj' means of