by giving the signal, as it were, to retire to rest : in this, too, %0athey imitate the usage of the camp. The moment the signal %0ais heard, aU is silent. %0a%0a(11.) They first construct the dwellings of the commonalty, %0aand then those of the king-bee. If they have reason to expect %0aan abundant ^ season, they add abodes also for the drones : %0athese are ceUs of a smaller size, though the drones themselves %0aare larger than the bees. %0a%0aCHAP. 11. — DEONES. %0a%0aThe drones have no sting,-* and would seem to be a kind of %0aimperfect bee, formed the very last of all ; the expiring effort, %0aas it were, of worn-out and exhausted old age, a late and tardy %0aofi'spring, and doomed, in a measure, to be the slaves of the %0agenuine bees. Hence it is that the bees exercise over them a %0arigorous authority, compel them to take the foremost rank in %0atheir labours, and if they show any sluggishness, punish them*' %0awithout mercy. And not only in their labours do the drones %0agive them their assistance, but in the propagation of their spe- %0acies as well, the very multitude of them contributing greatly %0ato the warmth of the hive. At all events, it is a well-known %0afact, that the greater"^ the multitude of the drones, the more %0a%0aCuvier says that the three kinds of cells are absolutely necessary, and %0athat they do not depend on the greater or less abundance. The king of %0athe ancients is what we know as the queen bee, which is impregnated by the %0adrones or males. %0a%0a26 This is the fact, but not so their imperfect state. %0a%0a2' They do not work, but merely impregnate the queen ; after which %0athey are driven from the hive, and perish of cold and starvation. %0a%0a"■^ It appears, as Cuvier says, that the ancients had some notion that the %0aswarm was multiplied by the aid of the drones. %0a%0a%0a%0aChap. 12.] %0a%0a%0a%0aQTTALTTIES OF HO>"ET. %0a%0a%0a%0a11 %0a%0a%0a%0anumerous is sure to be the progeny of the swarm. When fhe %0ahoney is beginning to come to maturity, the bees drive away %0athe drones, and setting upon each in great numbers, put them %0aall to death. It is only in the spring that the drones are %0aever to be seen. If you deprive a drone of its wings, and then %0areplace it in the hive, it will pull off the wings of the other %0adrones. %0a%0aCH.\P. 12, — THE QtrALITIES OF HOITEY. %0a%0aIn the lower part of the hive they construct for their future %0asovereign a palatial abode,-'' spacious and grand, separated from %0athe rest, and surmounted by a sort of dome : if this promi- %0anence should happen to be flattened, all hopes of progeny- are %0alost. All the cells are hexagonal, each foot^" having formed %0aits own side. No part of this work, however, is done at any %0astated time, as the bees seize every opportunity for the perform- %0aance of their task when the days are fine ; in one or two %0adays, at most, they fill their cells with honey. %0a%0a(12.) This substance is engendered from the air,^- mostly at %0athe rising of the constellations, and more especially when %0aSirius is shining ; never, however, before the rising of the %0aVergiliae, and then just before day-break. Hence it is, that at %0aearly dawn the leaves of the trees are found covered with a %0akind of honey-like dew, and those who go into the open air at %0aan early hour in the morning, find their clothes covered, and %0atheir hair matted, with a sort of unctuous liquid. "Whether %0ait is that this liquid is the sweat of the heavens, or whether %0au saliva emanating from the stars, or a juice exuding from the %0aair while purifying itself, would that it had been, when it %0acom.e8 to us, pure, limpid, and genuine, as it was, when first %0ait took its downward descent. But as it is, falling from so %0avast a height, attracting corruption in its passage, and tainted %0aby the exhalations of the earth as it meets them, sucked, too, %0aas it is from off the trees and the herbage of the fields, and %0aaccumulated in the stomachs of the bees — for they cast it up %0a%0a2' Cuvier says that the cell for the future queen is different from the %0aothers, and much larger. The bees also supply the queen larva much more %0aabundantly with food, and of more delicate quality. %0a%0a^" (Cuvier says that this coincidence with the number of the legs is quite %0aaccidental, as it is with the mouth that the animal constructs the cell. %0aThe basis of it is really derived from the calix or corolla of flowers. %0a%0a%0a%0aI %0a%0a%0a%0a12 %0a%0a%0a%0aplutt's natueal histoet. %0a%0a%0a%0a[Book XI. %0a%0a%0a%0aagain through the mouth— deteriorated besides by the juices %0aof flowers, and then steeped within the hives and subjected to %0asuch repeated changes— still, in spite of all this, it aflords us %0aby its flavour a most exquisite pleasure, the result, no doubt, %0aof its aethereal nature and origin. %0a%0aCHAP. 13. (13.) WHEKE THE BEST HONEY IS PRODUCED. %0a%0aThe honey is always best in those countries where it is to %0abe found deposited in the calix of the most exquisite flowers, %0asuch, for instance, as the districts of Hymettus and Hybla, %0ain Attica and Sicily respectively, and after them the island of %0aCalydna.^- At first, honey is thin, like water, after which it %0aeffervesces for some days, and purifies itself like must. On %0athe twentieth day it begins to thicken, and soon after becomes %0acovered with a thin membrane, which gradually increases %0athrough the scum which is thrown up by the heat. The %0ahoney of the very finest flavour, and the least tainted by the %0aleaves of trees, is that gathered from the foKage of the oak %0aand the linden, and from reeds. %0a%0aCHAP. 14. (14.) — THE KINDS OF HONEY PECtJXIAK TO VARIOUS %0aPLACES. %0a%0aThe peculiar excellence of honey depends, as already stated," %0aon the country in which it is produced ; the modes, too, of %0aestimating its quality are numerous. In some countries we find %0athe honey-comb remarkable for the goodness of the wax, as iu %0aSicily, for instance, and the country of the Peligni ; in other %0aplaces the honey itself is found in greater abundance, as in %0aCrete, Cyprus, and Africa ; and in others, again, the comb is %0aremarkable for its size ; the northern climates, for instance, %0afor in Germany a comb has been known to be as much as eight %0afeet in length, and quite black on the concave surface. %0a%0aButwhatever the country in which it may happen to have been %0aproduced, there are three different kinds of honey. — Spring %0ahoney is that made in a comb which has been constructed of %0aflowers, from which cii'cumstance it has received the name of %0athinum. There are some persons who say that this should not %0abe touched, because the more abundant the nutriment, the %0a%0a32 See B. iv. c. 24. 33 the last Chapter. %0a%0a34 Qr " Flower-honey." %0a%0a%0a%0aChap. 14.] %0a%0a%0a%0aVAHIOTJS KIKDS OF HONEY. %0a%0a%0a%0a13 %0a%0a%0a%0astronger Avill be the coming swarm ; while others, again, leave %0aless of this honey than of any other for the bees, on the ground %0athat there is sure to be a vast abundance at the rising of the %0agreater constellations, as well as at the summer solstice, when %0athe thyme and the vine begin to blossom, for then they are %0asure to find abundant materials for their cells. %0a%0aIn taking the combs the greatest care is always requisite, for %0awhen they are stinted for food the bees become desperate, and %0aeither pine to death, or else wing their flight to other places : %0abut on the other hand, over-abundance will entail idleness, %0aand then they will feed upon the honey, and not the bee-bread. %0aHence it is that the most careful breeders take care to leave %0athe bees a fifteenth part of this gathering. There is a certain %0aday for beginning the honey-gathering, fixed, as it were, by a %0alaw of Nature, if men would only understand or observe it, %0abeing the thirtieth day after the bees have swarmed and come %0aforth. This gathering mostly takes place before the end of %0aMay. %0a%0aThe second kind of honey is "summer honey," which, from %0athe circumstance of its being produced at the most favourable %0aseason, has received the Greek name of horaion it is gene- %0arally made during the next thirty days after the solstice, while %0aSirius is shining in all its brilliancy. Nature has revealed in %0athis substance most remarkable properties to mortals, were it %0anot that the fraudulent propensities of man are apt to falsify %0aand corrupt everything. For, after the rising of each constel- %0alation, and those of the highest rank more particularly, or after %0athe appearance of the rainbow, if a shower does not ensue, %0abut the dew becomes warmed by the sun's rays, a medicament, %0aand not real honey, is produced ; a gift sent from heaven for %0athe cure of diseases of the eyes, ulcers, and maladies of the %0ainternal viscera. If this is taken at the rising of Sirius, and %0athe rising of Yenus, Jupiter, or Mercury should happen to fall %0aon the same day, as ' often is the case, the sweetness of this %0asubstance, and the virtue which it possesses of restoring men %0ato life, are not inferior to those attributed to the nectar of the %0agods. %0a%0a%0a%0a3* Season-honey. %0a%0a%0a%0a14 %0a%0a%0a%0aPLI^^l's NATUEAL HISTOSr. %0a%0a%0a%0a[Book XI. %0a%0a%0a%0aCHAP. 15. (16.) HOW HONEY IS TESTED. HIUC-IIUM. XEIRA- %0a%0aUX, OK SISIUUM. %0a%0aThe crop of honey is most abundant if gathered at full %0amoon, and it is richest when the weather is fine. In all %0ahoney, that which flows of itself, like must or oil, has received %0afrom'us the name of acetum."^ The summer honey is the most %0aesteemed of all, from the fact of its being made when the %0aweather is driest : it is looked upon as the most serviceable %0awhen made from thyme it is then of a golden colour, and %0aof a most delicious flavour. The honey that we sec formed %0ain the calix of flowers is of a rich and unctuous nature ; that %0awhich is