ery much from the %0arest of the community, in their bright and shining appearance. %0a%0aCHAP. 17. (17.) THE MODE OF GOVERNMENT OF THE BEES. %0a%0aLet a man employ himself, forsooth, in the enquiry whether %0athere has been only one Hercules, how many fathers Liber %0athere have been, and all the other questions which are buried %0adeep in the mould of antiquity .' Here behold a tiny object, %0aone to be met with at most of our country retreats, and num- %0abers of which are always at hand, and yet, after all, it is not %0aagreed among authors whether or not the king'^ is the only one %0aamong them that is provided with no sting, and is possessed %0aof no other arms than those afforded him by his majestic office, %0aor whether, Nature has granted him a sting, and has only denied %0ahim the power of making use of it ; it being a well-knowu %0afact, that the ruling bee never does use a sting. The obedi- %0aence which his subjects manifest in his presence is quite sur- %0aprising. When he goes forth, the whole swarm attends him, %0athrongs about him, surrounds him, protects him, and will not %0aallow him to be seen. At other times, when the swarm is at %0awork within, the king is seen to visit the works, and appears %0ato be giving his encouragement, being himself the only one %0athat is exempt from work : around him are certain other bees %0awhich act as' body-guards and lictors, the careful guardians of %0ahis authority. The king never quits tlie hive except when the %0aswarm is about to depart ; a thing which may be known a long %0atime beforehand, as for some days a peculiar buzzing noise %0ais to be heard within, which denotes that the bees are waiting %0afor a favourable day, and making all due preparations for their %0adeparture. On such an occasion, if care is taken to deprive the %0aking of one of his wings, the swarm will not fiy away. When %0athey are on the wing, everyone is anxious to be near him, and %0atakes a pleasure in being seen in the performance of its duty. %0aWhen he is weary, they support him on their shoulders ; and %0a%0a58 The greater size of the abdomen makes the wings look shorter. %0a%0a59 The queen has a sting, like the working bees, but uses it less fre- %0aquently. %0a%0a%0a%0aChap. 18 ] OMENS AFFOEDED BY A SWARM OF BEES. 19 %0a%0a%0a%0awhen he is quite tired, they carry him outright. If one of them %0afalls in the rear from weariness, or happens to go astray, it is %0aable to follow the others by the aid of its aeuteness of smell. %0a"Wherever the king bee happens to settle, that becomes the %0aencampment of all. %0a%0aCH.U'. 18. H.vrPY OMENS SOMETIMES AFFOEDED BY A SWAKM %0a%0aOF BEES. %0a%0aAnd then, too, it is that they afford presages both of private %0aand public interest, clustering, as they do, like a bunch of %0agrapes, upon houses or temples ; presages, in fact, that are often %0aaccounted for by great events. Bees settled upon the lips of %0aPlato when still an infant even, announcing thereby the sweet- %0aness of that persuasive eloquence for which he was so noted. %0aBees settled, too, in the camp of the chieftain Drusus when, %0ahe gained the brilliant victory at Arbalo f° a proof, indeed, %0athat the conjectures of soothsayers are not hy any means in- %0afallible, seeing that they are of opinion that this is always of %0aevil augmy. AVhen their leader is withheld from them, the %0aswarm can always be detained ; and when lost, it will disperse %0aand take its departure to find other kings. Without a king, %0ain fact, thej^ cannot exist, and it is with the greatest reluct- %0aance that they put them to death when there are several ; they %0a2)refer, too, to destroy the cells of the j'oung ones, if they find %0areason to despair of providing food ; in such case they then %0aexpel the drones. And yet, with regard to the last, I find that %0asome doubts are entertained ; and that there are some authors %0awho are of opinion that they form a peculiar species, like that %0abee, the very l