dies, speckled all over, and of a compact round shape. %0aThose that are long, and resemble the wasp in appearance, %0aare an inferior kind ; and of these last, the very worst of all %0aare those which have the body covered with hair. In Pontus %0athere is a kind of white bee, which makes honey twice a %0amonth. On the banks of the river Thermodon there are %0atwo kinds found, one of which makes honey in the trees, the %0aother under ground : they form a triple row of combs, and %0aproduce honey in the greatest abundance. %0a%0aNature has provided bees with a sting, which is inserted in %0athe abdomen of the insect. There are some who think that %0aat the first blow which they inflict with this weapon they will %0ainstantly die,^' while others, again, are of opinion that such is %0anot the case, unless the animal drives it so deep as to cause %0aa portion of the intestines to follow ; and they assert, also, %0athat after they have thus lost their sting they become drones," %0a%0a8- So Virgil says — %0a%0a■ " Haec certamina tanta %0a%0aPulveris exigui jactu compressa quiescent." — Georg. iv. 87. %0aIf it is left in the wound, the insect dies, being torn asunder %0a«i Of course this is fabulous, as the drones are males. %0a%0a%0a%0aChap. 20.] %0a%0a%0a%0aTHE DISEASES OF BEES. %0a%0a%0a%0a21 %0a%0a%0a%0aand make no honey, being thus castrated, so to say, and %0aequally incapable of inflicting injury, and of making themselves %0auseful by their labours. We have instances stated of horses %0abeing killed by bees. %0a%0aThey have a great aversion to bad smells, and fly away %0afrom them ; a dislike which extends to artificial perfumes %0aeven. Hence it is that they will attack persons who smell %0aof unguents. They themselves, also, are exposed to the %0aattacks of wasps and hornets, which belong to the same class, %0abut are of a degenerate^ nature ; these wage continual warfare %0aagainst them, as also does a species of gnat, which is known %0aby the name of " mulio;""®