ebs similar to those of the spider, the %0amaterial of which is used for making the more costly and %0aluxurious garments of females, known as " bombycina. Pam- %0aphile, a woman of Cos,**' the daughter of Platea, was the first %0aperson who discovered the art of unravelling these webs and %0aspinning a tissue therefrom ; indeed, she ought not to be de- %0aprived of the glorj' of having discovered the art of making %0avestments which, while they cover a woman, at the same mo- %0ament reveal her naked charms. %0a%0aCHAP. 27. (23.) THE SILK-WORM OF COS HOW THE COAN %0a%0aVESTMENTS ARE MADE. %0a%0aThe silk-worm, too, is said to be a native of the isle of Cos, %0awhere the vapours of the earth give new life to the flowers %0aof the cypress, the terebinth, the ash, and the oak which have %0abeen beaten down by the showers. At first they assume the %0aappearance of small butterflies with naked bodies, but soon %0aafter, being unable to endure the cold, they throw out bristly %0ahairs, and assume quite a thick coat against the winter, by %0arubbing off the down that covers the leaves, by the aid of %0athe roughness of their feet. This they compress into balls %0aby carding it with their claws, and then draw it out and %0ahang it between the branches of the trees, making it fine %0aby combing it out as it were : last of all, they take and roll it %0around their body, thus forming a nest in which they are enve- %0aloped. It is in this state that they are taken ; after which %0athey are placed in earthen vessels in a warm place, and fed %0aupon bran. A peculiar sort of down soon shoots forth upon %0athe body, on being clothed with which they are sent to work %0aupon another task. The cocoons®^ which they have begun to %0at'orm are rendered soft and pliable by the aid of water, and %0aare then drawn out into threads by means of a spindle made of %0aa reed. Nor, in fact, have the men even felt ashamed to make %0ause^ of garments formed of this material, in consequence of %0a%0a