iods the excrements are largely %0asecreted in the abdomen, as Democritus thinks, or that the %0acreature has in itself a certain faculty of secreting®* a peculiar %0asort of woolly substance. How steadily does it work with its %0aclaws, how beautifully rounded and how equal are the threads %0aas it forms its web, while it employs the weight of its body as %0aan equipoise ! It begins at the middle to weave its web, and %0athen extends it by adding the threads in rings around, like a %0awarp upon the woof : forming the meshes at equal intervals, %0abut continually enlarging them as the web increases in breadth, %0ait finally unites them all by an indissoluble knot. "With what %0awondrous art does it conceal the snares that lie in wait %0afor its prey in its checkered nettings ! How little, too, woidd %0ait seem that there is any such trap laid in the compactness of %0a%0aenacted " ne vestis Serica viros faedaret" — " That men should not defile %0athemselves by wearing garments of silk," Ann. B. ii. c. 33. %0a*" The Ai-anea lupus of Linnseus. %0a%0aAs Cuvier observes, he has here guessed at the truth. %0a%0a%0a%0a28 %0a%0a%0a%0aPLIirr's NATURAL niSTOET. %0a%0a%0a%0aBook XI. %0a%0a%0a%0aits web and the tenacious texture of the woof, wliich Avould %0aappear of itself to be finished and arranged by the exercise of %0athe very highest art ! How loose, too, is the body of the web %0aas it yields to the blasts, and how readily does it catch all objects %0awhich come in its way ! You Avould fancy that it had left, %0aquite exhausted, the thrums of the upper portion of its net %0aunfinished where they are spread across ; it is with the great- %0aest difficulty that they are to be perceived, and yet the moment %0athat an object touches them, like the lines of the hunter's net, %0athey throw it into the body of the web. With what archi- %0atectural skill, too, is its hole arched over, and how well de- %0afended by a nap of extra thickness against the cold ! How %0acarefully, to