e grains, again, which %0aare too large for admission, they divide at the entrance of their %0aholes ; and those which have become soaked by the rain, they %0abring out and dry.^® They work, too, by night, during the %0afull moon ; but when there is no moon, they cease working. %0aAnd then, too, in their labours, what ardour they display, %0awhat wondrous carefulness ! Because they collect their stores %0afrom different quarters, in ignorance of the proceedings of one %0aanother, they have certain days set apart for holding a kind of %0amarket, on which they meet together and take stock.^' What vast %0athrongs are then to be seen hurrying together, what anxious %0aenquiries appear to be made, and what earnest parleys^ are %0agoing on among them as they meet ! We see even the very %0astones worn away by their footsteps, and roads beaten down %0aby being the scene of their labours. Let no one be in doubt, %0athen, how much assiduity and application, even in the very %0ahumblest of objects, can upon every occasion effect ! Ants are %0athe only living beings, besides man, that bestow burial on the %0adead. In Sicily there are no winged ants to be found. %0a%0a(31.) The horns of an Indian ant, suspended in the temple %0a%0aup grains against the winter, a period through which in reality they do %0anot eat. %0a%0a55 They stow away hits of meat and detached portions of fruit, tonourisli %0atheir larvae with their juices. %0a%0a^ It is in reality their larvae that they thus bring out to dry. The %0aworking ants, or neutrals, are the ones on which these labours devolve: %0athe males and females are winged, the working ants are without wings. %0a" Ad recognitionem mutuam." %0a%0a38 Some modern writers express an opinion that when they meet, they %0aconverse and encourage one another by the medium of touch and smell. %0a%0a%0a%0aChap. 37.] %0a%0a%0a%0aTHE CHKT8ALIS. %0a%0a%0a%0a39 %0a%0a%0a%0aof Hercules, at ErythreB,^' have been looked upon as quite %0amiraculous for their size. This ant excavates gold from holes, %0ain a country in the north of India, the inhabitants of which are %0aknown as the Dard®. It has the colour of a cat, and is in %0asize as large as an Egyptian wolf.*° This gold, which it ex- %0atracts in the winter, is taken by the Indians during the heats %0aof summer, while the ants are compelled, by the excessive %0awarmth, to hide themselves in their holes. Still, however, %0aon being aroused by catching the scent of the Indians, they %0asally forth, and frequently tear them to pieces, though pro- %0avided with the swiftest camels for the purpose of flight ; so %0agreat is their fleetness, combined with their ferocity and their %0apassion for gold ! %0a%0aCHAP. 37. (32.) — THE CHRYSALIS. %0a%0aMany insects, however, ai'e engendered in a different man- %0aner ; and some more especially from dew. This dew settles %0aupon the radish" leaf in the early days of spring ; but when it %0ahas been thickened by the action of the sun, it becomes re- %0aduced to the size of a grain of millet. From this a small grub %0aafterwards arises, which, at the end of three days, becomes %0atransformed into a caterpillar. For several successive days %0ait still increases in size, but remains motionless, and covered %0awith a hard husk. It moves only when touched, and is %0acovered with a web like that of the spider. In this state it %0ais called a chrysalis, but after the husk is broken, it flies forth %0ain the shape of a butterfly. %0a39 See B. V. c. 31. %0a%0a*" M. de Veltheini thinks that by this is really meant the Canis corsac, %0athe small fox of India, but that by some mistake it was represented by %0atravellers as an ant. It is not improbable, Cuvier says, that some quadru- %0aped, in making holes in the ground, may have occasionally thrown up some %0agrains of the precious metal. The story is derived from the narratives %0aof Clearchus and Megasthenes. Another interpretation of this story has %0aalso been suggested. We find from some 