 of our Saxon ancestors are well known to the %0aantiquarian. %0a%0aThe " urna" was half an "amphora," or nearly three gallons. %0a^5 See B. XXXV. c. 41. %0a%0a%0a%0a46 %0a%0a%0a%0aFlint's natukal history. %0a%0a%0a%0a[Book XI. %0a%0a%0a%0afour in number upon one head. In females the horns are gene- %0arally thinner than in the males, as is the case, also, with most %0akinds of wool-bearing animals. %0a%0aNo individuals, however, among sheep, or hinds, nor yet %0aany that have the feet divided into toes, or that have solid %0ahoofs, are furnished with horns ; with the sole exception of %0athe Indian ass,'^ which is armed with a single horn. To the %0abeasts that are cloven-footed Nature has granted two horns, %0abut to those that have fore-teeth in the upper jaw, she has %0agiven none. Those persons who entertain the notion that the %0asubstance of these teeth is expended in the formation of the %0ahorns, are easily to be refuted, if we only consider the case of %0athe hind, which has no more teeth than the male, and 5-et %0ais without horns altogether. In the stag the horn is only %0aimbedded in the skin, but in the other" animals it adheres to %0athe bone. %0a%0aCHAP. 46. THE HEADS OP ANIMALS. THOSE WHICH HAVE NOSF. %0a%0aThe head of the fish is very large in proportion to the rest %0aof the body, probably, to facilitate its diving under water. %0aAnimals of the oyster and the sponge kind have no head, %0awhich is the case, also, with most of the other kinds, whose %0aonly sense is that of touch. Some, again, have the head %0ablended with the body, the crab, for instance. %0a%0aCHAP. 47. THE HAIR. %0a%0aOf all animals man has the longest hair upon the head ; which %0ais the case more especially with those nations where the men and %0awomen in common leave the hair to grow, and do not cut it. %0aIndeed, it is from this fact, that the inhabitants of the Alps %0ahave obtained from us the name of " Capillati,"'* as also those %0aof Gallia, " Comata."'^ There is, however, a great difference %0ain this respect according to the various countries. In the %0aisland of Myconus,^" the people are bom without hair, just %0aas at Caunus the inhabitants are afflicted with the spleen %0a%0a'6 The rhinoceros. See B. viii. c. 39. %0a%0a" He surely must except the Phrygian oxen with the moveable horns, %0awhich he has previously mentioned. %0a'8 Or " long-haired." See B. iii. c. 7. %0a" See B. iv. c. 31. so See B. iv. c. 22. %0a%0a%0a%0aChap. 49.] %0a%0a%0a%0aTHE BEALN. %0a%0a%0a%0a47 %0a%0a%0a%0afrom their birth. There are some animals, also, that are natu- %0arally bald, such as the ostrich, for instance, and the aquatic %0araven, which last has thence derived its Greek"'^ name. It is %0abut rarely that the hair falls off in women, and in eunuchs %0asuch is never known to be the case ; nor yet does any person %0alose it before having known sexual intercourse.®^ The hair %0adoes not fall off below the brain, nor yet beneath the crown of %0athe head, or around the ears and the temples. Man is the %0aonly animal that becomes bald, with the exception, of course, %0aof such animals as are naturally so. Man and the horse are %0athe only creatures whose hair turns grey ; but with man this is %0aalways the case, fii'st in the fore-part of the head, and then in %0athe hinder part. %0a%0aCHAP. 48. — THE BONES OF THE HEAD. %0a%0aSome few persons only are double- crowned. The bones of %0athe head are flat, thin, devoid of marrow, and united with su- %0atures indented like a comb. When broken asunder they can- %0anot be united, but the extraction of a small portion is not ne- %0acessarily fatal, as a fleshy cicatrix forms, and so makes good %0athe loss. We have already mentioned, in their respective** %0aplaces, that the skull of the bear is the weakest of all, and %0athat of the parrot the hardest. %0a%0aCHAP. 49. THE BEAIN. %0a%0aThe brain exists in all animals which have blood, and in %0athose sea animals as well, which we have already mentioned %0aas mollusks, although they are destitute of blood, the poly- %0apus, for instance. Man, however, has, in proportion to his %0abody, the most voluminous brain of all. This, too, is the %0amost humid, and the coldest of all the viscera, and is enve- %0aloped above and below with two membranous integuments, %0afor either of which to be broken is fatal. In addition to these %0afacts, we may remark that the brain is larger in men than iu %0a%0a«i Sec B. v. c. 29. %0a%0a%3c^a\aKpoKupa^. See B. X. C. 68. %0a^ lie borrows this from Aristotle. %0a%0aB. viii. c. 54, and B. x. c. 58. The skull of the bear is not thinner %0aor weaker than that of other animals of its own size ; but the skull of iLe %0aparrot, in proportion to those of other birds, is remarkably hard. %0a%0a%0a%0a48 %0a%0a%0a%0aPLTNT'S NATURAL HISTOBT. %0a%0a%0a%0a[Book XL %0a%0a%0a%0awomen. In man the brain is destitute of blood and veins, and %0ain other animals it has no fat. Those who are well informed %0aon the subject, tell us that the brain is quite a different %0asubstance from the marrow, seeing that on being boiled it %0aonly becomes harder. In the very middle of the braia of %0aevery animal there are small bones found. Man is the only ani- %0amal in which it is kno-svn to palpitate"^ during infancy ; and %0ait does not gain its proper consistency until after the child has %0amade its first attempt to speak. The brain is the most ele- %0avated of all the viscera, and the nearest to the roof of the %0ahead ; it is equally devoid of flesh, blood, and excretions. The %0asenses hold this organ as their citadel ; it is in this that %0aare centred all the veins which spring from the heart ; it is %0ahere that they terminate ; this is the very culminating point of %0aall, the regulator of the understanding. "With all animals it %0ais advanced to the fore-part of the head, from the fact that %0athe senses have a tendency to the direction in which we look. %0aFrom the brain proceeds sleep, and its return it is that causes %0athe head to nod. Those creatures, in fact, which have no brain, %0anever sleep. It is said that stags^^ have in the head certain %0asmall maggots, twenty in number : they are situate in the %0aempty space that lies beneath the tongue, and around the joints %0aby which the head is united to the body. %0a%0aCHAP. 50. — THE EAKS. ANIMALS WHICH HEAB WITHOUT EiES %0aOil APERTXJKES. %0a%0aMan is the only animal the ears of which are immoveable. %0aIt is from the natural flaccidity of the ear, that the surname %0aof Flaccus is derived. There is no part of the body that %0acreates a more enormous expense for our women, in the %0apearls which are suspended from them. In the East, too, it %0ais thought highly becoming for the men, even, to wear gold %0arings in their ears. Some animals have large, and others %0asmall ears. The stag alone has them cut and divided, as it %0awere ; in the field-mouse they have a velvet surface. AU the %0aanimals that are viviparous have ears of some kind or other, %0awith the sole exception of the sea-calf, the dolphin, the fishes %0a%0a85 See B. vii. c. 1. %0a%0a65 Cuvier says that fhese are the larvae of the oestrus, which are deposited %0aon the lips of quadrupeds, and so make their way to various cavities. %0a%0a%0a%0aCbap. 02.] %0a%0a%0a%0aTUE ElES. %0a%0a%0a%0a49 %0a%0a%0a%0awhich we have mentioned^' as cartilaginous, and the viper. %0aThese animals have only cavities instead of ears, with the ex- %0aception of the cartilaginous fishes and the dolphin, which last, %0ahowever, it is quite clear possesses the sense of hearing, for it is %0acharmed by singing, and is often taken while enraptured with %0athe melody: how it is that it does hear, is quite marvellous. %0aThese animals, too, have not the slightest trace of olfactory %0aorgans, and yet they have a most acute sense of smell. %0a%0aAmong the winged animals, only the horned owl and the long- %0aeared owl have feathers which project like ears, the rest having %0aonly cavities for the purpose of hearing ; the same is the case, %0aalso, with the scaly animals and the serpents. Among horses %0aand beasts of burden of all kinds, it is the ears which indicate %0athe natural feelings; when the animal is weary, they are droop- %0aing and flaccid ; when it is startled, they quiver to and fro ; %0awhen it is enraged, they are pricked up ; and when it is ailing, %0athey are pendant. %0a%0aCHAP. 51. — THE FACE, THE FOKEHEAD, AND THE ETE-BEOWS. %0a%0aMan is the only creature that has a face, the other animals %0ahaving only a muzzle or a beak. Other animals have a fore- %0ahead as well, but it is only on the forehead of man that is %0adepicted sorrow, gladness, compassion, or severity. It is the %0aforehead that is the index of the mind. Man has eyebrows, %0aalso, which move together or alternately ; these, too, serve in %0asome measure as indications of the feelings. Do we deny or %0ado we assent, it is the eyebrows, mostly, that indicate our %0aintentions. Feelings of pride may be generated elsewhere, %0abut it is here that they have their principal abode ; it is in the %0aheart that they take their rise, but it is to the eyebrows that %0athey mount, and here they take up their position. In no part %0aof the body could they meet with a spot more lofty and more %0aprecipitous, in which to establish themselves free from aU %0acontrol. %0a%0aCHAP. 52. THE EYES — ANIMAIS WHICH HAVE NO EYES, OR HAVE %0a%0aONLY ONE EYE. %0a%0aBelow the forehead are the eyes, which form the most pre- %0acious portion of the human body, and which, by the enjoyment %0a%0a8' B. ix. c. 40. %0a%0aVOL. Ill, B %0a%0a%0a%0a50 %0a%0a%0a%0aFlint's natubal histohy. %0a%0a%0a%0a[Book XI. %0a%0a%0a%0aof the blessings of sight, distinguish life from death. Eyes, %0ahowever, have not been granted to all animals ; oysters have %0anone, but, with reference to some of the shell-fish, the question %0ais still doubtful ; for if we move the fingers before a scallop %0ahalf open, it will immediately close its shell, apparently from %0aseeing them, while the solen^^ will start away from an iron %0ainstrument when placed near it. Among quadrupeds the %0amole*' has no sight, though it has something that bears a re- %0asemblance to eyes, if we remove the membrane that is ex- %0atended in front of them. Among birds also, it is said that %0aa species of heron, which is known as the "leucus,"^ is %0awanting of one eye : a bird of most excellent augury, when %0ait flies towards the south or north, for it is said that it %0aportends thereby that there is about to be an end of perils and %0aalarms. Nigidius says also, that neither locusts nor grass- %0ahoppers have eyes. In snails,**^ the two small horns with which %0athey feel their way, perform the duties of eyes. Neither tlie %0amawworm^- nor any other kind of worm has eyes. %0a%0aCHAP. 53. — THE DIVEESITY OF THE COLOUK OF THE EYES. %0a%0aThe eyes vary in colour in the human race only ; in all %0aother animals they are of one uniform colour peculiar to the %0akind, though there are some horses that have eyes of an azure %0acolour. But in man the varieties and diversities are most %0anumerous ; the eyes being either large, of middling size, re- %0amarkably small, or remarkably prominent. These last are %0agenerally supposed to be very weak, while those which are %0adeep-seated are considered the best, as is the case also with %0athose which in colour resemble the eyes of the goat. %0a%0aCHAP. 54. THE THEOET OF SIGHT — PERSONS WHO CAX SEE BT %0a%0aNIGHT. %0a%0aIn addition to this, there are some persons who can see to a %0a^ Or razor-sheath. See B. x. c. 88. %0a%0a89 Aristotle was of this opinion, but Galen maintained that the mole can %0asee. Its eye is extremely small, and hard on the surface. %0a%0a90 Or "white" heron. As Cuvier remarks, this is probably a mere %0aaugur's fable. %0a%0a^ It is almost needless to remark, that both snails, as well as locusts and %0agrasshoppers, have eyes. %0a8* Lumbricus. %0a%0a%0a%0aChap. 54.] %0a%0a%0a%0atBe theoet or sight. %0a%0a%0a%0a51 %0a%0a%0a%0avery great distance, while there are others, again, -who can only %0adistinguish objects when brought quite close to them. The %0avision of many stands in need of the rays of the sun ; such %0apersons cannot see on a cloudy day, nor yet after the sun has %0aset. Others, again, have bad sight in the day-time, but a %0asight superior to that of others by night. Of persons having %0adouble pupils, or the evil eye, we have already spoken'^ at %0asufficient length. Blue^* eyes are the best for seeing in the %0adark. %0a%0aIt is said that Tiberius Caesar, like no other human being, %0awas so endowed by Nature, that on awaking in the night** he %0acould for a few moments distinguish objects just as well as %0ain the clearest daylight, but that by degrees he would find %0ahis sight again enveloped in darkness. The late Emperor %0aAugustus had azure eyes like those of some horses, the white %0abeing larger than with other men ; he used to be verj' angry %0aif a person stared intently at them for this peculiarity. Claudius %0aCaesar had at the corners of the eyes a white fleshy substance, %0acovered with veins, which would occasionally become sufi'used %0awith blood ; with the Emperor Caius* they had a fixed, steady %0agaze, while Nero could see nothing distinctly without wink- %0aing, and having it brought close to his eyes. The Emperor %0aCaius had twenty pairs of gladiators in his training-school, %0aand of all these there were only two who did not wink the %0aeyes when a menacing gesture was made close to them : hence %0ait was that these men were invincible. So difficult a matter is %0ait for a man to keep his eyes from winking : indeed, to wink is %0aso natural to many, that they cannot desist from it ; such per- %0asons we generally look upon as the most timid. %0a%0aNo persons have the eye all of one colour ; that of the %0amiddle of the eye is always different from the white which %0asurrounds it. In all animals there is no part^in the whole %0abody that is a stronger exponent of the feelings, and in man %0amore especially, for it is from the expression of the eye that %0awe detect clemency, moderation, compassion, hatred, love, %0asadness, and joy. From the eyes, too, the various characters %0aof persons are judged of, according as they are ferocious, me- %0a%0a93 B. vii. c. 2. 9* " Caesii." %0a%0a^ The same has been said also of Cardan, the elder Scaliger, Theodore %0aBeza, the French physician Mairan, auJ tlie republican Camille Desmoulins. , %0as** Caligula. %0a%0aE 2 %0a%0a%0a%0a52 %0a%0a%0a%0aPLINr's NATUKAl HTSTOBT. %0a%0a%0a%0a[Book XI. %0a%0a%0a%0aiiacing, sparkling, sedate, leering, askance, downcast, or Ian- %0aguishing. Beyond a doubt it is in the eyes that the mind has %0aits abode : sometimes the look is ardent, sometimes fixed and %0asteady, at other times the eyes are humid, and at others, again, %0ahalf closed. From these it is that the tears of pity flow, and %0awhen we kiss them we seem to be touching the very soul. It %0ais the eyes that weep, and from them proceed those streams %0athat moisten our cheeks as they trickle down. And what is %0athis liquid that is always so ready and in such abundance in %0aour moments of grief, and where is it kept in reserve at other %0atimes ? It is by the aid of the mind that we see, by the aid %0aof the mind that we enjoy perception ; while the eyes, like so %0amany vessels, as it were, receive its visual faculties and trans- %0amit them. Hence it is that profound thought renders a man %0ablind for the time, the powers of sight being withdrawn fi'om %0aexternal objects and thrown inward : so, too, in epilepsy, the %0amind is covered with darkness, while the eyes, though open, %0aare able to see nothing. In addition to this, it is the fact %0athat hares, as well as many human beings, can sleep with %0athe eyes open, a thing which the Greeks express by the term %0azopy^avriav. Nature has composed the eye of numerous mem- %0abranes of remarkable thinness, covering them with a thick coat %0ato ensure their protection against heat and cold. This coat she %0apurifies from time to time by the lachrymal humours, and she %0ahas made the surface lubricous and slippery, to protect the eye %0aagainst the efi'ects of a sudden shock. %0a%0aCHAP. 55. THE NATUEE OF THE PUPIL EXES WHICH DO KOT %0a%0aSHUT. %0a%0aIn the midst of the cornea of the eye Nature has formed a %0awindow in the pupil, the small dimensions of which do not %0apermit the si^ht to wander at hazard and with uncertainty, %0abut direct it as straight as though it were through a tuhe, %0aand at the same time ensure its avoidance of all shocks com- %0amunicated by foreign bodies. The pupils are surrounded by a %0ablack circle in some persons, while it is of a yellowish cast with %0aothers, and azure again with others. By this happy combina- %0ation the light is received by the eye upon the white that lies %0aaround the pupU, and its reflection being thus tempered, it %0afails to impede or confuse the sight by its harshness. So %0acomplete a mirror, too, does the eye form, that the pupil, %0a%0a%0a%0aChap. 55.] %0a%0a%0a%0aTHE NATtrnE OF THE PUPIL. %0a%0a%0a%0a53 %0a%0a%0a%0asmall as it is, is able to reflect the entire image of a man. %0aThis^ is the reason why most birds, when held in the hand %0aof a person, will more particularly peck at his eyes ; for seeing %0atheir own likeness reflected in the pupils, they are attracted to %0ait by what seem to be the objects of their natural affection. %0a%0aIt is only some few beasts of burden that are subject to %0amaladies of the eyes towards the increase of the moon : but it %0ais man alone that is rescued from blindness by the discharge %0aof the humours* that have caused it. Many persons have %0ahad their sight restored after being blind for twenty years ; %0awhile others, again, have been denied this blessing from their %0avery birth, without there being any blemish in the eyes. Many %0apersons, again, have suddenly lost tneir sight from no apparent %0acause, and without any preceding injury. The most learned %0aauthors say that there are veins which communicate from the %0aeye to the brain, but I am inclined to think that the communi- %0acation is with the stomach ; for it is quite certain that a person %0anever loses the ej'e without feeling sickness at the stomach. It %0ais an important and sacred duty, of high sanction among the %0aRomans, to close the eyes of the dead, and then again to open %0athem when the body is laid on the funeral pile, the usage %0ahaving taken its rise in the notion of its being improper - that %0athe eyes of the dead should be beheld by man, Avhile it is an %0aequally great offence to hide them from the view of heaven. %0aMan is the only living creature the eyes of which are subject %0ato deformities, from which, in fact, arose the family names of %0a" Strabo"^ and " Psetus." ^ The ancients used to call a man %0awho was born with only one eye, "codes," and " ocella," a %0aperson whose eyes were remarkably small. " Luscinus" was %0athe surname given to one who happened to have lost one eye %0aby an accident. %0a%0aThe eyes of animals that see at night in the dark, cats, for %0ainstance, are shining and radiant, so much so, that it is impos- %0asible to look upon them ; those of the she-goat, too, and the %0awolf are resplendent, and emit a light like fire. The eyes of %0athe sea-calf and the hy£ena change successively to a thousand %0a%0a^ Hardouin witli justice doubts the soundness of this alleged reason. %0aHe alludes, probably, to some method of curing cataract; perhaps %0asomewhat similar to that mentioned by him in B. xx. c. 20. %0a%0aThis was done by the nearest relatives. This usage still prevails in %0athis country, the eyelids being pressed down with pieces of gold or silver. %0a^ Or "squint-eyed." 2 Or "cock-eyed," %0a%0a%0a%0a51 %0a%0a%0a%0aPLIKT's NATirEAL HISTOET. %0a%0a%0a%0a