rable reading to " ssevissime %0adentiunt." *^ Only two-forked in reality. %0a%0a^ It is not covered with hair. %0a%0a" It is not bifurcate. %0a%0aThese are horny, conical papillne, the summits of which point back- %0awards. °^ See li. ix. c. 60. %0a%0a%0a%0a62 %0a%0a%0a%0aFlint's natural history. %0a%0a%0a%0a[Book Xr. %0a%0a%0a%0athey are known as ololygones.^ This liappens at stated periods %0aof the year, at which the males invite the females for the %0apurposes of propagation : letting down the lower lip to the %0asurface of the water, they receive a small portion of it in the %0amouth, and then, by quavering with the tongue, make a gur- %0agling noise, from which the croaking is produced which we %0ahear. In making this noise, the folds of the mouth, becoming %0adistended, are quite transparent, and the eyes start from the %0ahead and burn again with the effort. Those insects which %0ahave a sting in the lower part of the body, have teeth, and a %0atongue as well ; with bees it is of considerable length, and in %0athe grasshopper it is very prominent. Those insects which have %0aa fistulous sting in the mouth, have neither tongue nor teeth ; %0awhile others, again, have a tongue in the interior of the mouth, %0athe ant, for instance. In the elephant the tongue is remark- %0aably broad ; and while with all other animals, each according %0ato -its kind, it is always perfectly at liberty, with man, and %0ahim alone, it is often found so strongly tied down by certain %0aveins, that it becomes necessary to cut them. "We find it %0astated that the pontiff Metellus had a tongue so ill adapted for %0aarticulation, that he is generally supposed to have voluntarily %0asubmitted to torture for many months, while preparing to %0apronounce the speech which he was about to make on the de- %0adication of the temple of Opifera.*" In most persons the %0atongue is able to articulate with distinctness at about the %0aseventh year ; and many know how to employ it with such re- %0a