unch, %0aand that in the stag it is situate either in the tail or the %0aintestines ; and that hence it is, that those parts are so bitter %0athat dogs will not touch them. The gall, in fact, is nothing %0aelse but the worst parts of the blood purged off, and for this %0areason it is that it is so bitter : at all events, it is a well-known %0afact, that no animal has a liver unless it has blood as well. %0aThe liver receives the blood from the heart, to which it is %0aunited, and then disperses it in the veins. %0a%0aCnAP. 75. THE PKOPEKTIES OF THE GALL. %0a%0aA^Tien the gall is black, it is productive of madness in man, %0aand if it is wholly expelled death will ensue. Hence it is, too, %0athat the word " bile" has been employed by us to characterize %0aa harsh, embittered disposition; so powerful are the effects %0aof this secretion, when it extends its influence to the mind. %0aIn addition to this, Avhen it is dispersed over the whole of %0athe body, it deprives the eyes, even, of their natural colour ; %0aand when ejected, will tarnish copper vessels even, rendering %0aeverything black with which it comes in contact ; so that no %0aone ought to be surprised that it is the gall which constitutes %0athe venom of serpents. Those o,nimals of Pontus which feed %0aon wormwood have no gall : in the raven, the quail, and the %0apheasant, the gall-bladder is united to the renal parts, and, on %0aone side only, to the intestines. In many animals, again, it %0ais united onlj' to the intestines, the pigeon, the hawk, and the %0amurena, for example. In some few birds it is situate in the %0aliver ; but it is in serpents and fishes that it is the largest in %0aproportion. AVith the greater part of birds, it extends all along %0athroughout the intestines, as in the hawk and the kite. In %0asome other birds, also, it is situate in the breast as well : the %0agall, too, of the sea-calf is celebrated for its application to many %0apurposes. From the gall of the bull a colour is e