s after, or upon the day on which it has %0amiscarried. The next best after that of a sow that has mis- %0acaiTied, is that of one that has been killed the day after far- %0arowing : indeed, the paps of this last, if the young have not %0abegun to suck, are excellent eating, while those of an animal %0athat has miscarried are very inferior. The ancients called this %0apart by the name of " abdomen," before it grew hard, and %0awere not in the habit of killing swine while in a state of %0apregnancy. %0a%0aCHAP. 85. ANIMALS WHICH HAVE STTET : ANIMALS WHICH DO NOT %0a%0aGKOW FAT. %0a%0aThose among the homed animals which have teeth in one %0a%0a2 Or bag. %0a%0a5 "The (principal) place." %0a%0a* Ajasson renders tbis passage : " The effects are fatal when this organ, %0abecoming displaced, absorbs the air." The test is probably corrupt. %0a%0a%0a%0a76 %0a%0a%0a%0aPliny's natueal histoet. %0a%0a%0a%0a[Book IX. %0a%0a%0a%0ajaw only, and pastern bones on the feet, produce tallow or %0asuet. Those, on the other hand, which are cloven-footed, or %0ahave the feet divided into toes, and are without horns, have %0asimple fat only. This fat becomes hard, and when quite %0acold turns brittle, and is always found at the extremity of the %0aflesh ; while, on the other hand, the fat which lies between the %0askin and the flesh forms a kind of liquid juice. Some animals %0anaturally do not become fat, such as the hare and the par- %0atridge, for instance. All fat animals, male as well as female, %0aare mostly barren ; and those which are remarkably fat become %0aold the soonest. All animals have a certain degree of fatness %0ain the eyes. The fat in all animals is devoid of sensation, %0ahaving neither arteries nor veins. With the greater part of %0aanimals, fatness is productive of insensibility ; so much so, %0aindeed, that it has been said, that living swine have been %0agnawed even by mice. ® It has been even asserted that the fat %0awas drawn off from the body of a son of L. Apro