e sea-calf has cartilages, and no bones. %0aThe ears also, and the nostrils in all animals, when remarkably %0aprominent, are made flexible by a remarkable provision of %0aNature, in order that they may not be broken. When cartilage %0ais once broken, it will not unite ; nor will bone, when cut, grow %0aagain, except in beasts of burden, between the hoof and the %0apastern. %0a%0aMan increases in height till his twenty-first year, after %0awhich he fills out ; bul^ it is more particularly when he first %0aarrives at the age of puberty that he seems to have untied a %0asort of knot in his existence, and this especially when he has %0abeen overtaken by illness. %0a%0aCHAP. 88. — THE NEEVE : ANIMALS WHICH HAVE NONE. %0a%0aThe nerves ^ take their rise at the heart, and even surround %0ait in the ox ; they have the same nature and principle as the %0amarrow. In all animals they are fastened to the lubricous %0asurface of the bones, and so serve to fasten those knots in the %0abody which are known as articulations or joints, sometimes %0alying between them, sometimes surrounding them, and some- %0atimes running from one to another ; in one place they are %0along and round, and in another broad, according as the ne- %0acessity of each case may demand. When cut, they will not %0a%0a* The hare and the partridge, for instance. %0a%0a' There is considerable doubt what the ancients exactly meant by tlie %0a"ncrvi ;" and wliether, in fact, they had any definite idea of " nerves," in %0aour acceptation of the word. Pliny here expresses the opinions entertained %0aby Aristotle. " Tendons," or " sinews," would almost appear to be the proper %0atranslation of the word. %0a%0a%0a%0a78 %0a%0a%0a%0aPLIirr'S NATUEAL HISTOET. %0a%0a%0a%0a[Book XI %0a%0a%0a%0areunite, and if wounded, it is wonderful what excruciating %0apain they cause ; though, if completely cut asunder, they are %0aproductive of none whatever. Some animals are destitute of %0anerves, fish, for instance, the bodies of which are united by %0aarteries, though even these are not to be found in_ the mol- %0alusks. Wherever there are nerves found, it is the inner ones %0athat contract the limb, and the outer ones that extend it. %0a%0aAmong the nerves lie concealed the arteries, which are %0aso many passages for the spirit ; and upon these float the veins, %0aas conduits for the blood. The pulsation of the arteries is %0amore especially perceptible on the surface of the limbs, and %0aafford indications of nearly every disease, being either statio- %0anary, quickened, or retarded, conformably to certain measures %0aand metrical laws, which depend on the age of the patient, and %0awhich have been described with remarkable skill by Hero- %0aphilus, who has been looked upon as a prophet in the wondrous %0aart of medicine. These indications, however, have been %0ahitherto neglected, in consequence of their remarkable subtilty %0aand minuteness, though, at the same time, it is by the observa- %0ation of the pulse, as being fast or slow, that the health of the %0abody, as regulating life, is ascertained. %0a%0aCHAP. 89. THE AETERIES; THE VEINS: ANIMALS WITHOTTr %0a%0aAETEEIES OE VlilNS. THE BLOOD AND THE SWEAT. ' %0a%0aThe arteries are destitute of sensation, for they are devoid of %0ablood. They do not, all of them, however, contain the vital %0aspirit, and when one of them has been cut, it is only that part %0aof the body that is reduced to a torpid state. Eirds have %0aneither veins nor arteries, which is the case also with serpents, %0atortoises, and lizards ; and they have but a very small propor- %0ation of blood. The veins, which are dispersed beneath the %0awhole skin in filaments of extreme thinness, terminate with %0asuch remarkable fineness, that the blood is able to penetrate no %0afurther, or, indeed, anything else, except an extremely subtle %0ahumour which oozes forth from the skin in innumerable small %0adrops, and is known to us as " sweat." The knot, and place %0aof union of the veins, is the navel. %0a%0aCHAP. 90. (38.) — ANIMALS, THE BLOOD OV WHICH COAGULATES %0aWITH THE GEEATEST EAPIDITT : OTHEE ANIMALS, THE BLOOD %0aOF WHICH DOES NOT COAGULATE. ANIMALS WHICH HAVE THE %0a%0a%0a%0aChap. 91.] %0a%0a%0a%0aANIMALS SOMETIMES WITHOUT BLOOD. %0a%0a%0a%0a79 %0a%0a%0a%0aTHICKEST BLOOD : THOSE THE BLOOD OP WHICH IS THE THIN- %0aNEST : ANIMALS WHICH HAVE NO BLOOD. %0a%0aThose animals in whicti the blood is more abundant and of %0aan unctuous nature, are irascible ; it is darker in males than %0ain females, and in the young than in the aged : the blood of the %0alower extremities is the thickest. There is great vitality, too, %0ain the blood, and when it is discharged from the body, it %0acarries the life with it : it is not sensible, however, of touch. %0aThose animals in which the blood is the thickest are the most %0acourageous, and those in which it is the thinnest the most %0aintelligent; while those, again, which have little or no blood are %0athe most timorous of all. The blood of the bull coagulates and %0ahardens the most sjjeedily of all, and hence it is so particu- %0alarly deadly when drunk. On the other hand, the blood of %0athe wild boar, the stag, the roe-buck, and oxen of all kinds, %0adoes not coagulate. Blood is of the richest quality in the ass, %0aand the poorest in man. Those animals which have more than %0afour feet have no blood. In animals which are very fat, the %0ablood is less abundant than in others, being soaked up by the %0afat. Man is the only creature from which the blood flows at %0athe nostrils ; some persons bleed at one nostril only, some at %0aboth, while others again void blood by the lower " parts. %0aMany persons discharge blood from the mouth at stated periods, %0asuch, for instance, as Macrinus Viscus, lately, a man of prae- %0atorian dignity, and Volusius Saturninus,'- the Prefect of the %0aCity, who every year did the same, and yet lived to beyond %0aninety. The blood is the only substance in the body that is %0asensible of any temporary increase, for a larger quantity will %0acome from the victims if they happen to have drunk just %0abefore tliey arc sacrificed. %0a%0aCHAP. 91. ANIMALS WHICH ARE WITHOUT BLOOD AT CEKTAIN %0a%0aPEKIODS Oli" THE YEAR. %0a%0aThose animals which conceal themselves'^ at certain periods %0aof the year, as already mentioned, have no blood at those times, %0awith the exception, indeed, of some very small drops about the %0a%0aSee B. xxviii. c. 41. %0a" 111 allusion, probably, to hgemorilioids, or piles. %0a1^ See B. vii. c. I'i. ^■^ Bears, dormice, serpents, &c. %0a%0a%0a%0a80 %0a%0a%0a%0aflint's NATtTEAL HISTOET. %0a%0a%0a%0a[Book XI, %0a%0a%0a%0aheart. A marvellous dispensation of Nature ! and very similar %0ato that witnessed in man, where the blood is sensible of various %0amodifications from the slightest causes ; for not only, similarly %0ato the bile, does it rush upwards to the face, but it serves also %0ato indicate the various tendencies of the mind, by depicting %0ashame, anger, and fear, in many ways, either by the paleness %0aof the features or their unusual redness ; as, in fact, the red- %0aness of anger and the blush of modesty are quite different %0athings. It is a well-known fact, that when a man is in fear, %0athe blood takes to flight and disappears, and that many per- %0asons have been pierced through the body without losing one %0adrop of blood ; a thing, however, which is only the case with %0aman. But as to those animals which we have already men- %0ationed as changing'* colour, they derive that colour from the %0areflection'^ of other objects ; while, on the other hand, man is %0athe only one that has the elements which cause these changes %0acentred in himself. All diseases, as well as death, tend to %0aabsorb the blood. %0a%0aOHAP. 92. (39.) — WHETHER THE BLOOD IS THE PEINOIPLE OP %0a%0aLIFE. %0a%0aThere are some persons who are of opinion that the fineness %0aof the wit does not depend upon the thinness of the blood, but %0athat animals are more or less stupid in proportion to the skin %0aor other coverings of the body, as the oyster and the tortoise, %0afor instance : that the hide of the ox and the bristles of the hog, %0ain fact, ofler a resistance to the fine and penetrating powers of %0athe air, and leave no passage for its transmission in a pure %0aand liquid state. The same, they say, is the case, too, with %0amen, when the skin is very thick or callous, and so excludes %0athe air. Just as if, indeed, the crocodile was not equally re- %0amarkable for the hardness of its skin and its extreme cunning. %0a%0aCHAP. 93. THE HIDE OF ANIMALS. %0a%0aThe hide, too, of the hippopotamus is so thick, that lances," %0aeven, are turned from it, and yet this animal has the intelligence %0ato administer certain medicaments to itself. The hide, too, of %0a%0aThe polypus and the chameleon. %0aSee B. viii. cc. 51, 52. %0a16 Walking-sticks are still made of it. %0a%0a%0a%0aChap. 94.] %0a%0a%0a%0aTUE IIAiE; ETC. %0a%0a%0a%0a81 %0a%0a%0a%0athe elephant makes bucklers that are quite impenetrable, and %0ayet to it is ascribed a degree of intelligence superior to that of %0aany quadruped. The skin itself is entirely devoid of sen- %0asation, and more particularly that of the head ; wherever it %0ais found alone, and unaccompanied with flesh, if wounded, it %0awill not unite, as in the cheek and on the eyelid,'* for %0ainstance. %0a%0aCHAP. 94. THE HAIR AND THE COVERING OF THE SKIN. %0a%0aThose animals which are viviparous, have hair ; those which %0aare oviparous, have feathers, scales, or a shell, like the tor- %0atoise ; or else a purple skin, like the serpent. The lower part %0aof all feathers is hollow : if cut, they will not grow again, but if %0apulled out, they will shoot afresh. Insects fly by the aid of a %0afrail membrane ; the wings of the fish'" called the "swallow" are %0amoistened in the sea, while those of the bat which frequents %0aour houses are dry ; the wings of this last animal have certain %0aarticulations as well. The hairs that issue from a thick skin %0aare rough, while those on females are of a finer quality. Those %0afound on the horse's mane are more abundant, which is the %0acase also with the shoulders of the lion. The dasypus has %0ahair in the inside of the mouth even and under the feet, two %0afeatures Avhich Trogus has also attributed to the hare ; from %0aAvhich the same author concludes that hairy men are the most %0aprone to lust. The most hairy of all animals is the hare. %0aMan is the only creature that has hair as the mark of puberty ; %0aand a person who is devoid of this, whether male or female, %0ais sure to be sterile. The hair of man is partly born with %0ahim, and in part produced after his birth. The last kind of hair %0awill not grow upon eunuchs, though that which has been born %0awith thera does not fall ofl"; Avhich is the case also with %0awomen, in a great degree. Still however, there have been %0awomen known to be afflicted Avith falling off' of the hair, just %0aas some are to be seen with a fine down on the face, after the %0acessation of the menstrual discharge. In some men the hair %0athat mostly shoots forth after birth will not grow spontane- %0aously. The hair of quadrupeds comes off every year, and %0a%0a'■^ As ah-cadv mentioned, this is not the fact. %0a" See B. ix. c. 43. %0a%0aVOL. 111. O %0a%0a%0a%0a82 %0a%0a%0a%0aFlint's natur^ll uistort. %0a%0a%0a%0a[Book XI. %0a%0a%0a%0agrows again. That of the head in man grows the fastest, and %0anext to it the hair of the beard. When cut, the hairs shoot, %0anot from the place Avhere they have been cut, as is the case %0awith grass, but at the root. The hair grows quickly in cer- %0atain diseases, phthisis more particularly ; it grows also with %0arapidity in old age, and on the body after death. In persons %0aof a libidinous tendency the hair that is produced at birth falls %0aoff more speedily, while that which is afterwards produced %0agrows with the greatest rapidity. In quadrupeds, the hair %0agrows thicker in old age ; but on those with wool, it becomes %0athinner. Those quadrupeds which have thick hair on the %0aback, have the belly quite smooth. From the hides of oxen, %0aand that of the bull more especially, glue is extracted by %0aboiling. %0a%0aCHAP. 95. THE PAPS : BIRDS THAT HAVE PAPS. EEMABKABLK %0a%0aFACTS CONNECTED WITH THE DUGS OF ANIMALS. %0a%0aMan is the only male among animals that has nipples, all %0athe rest having mere marks only in place of them. Among %0afemale animals even, the only ones that have mammae on the %0abreast are those which can nurture their young, l^o oviparous %0aanimal has mammae, and those only have milk that are vivi- %0aparous ; the bat being the only winged animal that has it. As %0afor the stories that they tell, about the screech-owl ejecting milk %0afrom its teats upon the lips of infants, I look upon it as utterly %0afabulous : from ancient times the name " strix,"^° I am aware, %0ahas been employed in maledictions, but I do not think it is %0awell ascertained what bird is really meant by that name. %0a%0a(40.) The female ass is troubled with pains in the teats %0aafter it has foaled, and it is for that reason that at the end of %0asix months it weans its young ; while the mare suckles its %0ayoung for nearly the whole year. The solid-hoofed animals %0ado not bear more than two young ones at a time : they all of %0athem have two paps, and nowhere but between the iiind legs. %0aAnimals with cloven feet and with horns, such as the cow, for %0ainstance, have four paps, similarly situate, sheep and goats two. %0a%0a20 It is not improbable that, under this name, some kind of large vam- %0apire bat was meant ; but, as Pliny says, it is impossible to arrive at any %0acertain knowledge on the subject. 'I'he best account given of the strix is %0athat in Ovid's Fasti, B. vi. The name was given opprobiously to supposed %0awitches, the "foul and midnight hags" of Shakspeare. %0a%0a%0a%0aChap. 96.] %0a%0a%0a%0aTHE MILK. %0a%0a%0a%0a83 %0a%0a%0a%0aTh ose which, produce a more nunierous progeny, and those %0awhich have toes on the feet, have a greater number of paps dis- %0atributed in a double row all along the belly, such as the %0asow, for instance ; the better sorts have twelve, the more %0acommon ones two less : the same is the case also with tlie %0afemale of the dog. Other animals, again, have four paps situate %0ain the middle of the belly, as the female panther; others, again, %0atwo only, as the lioness. The female elephant has two only, %0asituate between the shoulders, and those not in the breast, but %0awithout it, and hidden in the arm-pits : none of the animals %0awhich have toes have the paps between the hind legs. The sow %0apresents the first teat to the first-born in each farrow, the first %0ateat being the one that is situate nearest to the throat. Each %0apig, too, knows its own teat, according to the order in which %0ait was born, and drawls its nourishment from that and no other : %0aif its own suckling, too, should happen to be withdrawn from %0aany one of them, the pap will immediately dry up, and shrink %0aback within the belly : if there should be only one pig left %0aof all the farrow, that pap alone which has been assigned for %0aits nutriment Avhen born, will continue to hang down for the %0apurpose of giving suck. The she-bear has four mammte, the %0adolphin only two, at the bottom of the belly ; they are not %0aeasily visible, and have a somewhat oblique direction : this is %0athe only animal which gives suck while in motion. The baleena %0aand sea-calf also suckle their young by teats. %0a%0aCHAP. 96. (41.) — THE MILK : THE BIKSTINGS. CHEESE ; OF WHAT %0aMILK CHEESE CANNOT BE MADE. UENNET ; THE VAKXOUS KINDS %0aOF ALIMENT IN MILK. %0a%0aThe milk that is secreted in a woman before her seventh %0amonth is useless ; but after that month, so long as the foetus %0ais healthy, the milk is wholesome : many women, indeed, %0aare so full of milk, that it will flow not only from the mammfe, %0abut exudes at the arm-pits even.^^ Camels continue in milk %0auntil they are pregnant again. Their milk, mixed in the pro- %0aportion of one part to three of water, is considered a very %0apleasant beverage. The cow has no milk before it has calved, %0aand that which immediately follows upon its bringing forth is %0aknown as the " colostra : " " if water is not mixed with it, it will %0a%0aTliis assertion is borrowed from Aristotle, Hist. Anim. B. yii. e. 14. %0a^ Or bicstings. %0a%0aG 2 %0a%0a%0a%0a84 %0a%0a%0a%0aPLIXY'S NATUB^Ui JIISTOUT. %0a%0a%0a%0a[Book XI. %0a%0a%0a%0acoagulate, and assume the hardness of pumice. She-asses, as %0asoon as they are pregnant, have milk in their udders ; when %0athe pastm-age is rich, it is fatal to their young to taste the %0amother's milk the first two days after birth ; the kind of %0amalady by which they are attacked is known by the name %0aof " colostration." Cheese cannot be made from the milk of %0aanimals which have teeth on either jaw, from the circumstance %0athat their milk does not coagulate. The thinnest milk of all %0ais that of the camel, and next to it that of the mare. The milk %0aof the she-ass is the richest of all, so much so, indeed, that it is %0aoften used instead of rennet. Asses' milk is also thought to %0abe very efficacious in whitening the skin of females : at all %0aevents, Poppaea,^^ the wife of Domitius Nero, used always to %0ahave with her five hundred asses with foal, and used to bathe %0athe whole of her body in their milk, thinking that it also con- %0aferred additional suppleness on the skin. All milk thickens %0aby the action of fire, and becomes serous when exposed to cold. %0aThe milk of the cow produces more cheese than that of the %0agoat : when equal in quantity, it will produce nearly twice the %0aweight. The milk of animals which have more than four %0amammte does not produce cheese ; and that is the best