ANIMALS. %0a%0aOf all the terrestrial animals, man is the only biped : he is %0aalso the only one that has a throat, and shoulders, or " hu- %0ameri," parts in other animals known by the name of " armi." %0aMan, too, is the only animal that has the " ulna," or elbow. %0aThose animals which are provided with hands, have flesh %0aonly on the interior of them,- the cater part consisting of sinews %0aand skin. %0a%0aCHAP. 99. THE FINGEES, THE AEMS. %0a%0aSome persons have six fingers on the hands. "We read that %0aC. Horatius, a man of patrician rank, had two daughters, who %0afor this reason had the name of " Sedigitaj and we find %0amention made of Volcatius Sedigitus,^* as a famous poet. %0aThe fingers of man have three joints, the thumb only two, %0ait bending in an opposite direction to all the other fingers. %0aViewed by itself, the movement of the thumb has a sidelong %0adirection, and it is much thicker than the rest of the fingers. %0aThe little finger is equal in length to the thumb, and two others %0aare also equal in length, the middle finger being the longest %0aof all. Those quadrupeds which live by rapine have five toes %0aon the fore feet, and four on the hinder ones. The lion, the %0awolf, and the dog, with some few others, have five claws %0aon the hind feet, one of which hangs down near the joint of the %0aleg. The other animals, also, which are of smaller size, have %0afive toes. The two arms are not always equal in length : it %0ais a well-known fact, that, in the school of gladiators belong- %0aing to Caius Cassar,^* the Thracian Studiosus had the right %0aarm longer than the left. Some animals also use their fore- %0apaws to perform the duties of hands, and employ them in %0aconveying food to the mouth as they sit, the squirrel, for in- %0astance. %0a%0aCHAP. 100. (44.) EESEMBLANCE OF THE APE TO MAN. %0a%0aAs to the various kinds of apes, they ofier a perfect resem- %0a%0aHe wrote a poem, in which the principal Latin (Iramatists are enume- %0arated, in the order of merit. A. Gellius, B. xt. c. 24, has preserved a por- %0ation of it. %0a25 Germanicus. %0a%0a%0a%0aChap. 102.] THE KNEES AND THE HAMS. %0a%0a%0a%0a87 %0a%0a%0a%0ay)lancc to man in the face, the nostrils, the ears, and the eye- %0alids ; being the onl)' quadrupeds, in fact, that have eyehishes on %0athe lower eyelid. They have mammee also on the breast, arms %0aand legs, which bend in opposite directions, and nails upon %0athe hands and fingers, the middle finger being the longest. %0aThey differ somewhat from man in the feet ; which, like the %0ahands, are of remarkable length, and have a print similar to %0athat of the palm of our hand. They have a thumb also, and %0aarticulations similar to those in man. The males differ from %0aman in the sexual parts only, while all the internal viscera %0aexactly resemble those of man. %0a%0aCHAP. 101. (45.) THE NAILS. %0a%0aIt is generally supposed that the nails are the terminations %0aof the sinews. All animals whicli have fingers luive nails us %0awell. In the ape they are long and overlapping,^'* like a tile, %0awhile in man they are broad : they will grow even after death. %0aIn the beasts of prey they are hooked, Avhile in others, such %0aas the dog, for instance, they are straight, with the exception, %0aindeed, of the one which is attached to the leg in most of %0athem. All the animals which have feet [and not hoots], have; %0atoes as well, except the elephant ; he, also, wouhl appear to %0ahave toes, five in number, but rudely developed, undivided, %0aand hardly distinct from one another, bearing a nearer resem- %0ablance, in fact, to hoofs than to claws. In the elephant the %0afore-feet are the largest, and in the hind-feet there are sliort %0ajoints. This animal is able, also, to bend the hams inward %0alike a man, while in all the others the joints of the hinder %0alegs bend in a contrary direction to those of the fore ones. %0aThose animals which are viviparous bend the fore-leg forward, %0awhile the joint of the hind-leg is directed backward, %0a%0aCHAP. 102.^ — THE KNEE^ AND THE HAMS. %0a%0aIn man the knee and the elbow bend contrary ways ; tho %0asame is the case, too, with the bear and the ape, and it is for %0athis reason that they are not so swift of foot as other ani- %0amals. Those quadrupeds which are oviparous, such as the %0acrocodile and the lizard, bend the knee of the fore-leg back- %0as'' This seems to be the meaning of " imbricatus." %0a%0a%0a%0aPLtNi' S NAIU'RAL IllSIOIiV. %0a%0a%0a%0a[liuuk XI. %0a%0a%0a%0av.-avds, and that of the hind-L^g forwards ; their thighs art- %0aplaced on them obliquely, in a similar manner to a man's %0athumb; which is the case idso with the multipede insects, the %0aliind-legs only excepted of such as leap. Birds, like quadru- %0apeds, have the joints of the wings bending forwards, but tlioso %0aof the legs backwards. %0a%0aCHAP. 103. PARTS OF TnK HtniAN BODY TO WUICri CEItTAIX %0a%0aKELIGIOUS IDEAS ARE ATTACHED. %0a%0aIn accordance with the usages of various nations, certain %0areligious ideas have been attached to the knees. It is thu %0aknees that suppliants clasp, and it is to these that they extend %0atheir hands ; it is the knees that they worship like so many %0aaltars, as it were ; perhaps, because in them is centred the %0avital strength. For in the joint of eitlier knee, the right %0aas well as the left, there is on the fore-side of each a certain %0aempty space, which bears a strong resemblance to a mouth, and %0athrough which, like the throat, if it is once pierced, the vital %0apowers escape.^'' There are also certain religious ideas at- %0atached to other parts of che body, as is testified in raising tlie %0ahack of the right hand to the lips, and extending it as a token %0aof good faith. It was the custom of the ancient Greeks, when %0ain the act of supplication, to touch the chin. The seat of the %0amemorj' lies in the lower part of the ear, which we touch %0awhen we summon a witness to depose upon memory to an %0aarrest.''® The seat, too, of Xemesis^" lies behind the right ear, a %0agoddess which has never yet found a Latin name, no, not in tlio %0aCapitol even. It is to this part that we apply the finger next %0athe little finger, after touching the mouth with it, Avhen we %0asilently ask pardon of the gods for having let slip an indiscreet %0aword. %0a%0aCHAP. 104. VARICOSE VEINS. %0a%0ailen only, in general, have varicose veins in the legs, wo- %0amen but very rarely. "We are informed by Oppius, that %0a%0a3'' Though wounds in the knee are highly dangerous, death does not ««- %0aeessarily ensue. %0a%0a"'8 Of another person, who had thus forfeited his bail. It was the cus- %0atom to touch the car of the attesting witness. %0a%0aS3 The god(iess of retribution. See R. xxviii. c. o, where he makes fur- %0ather mention of her statue in the Capitol, %0a%0a%0a%0aChap. 106.]. %0a%0a%0a%0aHOOFS. %0a%0a%0a%0a89 %0a%0a%0a%0aC. ifarius, who was seven times consul, was the only man ever %0aknown to be able to have them extracted in a standing- po- %0asition. %0a%0aCHAP. 105. THE GAIT, THE FEET, THE LEGS. %0a%0aAll animals take a right-hand direction when they first %0abegin to walk, and lie down on the left side. While the other %0aanimals walk just as it may happen, the lion only and the %0acamel walk foot by foot, or in such a way that the left foot %0anever passes the right, but always comes behind it. Men have %0athe largest feet ; in every kind of animal the female has the %0asmallest. Man only" has calves, and flesh upon the legs : we %0afind it stated by authors, however, that there was once an %0aEgyptian who had no calves on his legs. All men, too, with %0asome few exceptions, have a sole to the foot. It is from these %0aexceptional cases that persons have obtained the names of %0aPlancus,'" Plautus, Punsa, and Scaurus ; just as, from the mal- %0aformation of the legs, we find persons called Varus,^^ Vacia, and %0aVatinius, all which blemishes are to be seen in quadrupeds %0aalso. Animals which have no horns have a solid hoof, from %0awhich circumstance it is used by them as a weapon of off'ence, %0ain place of horns ; such animals as these are also des- %0atitute of pastern bones, but those which have cloven hoofs %0ahave them ; w'hile those, again, which have toes have none, %0anor are they ever found iu the fore-feet of animals. The %0acamel has pastern bones like those of the ox, but somewhat %0asmaller, the feet being cloven, with a slight line of division, %0aand having a fleshy sole, like that of the bear : hence it is, %0athat in a long journey, the animal becomes fatigued, and the %0afoot cracks, if it is not shod. %0a%0aCHAP. lOG, (46.) HOOFS. %0a%0aThe horn of the hoof grows again in no animals except %0abeasts of burden. The swine in some places in lUyricum %0ahave solid hoofs. Nearly all the horned animals are cloven- %0afooted, no animal having solid hoofs and two horns. The %0aIndian ass is only a one-horned animal, and the oryx is both %0a%0aThe frog is, in some measure, an exception. %0a%0aOr "flat-foot," "splay-foot," "large-foot," and "club-footed." %0a%0aWords meaning " kuock-kneed," "bow-legged," and "wry-legged." %0a%0a%0a%0a90 %0a%0a%0a%0aPLlXl's KATDEAL niiSTOKY. %0a%0a%0a%0a[15ook XI. %0a%0a%0a%0aone-horned and cloven-footed. The Indian ass^' is the %0aonly solid-hoofed animal that has pastern-bones. As to %0aswine, they are looked upon as a sort of mongrel race, with a %0amixture of both kinds, and hence it is that their ankle-bones %0aare so misshapen. Those authors who have imagined that %0aman has similar pastern-bones, are easily to be confuted. The %0aIj-nx is the only one among the animals that have the feet %0adivided into toes, that has anything bearing a resemblance %0ato a pastern-bone ; while with the lion it is more crooked %0astill. The great pastern-bone is straight, and situate in the %0ajoints of the foot; it projects outwards in a convex protube- %0arance, and is held fast in its vertebration by certain liga- %0aments. %0a%0aCHAP. 107. (47.) THE FEET OF BIEDS. %0a%0aAmong birds, some have the feet divided into toes, while %0aothers, again, are broad and flatfooted — in others, which par- %0atake of the intermediate nature of both, the toes are divided, %0awith a wide space between them. All birds, however, have %0afour toes — three in front, and one on the heel ; this last, how- %0aever, is wanting in some that have long legs. The iynx*' is %0athe only bird that has two toes on each side of the leg. This %0abird also protrudes a long tongue similar to that of the serpent, %0aand it can turn the neck quite round and look backwards ; if %0ahas great talons, too, like those of the jackdaw. Some of the %0aheavier birds have spurs also upon the legs; but none of %0athose have them which have crooked talons as well. The %0along-footed birds, as they fly, extend the legs towards the tail, %0awhile those that have short legs hold them contracted close to %0athe middle of the body. Those authors who deny that there %0ais any bird without feet, assert that those even which are %0acalled apodes,^* are not without them, as also the oce, and the %0adrepanis,** which last is a bird but very rarely seen. Ser- %0apents, too, have been seen with feet like those of the goose. %0a%0aThe rhinoceros. %0a" Or wryneck. « See B. x. c. 5. %0a%0aSupposed to be the Hirundo apiisof Linnaeus. Of the "oce" nothing %0ais known ; indeed, ths reading is very doubtful. %0a%0a%0a%0aChap. 100.] %0a%0a%0a%0aTHE SEXUAL PAKTS. %0a%0a%0a%0a91 %0a%0a%0a%0aCHAP. 108. (48.) THE FEET OF ANIMALS, FROM TTirSE HATING %0a%0aTWO FEET TO THOSE WITH A HUNDUED. DWAHFi. %0a%0aAmong insects, those which have hard eyes have the fore- %0afeet long, in order that from time to time they may rub the %0aeyes with their feet, as we frequently see done by flies. The %0ainsects which have long hind-feet are able to leap, the locust, %0afor instance. All these insects have six feet : and some of the %0aspiders have two very long feet in addition. They have, all %0aof them, three joints. We have already" stated that marine %0ainsects have eight feet, such as the polypus, the ssepia, the %0acuttle-fish, and the crab, animals which move their arms in a %0acontrary direction to their feet, which last they move around %0aas well as obliquely : they are the only animals the feet of %0awhich have a rounded form. Other insects have two feet to %0aregulate their movements ; in the crab, and in that only, these %0aduties are performed by four. The land animals which exceed %0athis number of feet, as most of the worms,*® never have fewer %0athan twelve feet, and some, indeed, as many as a hundred. %0aThe number of feet is never uneven in any animal. Among %0athe solid-hoofed animals, the legs are of their proper length %0afrom the moment of their birth, after which they may with %0amore propriety be said to extend themselves than to increase %0ain growth : hence it is, that in infancy they are able to scratch %0atheir ears with the hind feet, a thing which, when they grow %0aolder, they are not able to do, because their increase of growth %0aaffects only the superficies of the body. It is for the same %0areason also, that they are only able to graze at first by bending %0athe knees, until such time as the neck has attained its proper %0alength. %0a%0a(49.) There are dwarfs to be found among all animals, and %0aamong birds even. %0a%0aCHAP. 109. THE SEXTTAL PARTS. HERMAPHRODITES. %0a%0a"We have already spoken sufficiently** at length of those ani- %0amals, the males of which have the sexual parts behind. In %0athe wolf, the fox, the weasel, and the ferret, these parts are %0abony ; and it is the genitals of the last-mentioned animal %0a%0aB. ix. c. 44. %0a%0a*8 He evidently means insects of the centipede class. See B. xxix. c. 39. %0a" B. X. c. 83. %0a%0a%0a%0a92 %0a%0a%0a%0apltkt's nattthal nisxonT. %0a%0a%0a%0a[Book XI. %0a%0a%0a%0athat supply the principal remedies for calciilus in the human %0abladder. It is said also that the genitals of the bear are %0aturned into a hornT substance the moment it dies. Among %0athe peoples of the East the very best bow-strings are those %0awhich are made of the member of the camel. These parts also, %0aamong different nations, are made the object of certain usages'" %0aand religious observances ; and the Galli/^ the priests of the %0aMother of the gods, are in the habit of castrating themselves, %0awithout any dangerous results. On the other hand, there is %0ain some few w^omen a monstrous resemblance to the male con- %0aformation, while hermaphrodites appear to partake of the %0anature of both. Instances of this last conformation were %0aseen in quadrupeds in Nero's reign, and for the first time, I %0aimagine ; for he ostentatiously paraded hermaphrodite horses %0ayoked to his car, which had been found in the territory of %0athe Treviri, in Gaul ; as if, indeed, it was so remarkably fine a %0asight to behold the ruler of the earth seated in a chariot dra^^-n %0aby monstrosities ! %0a%0aCHAP. 110. — rnE TESTES — THE THKEE CLASSES OP EUNUCHS. %0a%0aIn sheep and cattle the testes hang down to the legs, while %0ain the boar they are knit up close to the body. In the dolphin %0athey are very long, and are concealed in the lower part of the %0abelly. In the elephant, also, they are quite concealed. In %0aoviparous animals they adhere to the interior of the loins: %0athese animals are the most speedy in the venereal congress. %0aFishes and serpents have no testes, but in place of them they %0ahave two-veins, which run from the renal region to the genitals. %0aThe bird known as the " buteo,"*^ has three testes. Man is %0athe only creature in which the testes are ever broken, either %0aaccidentally or by some natural malady ; those -who are thus %0aafflicted form a third class of half men, in addition to her- %0amaphrodites and eunuchs. In all species of animals the male %0ais more courageous than the female, with the exception of the %0apanther and the bear. %0a%0aCHAP. 111. (50.) THE TAILS OP ANIMALS. %0a%0aNearly all the animals, both viviparous as well as oviparous, %0a%0a5" Such as circumcision among the Jews. %0a51 See B. XXXV. c. 46. %0a%0a" Probably the buzzard; from this story also called the "triorchis." %0a%0a%0a%0aChap. 112.] DIFFEEEKT VOICES OF ANIMALS. %0a%0a%0a%0a93 %0a%0a%0a%0awith the exception of man and the ape, have tails in propor- %0ation to the necessities of the body. In animals with bristles %0athe tail is bare, as in the boar, for instance. In those that are %0ashaggy, it is small, such as the bear ; while in those animals %0athat have long hair, the tail is long also, the horse, for in- %0astance. The tail of a lizard or serpent, if cut off, wall grow %0aagain. The tail governs the movements of the fish like a %0arudder, and turning from side to side, to the right or to the %0aleft, impels it onwards, acting in some degree like an oar. %0aA double tail is sometimes found in lizards. In oxen, the %0astalk of the tail is of remarkable length, and is covered with %0arough hair at the extremitj-. In the ass, too, it is longer than %0ain the horse, but in beasts of burden it is covered with bristly %0ahairs. The tail of the lion, at the extremity, is like that of %0athe ox and the field-mouse ; but this is not the case with the %0apanther. In the fox and the wolf it is covered with long %0aluiir, as in sheep, in w^hich it is longer also. In swine, the %0atail is curled ; among dogs, those that are mongrels carry it %0aclose beneath the belly. %0a%0aCHAP. 112. (51.) — THE DIFFERENT VOICES OF ANIMALS. %0a%0aAristotle^- is of opinion that no animal has a voice which %0adoes not respire, and that hence it is that there is no voice in %0ainsects, but only a noise, through the circulation of the air in %0athe interior, and its resounding, by reason of its compression. %0a8ome insects, again, he says, emit a sort of humming noise, %0asuch as the bee, for instance ; others a shrill, long-drawn note, %0alike the grasshopper, the two cavities beneath the thorax re- %0aceiving the air, which, meeting a moveable membrane within, %0aemits a sound by the attrition. — Also that flies, bees, and %0aother insects of that nature, are only heard while they are %0aflying, and cease to be heard the moment they settle, and that %0athe sound which they emit proceeds from the friction and the %0aair within them, and not from any act of respiration. At all %0aevents, it is generally believed that the locust emits a sound %0aby rubbing together the wdngs and thighs, and that among %0athe aquatic animals the scallop makes a certain noise as it %0aflies.** Mollusks, however, and the testaceous animals have no %0avoice and emit no sounds. As for the other fishes, although %0a%0a%0a%0a" Hist. Anim. B. iv. c. 9. %0a%0a%0a%0a53 See B. ix. c. 52. %0a%0a%0a%0a94 %0a%0a%0a%0apliny's natural history. %0a%0a%0a%0aBook XI %0a%0a%0a%0athey are destitute of lungs and the tracheal artery, they are %0anot entirely without the power of emitting certain sounds : it %0ais only a mere joke to say that the noise which they makeij %0aproduced by grating their teeth together. The tish, too, that %0ais found in the river Acheloiis, and is known as the boar-fish," %0amakes a grunting noise, as do some others which we have pre- %0aviously** mentioned. The oviparous animals hiss: in the %0aserpent this hissing is prolonged, in the tortoise it is short and %0aabrupt. Frogs make a peculiar noise of their own, as already %0astated;^ unless, indeed, this, too, is to be looked upon as a %0amatter of doubt ; but their noise originates in the mouth, and %0anot in the thorax. Still, however, in reference to this subject, %0athe nature of the various localities exercises a very considerable %0ainfluence, for in Macedonia, it is said, the frogs are dumb, and %0athe same in reference to the wild boars there. Among birds, %0athe smaller ones chirp and twitter the most, and more espe- %0acially about the time of pairing. Others, again, exercise their %0avoice while figliting, the quail, for instance ; others before %0athey begin to fight, such as the partridge ; and others M'hen %0athey have gained the victory, the dunghill cock, for instance, %0aThe males in these species have a peculiar note of their own, %0awhile in others, the nightingale for example, the male has %0athe same note as the female. %0a%0aSome birds sing all the year round, others only at certain %0atimes of the year, as we have already mentioned when speak- %0aing of them individually. The elephant produces a noise %0asimilar to that of sneezing, by the aid of the mouth, and in- %0adependently of the nostrils ; but by means of the nostrils it %0aemits a sound similar to the hoarse braying of a trumpet %0aIt is only in the bovine race that the voice of the female is the %0adeepest, it being in all other kinds of animals more shrill than %0athat of the male ; it is the same also with the male of the %0ahuman race when castrated. The infant at its birth is never %0aheard to utter a cry before it has entirely left the uterus: %0ait begins to speak at the end of the first year. A son of %0aCroesus," however, spoke when only six months old, and, while %0ayet wielding the child's rattle, afforded portentous omens, for %0a%0a5* "Aper." 65 B. ix. c. 7. %0a%0a6s See c. 65 of the present Book. %0a%0a*' Not the diimh son mentioned by Herodotus, who saved his father's %0alife at the taking of Sardes. %0a%0a%0a%0aChap. 113.] %0a%0a%0a%0aSUPEKFI.UOUS LIMBS. %0a%0a%0a%0a95 %0a%0a%0a%0ait was at the same period that his father's empire fell. Those %0achildren which begin to speak the soonest, begin to walk the %0alatest. The human voice acquires additional strength at the %0afourteenth year ; but in old age it becomes more shrill again, %0aand there is no living creature in which it is subject to more %0afrequent changes. %0a%0aIn addition to the preceding, there are still some singular %0acircumstances that deserve to be mentioned with reference to %0athe voice. If saw-dust or sand is thrown down in the orches- %0atra of a theatre, or if the walls around are left in a rough %0astate, or empty casks are placed there, the voice is absorbed ; %0awhile, on the other hand, if the wall is quite straight, or if %0abuilt in a concave fonn, tlie voice will move along it, and will %0aconvey words spoken in the slightest whisper from one %0aend*^ to the other, if there is no inequality in the surface to %0aimpede its progress. The voice, in man, contributes in a great %0adegree to form his physiognomy, for we form a knowledge of %0aa man before we see him by hearing his voice, just as well^ %0aas if we had seen him with our eyes. There are as many %0akinds of voices, too, as there are individuals in existence, and %0aeach man has his own peculiar voice, just as much as his own %0apeculiar physiognomy. Hence it is, that arises that vast di- %0aversity of nations and languages throughout the whole earth : %0ain this, too, originate the many tunes, measures, and inflexions %0athat exist. But, before all other things, it is the voice that %0aserves to express our sentiments,'^" a power that distinguishes %0aus from the beasts ; just as, in the same way, the various shades %0aand differences in language that exist among men have created %0aan equally marked difference between us and the brutes. %0a%0aCHAP. 113. (52.) SUPEKFLTJOUS LIMBS. %0a%0aSupernumerary limbs, when they grow on animals, are of %0ano use, Avhich is the case also with the sixth finger, when it %0agrows on man. It was thought proper in Egypt to rear a %0ahuman monster, that had two additional eyes in the back part %0aof the head ; it could not see with them, however. %0a%0a^8 Like the whispering: gallery of St. Paul's Cathedral. %0a" " Non aliter quani ociilis." On this, few will be found to agree with %0aPliny. %0a%0a* ' And not to " conceal " them, according to the opinion of some modern %0apoliticians. %0a%0a%0a%0aPLTXr'S KATUHAL UISTOUT. %0a%0a%0a%0a[Book XI, %0a%0a%0a%0aCHAP. 114. — SIGNS OF TITALIXy AND OF THE MORAL %0a%0aDISrOSITlON OF M.AN, FllOM THK LIMBS. %0a• %0a%0aI am greatly surprised that Aristotle has not only believed, %0abut has even committed it to writing, that there are in the %0ahuman body certain prognostics of the duration of life. Al- %0athough I am quite convinced of the utter futility of these re- %0amarks, and am of opinion that they ouglit not to he published %0a-without hesitation, for fear lest each person might be anxiouslj' %0alooking out for these prognostics in his own person, I shall still %0amake some slight mention of the subject, seeing that so learned %0aa man as Aristotle did not treat it with contempt. He has set %0adown the following as indications of a short life — few teeth, %0avery long fingers, a leaden colour, and numerous broken lines %0ain the palm of the hand. On the other hand, he looks upon the %0afollowing as prognostics of a long life — stooping in the shoul- %0aders, one or two long unbroken lines in the hand, a greater num- %0aber than two-and-thirtj' teeth, and large ears . He does not, I %0aimagine, require that all these sj^mptoms should unite in one %0aperson, but looks upon them as individuallj^ significant : in my %0aopinion, however, they are utterlj^ frivolous, all of them, al- %0athough they obtain currency among the vulgar. Our own writer, %0aTrogus, has in a similar manner set down the physiognomy as %0aindicative of the moral disposition ; one of the very gravest of %0athe Roman authors, whose own*" words I will here subjoin:— %0a%0a" Where the forehead is broad, it is significant of a dull and %0asluggish understanding beneath ; and where it is small, it in- %0adicates an unsteady disposition. A rounded forehead denotes %0aan irascible temper, it seeming as though the swelling anger %0ahad left its traces there. Where the eye-brows are extended %0ain one straight line, they denote effeminacy in ihe owner, and %0awhen they are bent downwards towards the nose, an austere %0adisposition. On the other hand, when the eye-brows are bent %0atowards the temples, they are indicative of a sarcastic dispo- %0asition ; but when they lie very low, thcj denote malice and %0aenvy. Long eyes are significant of a spiteful, malicious nature; %0aand where the corners of the eyes next the nose are fleshy, it %0ais a sign also of a wicked disposition. If the white of the eye %0ais large, it bears tokens of impudence, while those who are %0aincessantly closing the ej'elids are inconstant. Largeness of %0a%0a61 But they are borrowed from Aristotle, Hist. Ar.im. E. i. c. 9. %0a%0a%0a%0aChap. 115.] %0a%0a%0a%0aEESPIEA.TION AND KTTTEIMENT. %0a%0a%0a%0a97 %0a%0a%0a%0athe ears is a sign of loquacity and foolishness." Thus much %0aof what Trogus says. %0a%0aCHAP. 115, (53.) — RESPIRATION AND NUTRIMENT. %0a%0aThe hreath of the lion is fetid, and that of the bear quite %0apestilential ; indeed, no beast will touch anything with Avhich %0aits breath has come in contact, and substances which it has %0abreathed upon will become putrid sooner than others. It is %0ain man only that Nature has willed that the breath should %0abecome tainted in several ways, either through faultiness in %0athe victuals or the teeth, or else, as is more generally the case, %0athrough extreme old age. Our breath in itself was insensible %0ato all pain, utterly devoid as it was of all powers of touch and %0afeeling, without which there can be no sensation ; ever re- %0anewed, it was always forthcoming, destined to be the last ad- %0ajunct that shall leave the body, and the only one to remain %0awhen aU is gone beside ; it drew, in fine, its origin from, %0aheaven. In spite of all this, however, certain penalties were %0adiscovered to be inflicted upon it, so that the very substance %0aby the aid of which we live might become a torment to us in %0alife. This inconvenience is more particularly experienced %0aamong the Partliians, from their youth upwards, on account %0aof the indiscriminate use of food among them ; and, indeed, %0atheir very excess in wine causes their breath to be fetid. The %0agrandees, however, of that nation have a remedy for bad breath %0ain the pips of the Assyrian citron,^- which they mix with their %0afood, and the aroma of which is particularly agreeable. The %0abreath of the elephant will attract serpents from their holes, %0awhile that of the stag scorches them. We have already made %0amention*^ of certain races of men who could by suction extract %0afrom the body the venom of serpents ; and swine will even eat %0aserpents,*^ which to other animals are poisonous. All those %0acreatures which we have spoken of as insects, can be killed by %0amerely sprinkling them Avith oil.*^* Vultures, which are put %0ato flight by unguents, are attracted by other odours : the beetle, %0atoo, is- attracted by the rose. The scorpion puts to death certain %0aserpents. The Scythians dip their arrows in the poison of %0a%0a«2 See B. xii. c. 7. " B. vii. c. 2. %0a%0a" See B. xxix. c. 23. %0a%0a" See c. 21 of the present Book. %0a%0aVOL. in. H %0a%0a%0a%0a98 %0a%0a%0a%0aFlint's katural histobt. %0a%0a%0a%0a[Book XL %0a%0a%0a%0aserpents and human blood : against this frightful composition %0athere is no remedy, for with the slightest touch it is productive %0aof instant death. %0a%0aCHAP. 116. ANIMALS WHICH WHEN FED UPON POISON Do %0a%0aNOT DIE, AND THE FLESH OF WHICH IS POISONOUS. %0a%0aThe animals which feed upon poison have been already" %0amentioned. Some of them, which are harmless of themselves, %0abecome noxious if fed upon venomous substances. The wild %0aboar of Pamphylia and the mountainous parts of Cilicia, after %0ahaving devoured a salamander, will become poisonous to those %0awho eat its flesh ; and yet the danger is quite imperceptible %0aby reason of any peculiarity in the smell and taste. The sala- %0amander, too, will poison either water or wine, in which it %0ahappens to be drowned ; and what is more, if it has only drunk %0athereof, the liquid becomes poisonous. The same is the case, %0atoo, with the frog known to us as the bramble-frog. So nu- %0amerous are the snares that are laid in wait for life ! Wasps %0agreedily devour the flesh of the serpent, a nutriment which %0arenders their stings fatal ; so vast is the diflerence to be found %0abetween one kind of food and another. In the country, too, %0aof the Ichthyophagi,^' as we learn from Theophrastus, the oxen %0aare fed upon fish, but only when alive. %0a%0aCHAP. 117. — REASONS FOR INDIGESTION. REMEDIES FOB %0aCRUDITY. %0a%0aThe most wholesome nutriment for man is plain food. An %0aaccumulation of flavours is injurious, and still more so, if %0aheightened by sauces. All acrid elements are difiicult of di- %0agestion, and the same is the case if food is devoured greedily, %0aor in too large quantities. Food is also less easily digested in %0asummer than in winter, and in old age than in youth. The %0avomits which man has invented, by way of remedy for this %0aevil, render the body more cold, and are more particularly inju- %0arious to the eyes and teeth. %0a%0aCHAP. 118. FROM WHAT CAUSES CORPULENCE ARISES; %0a%0aHOW IT MAY BE REDUCED. %0a%0aDigestion during sleep is more productive of corpulence than %0astrength. Hence it is, that it is preferable for athletes to %0a«5 B. ix. c. 33. 67 Or Fish-eaters. %0a%0a%0a%0aChap. 119.] %0a%0a%0a%0aBUMMAET. %0a%0a%0a%0a99 %0a%0a%0a%0aquicken digestion by walking. Watching, at night more es- %0apecially, promotes digestion of the food. %0a%0a(54.) The size of the body is increased by eating sweet and %0afatty substances, as well as by drinking, while, on the other %0ahand, it is diminished by eating dry, acrid, or cold substances, %0aand by abstaining from drink. Some animals of Africa, as %0awell as sheep, drink but once every four days. Abstinence %0afrom food for seven days, even, is not of necessity fatal to man ; %0aand it is a well-known fact, that many persons have not died till %0aafter an abstinence of eleven days. Man is the only animal %0athat is ever attacked with an insatiate^ craving for food. %0a%0aCHAP. 119. — WHAT THINGS,- BT MEHELY TASTING OF THEM, %0aALLAY HtJNGEE AND THIEST. %0a%0aOn the other hand, there are some substances which, tasted %0ain small quantities only, appease hunger and thirst, and keen %0aup the strength, such as butter, for instance, cheese made of %0amares' milk, and liquorice. But the most pernicious thing of %0aall, and in every station of life, is excess, and more especially %0aexcess in food ; in fact, it is the most prudent plan to re- %0atrench everything that may be possibly productive of injury. %0aLet us, however, now pass on to the other branches of Nature. %0a%0aSuMMAEY. — Remarkable facts, narratives, and observations, %0atwo thousand, two hundred, and seventy. %0a%0aEoMAN AUTHORS QUOTED. — M. Varro,^^ Hyginus,™ Scrofa," %0aSasema,''^ Celsus Cornelius," iEmilius Maccr,'* Virgil,'* Colu- %0amella,'® Julius Aquila" who wrote on the Tuscan art of Divi- %0anation, Tarquitius'^ who wi'ote on the same subject, Umbricius %0aMelior" who wrote on the same subject, Cato the Censor," %0aDomitius Calvinus,^^ Trogus,^^ Melissus,** Fabianus,** Muci- %0aanu^,^* Nigidius,^^ Manilius,**' Oppius.^^ %0a%0a^ Or bulimia. %0a%0a«9 See end of B. ii. See end of B. iii. %0a%0aC. Tremellius Scrofa, a friend of M. Varro, and one of the early writers %0aon agriculture. ''^ See end of B. x. %0a%0a" See end of B. vii. See end of B. ix. %0a%0a" See end of B. vii. '^ See end of B. viii. %0a%0a" See end of B. ii. '* See end of B. ii. %0a%0a" See end of B. x. ^" See end of B. iii. %0a%0aNothing seems to be known of this writer. %0a82 See end of B. vii. See end of B. vii. %0a%0a" See end of B. ii. See end of B. ii. %0a%0a9« See end of B. vi. *' See end of B. x. %0a%0aC. Oppius, one of the most intimate friends of Julius Csesar, for whom, %0a%0a%0a%