eed, in no one of her works has Nature more fully %0a%3c displayed her exhaustless ingenuity. %0a%3c %0a%3c (2.) In large animals, on the other hand, or, at all events, %0a%3c %0a%3c ' " Immensifi subtilitatis." As Cuvier remarks, the ancients have com- %0a%3c mitted more errors in reference to the insects, than to any other portion of %0a%3c the animal world. The discovery of the microscope has served more than %0a%3c anything to correct these erroneous notions. %0a%3c %0a%3c * " Insecta," "articulated." %0a%3c %0a%3c VOL. 111. B %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c BOOK XI. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 2 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c flint's natural history. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [Book XI. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c in the rery largest among them, she found hor task easy and %0a%3c her materials ready and pliable ; but in those minute creatures, %0a%3c so nearly akin as they are to non-entity, how surpassing the %0a%3c intelligence, how vast the resources, and how ineffable the %0a%3c perfection which she has displayed. Where is it that she has %0a%3c united so many senses as in the gnat ? — not to speak of creatures %0a%3c that might be mentioned of still smaller size — Where, I say, %0a%3c has she found room to place in it the organs of sight ? Where %0a%3c has she centred the sense of taste ? Where has she inserted %0a%3c the power of smell ? And where, too, has she implanted that %0a%3c sharp shrill voice of the creature, so utterly disproportioned to %0a%3c the smallness of its body ? With what astonishing subtlety %0a%3c has she united the wings to the trunk, elongated the joints %0a%3c of the legs, framed that long, craving concavity for a belly, and %0a%3c then inflamed the animal with an insatiate thirst for blood, %0a%3c that of man more especially! What ingenuity has she displayed %0a%3c in providing it with a sting,^ so well adapted for piercing the %0a%3c skin! And then too, just as though she had had the most %0a%3c extensive field for the exercise