to be accorded to bees, which alone, %0a%3c of all the insects, have been created for the benefit of man. %0a%3c They extract honey and collect it, a juicy substance remarkable %0a%3c for its extreme sweetness, lightness, and wholesomeness. They %0a%3c form their combs and collect wax, an article that is useful for %0a%3c a thousand purposes of life ; thej^ are patient of fatigue, toil at %0a%3c their labours, form themselves into political communities, hold %0a%3c councils together in private, elect chiefs in common, and, a thing %0a%3c that is the most remarkable of all, have their own code of morals. %0a%3c In addition to this, being as they are, neither tame nor wild, %0a%3c 80 all-powerful is Nature, that, from a creature so minute as to %0a%3c be nothing more hardly than the shadow of an animal, she has %0a%3c created a marvel beyond all comparison. What muscular %0a%3c power, what exertion of strength are we to put in comparison %0a%3c with such vast energy and such industry as theirs ? What dis- %0a%3c play of human genius, in a word, shaJl we compare with the %0a%3c reasoning powers manifested by them ? In this they have, at %0a%3c all events, the advantage of us — they know of nothing but what %0a%3c is for the common benefit of all. Away, then, with all questions %0a%3c whether they respire or no, and let us be ready to agree on %0a%3c the question of their blood ; and yet, how little of it can pos- %0a%3c sibly exist in bodies so minute as theirs. — And now let us %0a%3c form some idea of the instinct they display. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 5. (6.) THE OEDEE DISPLAYED IN THE WORKS OP BEES. %0a%3c %0a%3c Bees keep within the hive during the winter — for whence %0a%3c are they to derive the strength requisite to withstand frosts %0a%3c and snows, and the northern blasts ? The same, in fact, is %0a%3c done by all insects, but not to so late a period; as those %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 6 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c PLINY'S NATTJEAL HISTOET. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 