d by the %0a%3c leaves of trees, is that gathered from the foKage of the oak %0a%3c and the linden, and from reeds. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 14. (14.) — THE KINDS OF HONEY PECtJXIAK TO VARIOUS %0a%3c PLACES. %0a%3c %0a%3c The peculiar excellence of honey depends, as already stated," %0a%3c on the country in which it is produced ; the modes, too, of %0a%3c estimating its quality are numerous. In some countries we find %0a%3c the honey-comb remarkable for the goodness of the wax, as iu %0a%3c Sicily, for instance, and the country of the Peligni ; in other %0a%3c places the honey itself is found in greater abundance, as in %0a%3c Crete, Cyprus, and Africa ; and in others, again, the comb is %0a%3c remarkable for its size ; the northern climates, for instance, %0a%3c for in Germany a comb has been known to be as much as eight %0a%3c feet in length, and quite black on the concave surface. %0a%3c %0a%3c Butwhatever the country in which it may happen to have been %0a%3c produced, there are three different kinds of honey. — Spring %0a%3c honey is that made in a comb which has been constructed of %0a%3c flowers, from which cii'cumstance it has received the name of %0a%3c thinum. There are some persons who say that this should not %0a%3c be touched, because the more abundant the nutriment, the %0a%3c %0a%3c 32 See B. iv. c. 24. 33 the last Chapter. %0a%3c %0a%3c 34 Qr " Flower-honey." %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Chap. 14.] %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c VAHIOTJS KIKDS OF HONEY. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 13 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c stronger Avill be the coming swarm ; while others, again, leave %0a%3c less of this honey than of any other for the bees, on the ground %0a%3c that there is sure to be a vast abundance at the rising of the %0a%3c greater constellations, as well as at the summer solstice, when %0a%3c the thyme and the vine begin to blossom, for then they are %0a%3c sure to find abundant materials for their cells. %0a%3c %0a%3c In taking the combs the greatest care is al