8.) THE VARIOUS KINDS OF BEES. %0a%3c %0a%3c There are field bees also, and wild bees, ungainly in appear- %0a%3c ance, and much more irascible than the others, but remarkable %0a%3c for their laboriousness and the excellence of their work. Of %0a%3c domestic bees there are two sorts ; the best are those with %0a%3c short bodies, speckled all over, and of a compact round shape. %0a%3c Those that are long, and resemble the wasp in appearance, %0a%3c are an inferior kind ; and of these last, the very worst of all %0a%3c are those which have the body covered with hair. In Pontus %0a%3c there is a kind of white bee, which makes honey twice a %0a%3c month. On the banks of the river Thermodon there are %0a%3c two kinds found, one of which makes honey in the trees, the %0a%3c other under ground : they form a triple row of combs, and %0a%3c produce honey in the greatest abundance. %0a%3c %0a%3c Nature has provided bees with a sting, which is inserted in %0a%3c the abdomen of the insect. There are some who think that %0a%3c at the first blow which they inflict with this weapon they will %0a%3c instantly die,^' while others, again, are of opinion that such is %0a%3c not the case, unless the animal drives it so deep as to cause %0a%3c a portion of the intestines to follow ; and they assert, also, %0a%3c that after they have thus lost their sting they become drones," %0a%3c %0a%3c 8- So Virgil says — %0a%3c %0a%3c ■ " Haec certamina tanta %0a%3c %0a%3c Pulveris exigui jactu compressa quiescent." — Georg. iv. 87. %0a%3c If it is left in the wound, the insect dies, being torn asunder %0a%3c «i Of course this is fabulous, as the drones are males. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Chap. 20.] %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c THE DISEASES OF BEES. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 21 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c and make no honey, being thus castrated, so to say, and %0a%3c equally incapable of inflicting injury, and of making themselves %0a%3c useful by their labours. We have instances stated of horses %0a%3c being killed by bees. %0a%3c %0a%3c They have a great aversion to bad smells, and fly away %0a%3c from them ; a dislike which extends to artificial perfumes %0a%3c even. Hence it is that they will attack persons who smell %0a%3c of unguents. They themselves, also, are exposed to the %0a%3c attacks of wasps and hornets, which belong to the same class, %0a%3c but are of a degenerate^ nature ; these wage continual warfare %0a%3c against them, as also does a species of gnat, which is known %0a%3c by the name of " mulio;""® swallows, too, and various other %0a%3c birds prey upon them. Frogs lie in wait for them when in %0a%3c quest of water, which, in fact, is their principal occupation %0a%3c at the time they are rearing their young. And it is not only %0a%3c the frog that frequents ponds and streams that is thus injuri- %0a%3c ous to them, but the bramble-frog as well, which will come %0a%3c to the hives even in search of them, and, crawling up to the %0a%3c entrance, breathe through the apertures ; upon hearing which, a %0a%3c bee flies to the spot, and is snapped up in an instant. It is %0a%3c generally stated that frogs are proof against the sting of the %0a%3c bee. Sheep, too, are peculiarly dangerous to them, as they %0a%3c have the greatest difficulty in extricating themselves from %0a%3c the fleece. The smell of crabs,®' if they happen to be cooked in %0a%3c their vicinity, is fatal to them. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 20. — THE DISEASES OF BEES. %0a%3c %0a%3c Bees are also by nature liable to certain diseases of their %0a%3c own. The sign that they are diseased, is a kind of torpid, %0a%3c moping sadness : on such occasions, they are to be seen bring- %0a%3c ing out those that are sick before the hives, and placing them %0a%3c in the warm sun, while others, again, are providing them with %0a%3c food. Those that are dead they carry away from the hive, %0a%3c and attend the bodies, pajdng their last duties, as it were, in %0a%3c funeral procession. If the king 