eir numbers are recruited by %0a%3c fresh offspring from time to time. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 25. (22.) THE BOMBTX OF ASSYEIA. %0a%3c %0a%3c A fourth class of this kind®" of insect is the bombyx,^' which %0a%3c is a native of AssjTia, and is of larger size than any of those %0a%3c which have been previously mentioned. They construct their %0a%3c nests of a kind of mud which has the appearance of salt, and %0a%3c then fasten them to a stone, where they become so hard, that %0a%3c it is scarcely possible to penetrate them with a dart even. %0a%3c In these nests they make wax, in larger quantities than bees, %0a%3c and the grub which they then produce is larger. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 26. — THE LAEV^ OF THE SILK-WOEM — WHO FIEST INVENTED %0a%3c SILK CLOTHS. %0a%3c %0a%3c There is another class also of these insects produced in quite %0a%3c a diflferent manner. These last spring from a grub of larger %0a%3c size, with two horns of very peculiar appearance. The %0a%3c larva then becomes a caterpillar, after which it assumes the %0a%3c state in which it is known as homhylis, then that called necy- %0a%3c dalm, and after that, in six months, it becomes a silk-worm." %0a%3c %0a%3c Cuvier says that it is the males, and not the females, that have no sting. %0a%3c %0a%3c What modern naturalists call the " Hymenoptera." %0a%3c *' Some kind of wasp, or, as Cuvier says, probably the mason bee. %0a%3c ^ Called "bombyx" also; though, as Cuvier remarks, of a kind al- %0a%3c together different from the preceding one. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 26 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Flint's natural history. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [Book XI. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c These insects weave webs similar to those of the spider, the %0a%3c material of which is used for making the more costly and %0a%3c luxurious garments of females, known as " bombycina. Pam- %0a%3c phile, a woman of Cos,**' the daughter of Platea, was the first %0a%3c person who discovered the art of unravelling these webs and %0a