 whether it is that, at stated periods the excrements are largely %0a%3c secreted in the abdomen, as Democritus thinks, or that the %0a%3c creature has in itself a certain faculty of secreting®* a peculiar %0a%3c sort of woolly substance. How steadily does it work with its %0a%3c claws, how beautifully rounded and how equal are the threads %0a%3c as it forms its web, while it employs the weight of its body as %0a%3c an equipoise ! It begins at the middle to weave its web, and %0a%3c then extends it by adding the threads in rings around, like a %0a%3c warp upon the woof : forming the meshes at equal intervals, %0a%3c but continually enlarging them as the web increases in breadth, %0a%3c it finally unites them all by an indissoluble knot. "With what %0a%3c wondrous art does it conceal the snares that lie in wait %0a%3c for its prey in its checkered nettings ! How little, too, woidd %0a%3c it seem that there is any such trap laid in the compactness of %0a%3c %0a%3c enacted " ne vestis Serica viros faedaret" — " That men should not defile %0a%3c themselves by wearing garments of silk," Ann. B. ii. c. 33. %0a%3c *" The Ai-anea lupus of Linnseus. %0a%3c %0a%3c As Cuvier observes, he has here guessed at the truth. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 28 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c PLIirr's NATURAL niSTOET. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Book XI. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c its web and the tenacious texture of the woof, wliich Avould %0a%3c appear of itself to be finished and arranged by the exercise of %0a%3c the very highest art ! How loose, too, is the body of the web %0a%3c as it yields to the blasts, and how readily does it catch all objects %0a%3c which come in its way ! You Avould fancy that it had left, %0a%3c quite exhausted, the thrums of the upper portion of its net %0a%3c unfinished where they are spread across ; it is with the great- %0a%3c est difficulty that they are to be perceived, and yet the moment %0a%3c that an object touches them, like the lines of the hunter's net, %0a%3c they throw it into the body of the web. With what archi- %0a%3c tectural skill, too, is its hole arched over, and how well de- %0a%3c fended by a nap of extra thickness against the cold ! How %0a%3c carefully, too, it retires into a corner, and appears intent upon %0a%3c anything but what it really is, all the while that it is so care- %0a%3c fully shut up from view, that it is impossible to perceive whe- %0a%3c ther there is anything within or not I And then too, how ex- %0a%3c traordinary the strength of the web ! When is the wind ever %0a%3c known to break it, or what accumulation of dust is able to %0a%3c weigh it down ? %0a%3c %0a%3c The spider often spreads its web right across between two %0a%3c trees, when plpng its art and learning how to spin ; and then, %0a%3c as to its length, the thread extends from the very top of the %0a%3c tree to the ground, while the insect springs up again in an %0a%3c instant from the earth, and travels aloft by the very self-same %0a%3c thread, thus mounting at the same moment and spinning %0a%3c its threads. When its prey falls into its net, how on the alert %0a%3c it is, and with what readiness it runs to seize it ! Even %0a%3c though it should be adhering to the very edge of its web, the %0a%3c insect always runs instantly to the middle, as it is by these %0a%3c means that it can most effectually shake the web, and so suc- %0a%3c cessfully entangle its prey. When the web is torn, the %0a%3c spider immediately sets about repairing it, and that so neatly, %0a%3c that nothing like patching can ever be seen. The spider lies %0a%3c in wait even for the young of the lizard, and after enveloping %0a%3c the head of the animal, bites its lips ; a sight by no means %0a%3c unworthy of the amphitheatre itself, when it is one's good for- %0a%3c tune to witness it. Presages also are drawn from the spider ; %0a%3c for when a river is about to swell, it will suspend its web %0a%3c higher than usual. In calm weather these insects do not spin, %0a%3c but when it is cloudy they do, and hence it is, that a great %0a%3c number of cobwebs is a sure sign of showery weather. It is %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Chap. 30.] %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c SCOEPTONS. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 29 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c generally supposed that it is the female spicier that spins, %0a%3c and the male that lies in wait for prey, thus making an equal %0a%3c division of their duties. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 29. THE GENEEATION OF SPIDEES. %0a%3c %0a%3c Spiders couple®^ backwards, and produce maggots like eggs ; %0a%3c for I ought not to defer making some mention of this subject, %0a%3c seeing, in fact, that of most insects there is hardly anything %0a%3c else to be said. All these eggs they lay in their webs, but %0a%3c scattered about, as they leap from place to place while laying %0a%3c them. The phalangium is the only spider that lays a con- %0a%3c siderable number of them, in a hole ; and as soon as ever %0a%3c the progeny is hatched it devours its mother, and very often %0a%3c the male parent as well, for that, too, aids in the process of %0a%3c incubation. These last produce as many as three hundred %0a%3c eggs, the others a smaller number. Spiders take three days %0a%3c to hatch their eggs. They come to their full growth in %0a%3c twenty-eight days. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 30. (25.) — SCOEPIONS. %0a%3c %0a%3c In a similar manner to the spider, the land scorpion also pro- %0a%3c duces maggots^ similar to eggs, and dies in a similar manner. %0a%3c This animal is a dangerous scourge, and has a venom like that %0a%3c of the serpent ; with the exception that its effects are far %0a%3c more"^ painful, as the person who is stung will linger for %0a%3c three days before death ensues. The sting is invariably %0a%3c fatal to virgins, and nearly always so to matrons. It is so %0a%3c to men also, in the morning, when the animal has issued from %0a%3c its hole in a fasting state, and has not yet happened to dis- %0a%3c char