e found who ever saw one. %0a%3c %0a%3c *^ They only appear to be so, from the peculiar streaks on the eyes. %0a%3c Linnaeus has hence called one variety, the Tabanus caecutiens. %0a%3c %0a%3c '8 Or with pounded chalk or whitening. -Lilian adds, "if they are placed %0a%3c in the sun," which appears necessary for the full success of the experiment. %0a%3c Life appears to be suspended in such cases for a period of surprising length. %0a%3c %0a%3c *^ Probably the golden pheasant, as already mentioned. %0a%3c Some kind of neron or crane, Cuvier thinks. %0a%3c %0a%3c 6' The Alauda cristata of Linnseus, so called from " galera," a pointed %0a%3c cap like a helmet. %0a%3c %0a%3c 62 The fiftb legion. 63 The hoopoe, B. x. c. 44. %0a%3c %0a%3c " Savigny and Cu'^ier take this to be the Ardea virgo of Linnaeus, a %0a%3c native of Numidia. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 44 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Flint's natural iiistoet. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [Book XI. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 45. THE VAKIOUS KINDS OF HOllXS. ANIMALS IN WHICH %0a%3c %0a%3c XHEr ARE MOVKABLE. %0a%3c %0a%3c Horns, too, of various forms have been granted to many %0a%3c animals of the aquatic, marine, and reptile kind, but those %0a%3c which are more properly understood under that name belong %0a%3c to the quadrupeds only ; for I look upon the tales of Actaeon %0a%3c and of Cippus even, in Latin story, as nothing more nor less than %0a%3c fables.^ And, indeed, in no department of her works has %0a%3c Nature displayed a greater capriciousness. In providing ani- %0a%3c mals with these weapons, she has made merry at their ex- %0a%3c pense ; for some she has spread them out in branches, the %0a%3c stag, for instance ; to others she has given them in a more %0a%3c simple form, as in the " subulo," so called from the resem- %0a%3c blance of its horns to a " subula,"*"' or shoemaker's awl. In %0a%3c others, again, she has flattened them in the shape of a man's %0a%3c hand, with the fingers extended, fi-om which circumstance the %0a%3c animal has received the name of " platyceros."*' To the roe- %0a%3c buck she has given branching horns, but small, and has made %0a%3c them so as not to fall off and be cast each year ; while to the %0a%3c ram she has given them of a contorted and spiral form, as %0a%3c though she were providing it with a caestus for offence. The %0a%3c horns of the bull, again, are upright and threatening. In this %0a%3c last kind, the females, too, are provided with them, while in %0a%3c most it is only the males. The chamois has them, curving %0a%3c backwards ; while in the fallow deer®® they bend forward. %0a%3c The strepsiceros,^'" which in Africa bears the name of addax, has %0a%3c horns erect and spiral, grooved and tapering to a sharp point, %0a%3c so much so, that you would almost take them to be the sides %0a%3c of a lyro.''^* In the oxen of Phrygia, the horns are moveable,'' %0a%3c %0a%3c 65 The suddenness of their appearance, no doubt, was fabulous ; but we %0a%3c have well-authenticated cases in recent times of substances growing on the %0a%3c human head, to all appearance resembling horns, and arising from a dis- %0a%3c ordered secretion of the hair. Witness the case of Mary Davies, a so- %0a%3c called horn from whose head is preserved in the Ashmolean Museum at %0a%3c Oxford. The story of Genucius Cipnus, the Eomau prator is told by %0a%3c Ovid, Met. B. xv. 1. 565, et seq. " . " ' ' %0a%3c %0a%3c ^ A spitter, or second year stag, according to Cuvier. %0a%3c %0a%3c «^ " Broad-horned." The Ccrvus dama of Linnaeus. %0a%3c %0a%3c ^ " Daina." The Antelope redunca of Linnaeus, Cuvier thinks. %0a%3c %0a%3c •* No doubt a kind of antelope. %0a%3c %0a%3c ^* "Lyras" seems preferable to "liras." %0a%3c %0a%3c ™ There are several varieties of oxen, in which the horns adhere to tlie %0a%3c Bkia, and not to the cranium. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c CLap. 45.] %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c TAllIOUS KINDS or H0KN3. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 45 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c like the ears; and among the cattle of the Troglodytte, they %0a%3c are pointed downwards to the ground, for which reason it is %0a%3c that they are obliged to feed with the head on one side. %0a%3c Other animals, again, have a single horn, and that situate in %0a%3c the middle of the head, or else on the nose, as already %0a%3c stated.'^ %0a%3c %0a%3c Then, agaih, in some animals the horns are adapted for %0a%3c butting, and in others for goring ; with some they are curved %0a%3c inwards, with others outwards, and with others, again, they %0a%3c are fitted for tossing : all which objects are effected in vari- %0a%3c ous ways, the horns either lying backwards, turning from, or %0a%3c else towards each other, and in all cases running to a sharp %0a%3c point. In one kind, also, the horns are used for the purpose %0a%3c of scratching the body, instead of hands. %0a%3c %0a%3c In snails the horns are fleshy, and are thus adapted for the %0a%3c purpose of feeling the way, which is also the case with the ce- %0a%3c rastes ; " some reptiles, again, have only one horn, though the %0a%3c snail has always two, suited for protruding and withdrawing. %0a%3c The barbarous nations of the north drink from the horns of the %0a%3c urus," a pair of which will hold a couple of um£e other %0a%3c tribes, again, point their spears with them. With us they are %0a%3c cut into lamina), upon which they become transparent ; indeed, %0a%3c the rays of a light placed within them may be seen to a much %0a%3c greater distance than without. They are used also for various %0a%3c appliances of luxury, either coloured or varnished, or else %0a%3c for those kinds of paintings which are known as " cestrota,"'® %0a%3c or horn-pictures. The horns of all animals are hollow within, %0a%3c it being only at the tip that they are solid : the only excep- %0a%3c tion is the stag, the horn of which is solid throughout, and %0a%3c is cast every year. When the hoofs of oxen are worn to the %0a%3c quick, the husbandmen have a method of curing them, by %0a%3c anointing the horns of the animal with grease. The substance %0a%3c of the horns is so ductile, that even while upon the body of %0a%3c the living animal, they can be bent by being steeped in boil- %0a%3c ing wax, and if they are split down when they are first shoot- %0a%3c ing, they may be twisted different ways, and so appear to be %0a%3c %0a%3c ■Ji B. viii.cc.29— 31. %0a%3c %0a%3c The Coluber cerastes of Linnaeus. See B. viii. c. 35. %0a%3c The drinking-horns of our Saxon ancestors are well known to the %0a%3c antiquarian. %0a%3c %0a%3c The " urna" was half an "amphora," or nearly three gallons. %0a%3c ^5 See B. XXXV. c. 41. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 46 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Flint's natukal history. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [Book XI. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c four in number upon one head. In females the horns are gene- %0a%3c rally thinner than in the males, as is the case, also, with most %0a%3c kinds of wool-bearing animals. %0a%3c %0a%3c No individuals, however, among sheep, or hinds, nor yet %0a%3c any that have the feet divided into toes, or that have solid %0a%3c hoofs, are furnished with horns ; with the sole exception of %0a%3c the Indian ass,'^ which is armed with a single horn. To the %0a%3c beasts that are cloven-footed Nature has granted two horns, %0a%3c but to those that have fore-teeth in the upper jaw, she has %0a%3c given none. Those persons who entertain the notion that the %0a%3c substance of these teeth is expended in the formation of the %0a%3c horns, are easily to be refuted, if we only consider the case of %0a%3c the hind, which has no more teeth than the male, and 5-et %0a%3c is without horns altogether. In the stag the horn is only %0a%3c imbedded in the skin, but in the other" animals it adheres to %0a%3c the bone. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 46. THE HEADS OP ANIMALS. THOSE WHICH HAVE NOSF. %0a%3c %0a%3c The head of the fish is very large in proportion to the rest %0a%3c of the body, probably, to facilitate its diving under water. %0a%3c Animals of the oyster and the sponge kind have no head, %0a%3c which is the case, also, with most of the other kinds, whose %0a%3c only sense is that of touch. Some, again, have the head %0a%3c blended with the body, the crab, for instance. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 47. THE HAIR. %0a%3c %0a%3c Of all animals man has the longest hair upon the head ; which %0a%3c is the case more especially with those nations where the men and %0a%3c women in common leave the hair to grow, and do not cut it. %0a%3c Indeed, it is from this fact, that the inhabitants of the Alps %0a%3c have obtained from us the name of " Capillati,"'* as also those %0a%3c of Gallia, " Comata."'^ There is, however, a great difference %0a%3c in this respect according to the various countries. In the %0a%3c island of Myconus,^" the people are bom without hair, just %0a%3c as at Caunus the inhabitants are afflicted with the spleen %0a%3c %0a%3c '6 The rhinoceros. See B. viii. c. 39. %0a%3c %0a%3c " He surely must except the Phrygian oxen with the moveable horns, %0a%3c which he has previously mentioned. %0a%3c '8 Or " long-haired." See B. iii. c. 7. %0a%3c " See B. iv. c. 31. so See B. iv. c. 22. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Chap. 49.] %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c THE BEALN. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 47 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c from their birth. There are some animals, also, that are natu- %0a%3c rally bald, such as the ostrich, for instance, and the aquatic %0a%3c raven, which last has thence derived its Greek"'^ name. It is %0a%3c but rarely that the hair falls off in women, and in eunuchs %0a%3c such is never known to be the case ; nor yet does any person %0a%3c lose it before having known sexual intercourse.®^ The hair %0a%3c does not fall off below the brain, nor yet beneath the crown of %0a%3c the head, or around the ears and the temples. Man is the %0a%3c only animal that becomes bald, with the exception, of course, %0a%3c of such animals as are naturally so. Man and the horse are %0a%3c the only creatures whose hair turns grey ; but with man this is %0a%3c always the case, fii'st in the fore-part of the head, and then in %0a%3c the hinder part. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 48. — THE BONES OF THE HEAD. %0a%3c %0a%3c Some few persons only are double- crowned. The bones of %0a%3c the head are flat, thin, devoid of marrow, and united with su- %0a%3c tures indented like a comb. When broken asunder they can- %0a%3c not be united, but the extraction of a small portion is not ne- %0a%3c cessarily fatal, as a fleshy cicatrix forms, and so makes good %0a%3c the loss. We have already mentioned, in their respective** %0a%3c places, that the skull of the bear is the weakest of all, and %0a%3c that of the parrot the hardest. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 49. THE BEAIN. %0a%3c %0a%3c The brain exists in all animals which have blood, and in %0a%3c those sea animals as well, which we have already mentioned %0a%3c as mollusks, although they are destitute of blood, the poly- %0a%3c pus, for instance. Man, however, has, in proportion to his %0a%3c body, the most voluminous brain of all. This, too, is the %0a%3c most humid, and the coldest of all the viscera, and is enve- %0a%3c loped above and below with two membranous integuments, %0a%3c for either of which to be broken is fatal. In addition to these %0a%3c facts, we may remark that the brain is larger in men than iu %0a%3c %0a%3c «i Sec B. v. c. 29. %0a%3c %0a%3c %3c^a\aKpoKupa^. See B. X. C. 68. %0a%3c ^ lie borrows this from Aristotle. %0a%3c %0a%3c B. viii. c. 54, and B. x. c. 58. The skull of the bear is not thinner %0a%3c or weaker than that of other animals of its own size ; but the skull of iLe %0a%3c parrot, in proportion to those of other birds, is remarkably hard. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 48 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c PLTNT'S NATURAL HISTOBT. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [Book XL %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c women. In man the brain is destitute of blood and veins, and %0a%3c in other animals it has no fat. Those who are well informed %0a%3c on the subject, tell us that the brain is quite a different %0a%3c substance from the marrow, seeing that on being boiled it %0a%3c only becomes harder. In the very middle of the braia of %0a%3c every animal there are small bones found. Man is the only ani- %0a%3c mal in which it is kno-svn to palpitate"^ during infancy ; and %0a%3c it does not gain its proper consistency until after the child has %0a%3c made its first attempt to speak. The brain is the most ele- %0a%3c vated of all the viscera, and the nearest to the roof of the %0a%3c head ; it is equally devoid of flesh, blood, and excretions. The %0a%3c senses hold this organ as their citadel ; it is in this that %0a%3c are centred all the veins which spring from the heart ; it is %0a%3c here that they terminate ; this is the very culminating point of %0a%3c all, the regulator of the understanding. "With all animals it %0a%3c is advanced to the fore-part of the head, from the fact that %0a%3c the senses have a tendency to the direction in which we look. %0a%3c From the brain proceeds sleep, and its return it is that causes %0a%3c the head to nod. Those creatures, in fact, which have no brain, %0a%3c never sleep. It is said that stags^^ have in the head certain %0a%3c small maggots, twenty in number : they are situate in the %0a%3c empty space that lies beneath the tongue, and around the joints %0a%3c by which the head is united to the body. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 50. — THE EAKS. ANIMALS WHICH HEAB WITHOUT EiES %0a%3c Oil APERTXJKES. %0a%3c %0a%3c Man is the only animal the ears of which are immoveable. %0a%3c It is from the natural flaccidity of the ear, that the surname %0a%3c of Flaccus is derived. There is no part of the body that %0a%3c creates a more enormous expense for our women, in the %0a%3c pearls which are suspended from them. In the East, too, it %0a%3c is thought highly becoming for the men, even, to wear gold %0a%3c rings in their ears. Some animals have large, and others %0a%3c small ears. The stag alone has them cut and divided, as it %0a%3c were ; in the field-mouse they have a velvet surface. AU the %0a%3c animals that are viviparous have ears of some kind or other, %0a%3c with the sole exception of the sea-calf, the dolphin, the fishes %0a%3c %0a%3c 85 See B. vii. c. 1. %0a%3c %0a%3c 65 Cuvier says that fhese are the larvae of the oestrus, which are deposited %0a%3c on the lips of quadrupeds, and so make their way to various cavities. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Cbap. 02.] %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c TUE ElES. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 49 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c which we have mentioned^' as cartilaginous, and the viper. %0a%3c These animals have only cavities instead of ears, with the ex- %0a%3c ception of the cartilaginous fishes and the dolphin, which last, %0a%3c however, it is quite clear possesses the sense of hearing, for it is %0a%3c charmed by singing, and is often taken while enraptured with %0a%3c the melody: how it is that it does hear, is quite marvellous. %0a%3c These animals, too, have not the slightest trace of olfactory %0a%3c organs, and yet they have a most acute sense of smell. %0a%3c %0a%3c Among the winged animals, only the horned owl and the long- %0a%3c eared owl have feathers which project like ears, the rest having %0a%3c only cavities for the purpose of hearing ; the same is the case, %0a%3c also, with the scaly animals and the serpents. Among horses %0a%3c and beasts of burden of all kinds, it is the ears which indicate %0a%3c the natural feelings; when the animal is weary, they are droop- %0a%3c ing and flaccid ; when it is startled, they quiver to and fro ; %0a%3c when it is enraged, they are pricked up ; and when it is ailing, %0a%3c they are pendant. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 51. — THE FACE, THE FOKEHEAD, AND THE ETE-BEOWS. %0a%3c %0a%3c Man is the only creature that has a face, the other animals %0a%3c having only a muzzle or a beak. Other animals have a fore- %0a%3c head as well, but it is only on the forehead of man that is %0a%3c depicted sorrow, gladness, compassion, or severity. It is the %0a%3c forehead that is the index of the mind. Man has eyebrows, %0a%3c also, which move together or alternately ; these, too, serve in %0a%3c some measure as indications of the feelings. Do we deny or %0a%3c do we assent, it is the eyebrows, mostly, that indicate our %0a%3c intentions. Feelings of pride may be generated elsewhere, %0a%3c but it is here that they have their principal abode ; it is in the %0a%3c heart that they take their rise, but it is to the eyebrows that %0a%3c they mount, and here they take up their position. In no part %0a%3c of the body could they meet with a spot more lofty and more %0a%3c precipitous, in which to establish themselves free from aU %0a%3c control. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 52. THE EYES — ANIMAIS WHICH HAVE NO EYES, OR HAVE %0a%3c %0a%3c ONLY ONE EYE. %0a%3c %0a%3c Below the forehead are the eyes, which form the most pre- %0a%3c cious portion of the human body, and which, by the enjoyment %0a%3c %0a%3c 8' B. ix. c. 40. %0a%3c %0a%3c VOL. Ill, B %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 50 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Flint's natubal histohy. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [Book XI. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c of the blessings of sight, distinguish life from death. Eyes, %0a%3c however, have not been granted to all animals ; oysters have %0a%3c none, but, with reference to some of the shell-fish, the question %0a%3c is still doubtful ; for if we move the fingers before a scallop %0a%3c half open, it will immediately close its shell, apparently from %0a%3c seeing them, while the solen^^ will start away from an iron %0a%3c instrument when placed near it. Among quadrupeds the %0a%3c mole*' has no sight, though it has something that bears a re- %0a%3c semblance to eyes, if we remove the membrane that is ex- %0a%3c tended in front of them. Among birds also, it is said that %0a%3c a species of heron, which is known as the "leucus,"^ is %0a%3c wanting of one eye : a bird of most excellent augury, when %0a%3c it flies towards the south or north, for it is said that it %0a%3c portends thereby that there is about to be an end of perils and %0a%3c alarms. Nigidius says also, that neither locusts nor grass- %0a%3c hoppers have eyes. In snails,**^ the two small horns with which %0a%3c they feel their way, perform the duties of eyes. Neither tlie %0a%3c mawworm^- nor any other kind of worm has eyes. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 53. — THE DIVEESITY OF THE COLOUK OF THE EYES. %0a%3c %0a%3c The eyes vary in colour in the human race only ; in all %0a%3c other animals they are of one uniform colour peculiar to the %0a%3c kind, though there are some horses that have eyes of an azure %0a%3c colour. But in man the varieties and diversities are most %0a%3c numerous ; the eyes being either large, of middling size, re- %0a%3c markably small, or remarkably prominent. These last are %0a%3c generally supposed to be very weak, while those which are %0a%3c deep-seated are considered the best, as is the case also with %0a%3c those which in colour resemble the eyes of the goat. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 54. THE THEOET OF SIGHT — PERSONS WHO CAX SEE BT %0a%3c %0a%3c NIGHT. %0a%3c %0a%3c In addition to this, there are some persons who can see to a %0a%3c ^ Or razor-sheath. See B. x. c. 88. %0a%3c %0a%3c 89 Aristotle was of this opinion, but Galen maintained that the mole can %0a%3c see. Its eye is extremely small, and hard on the surface. %0a%3c %0a%3c 90 Or "white" heron. As Cuvier remarks, this is probably a mere %0a%3c augur's fable. %0a%3c %0a%3c ^ It is almost needless to remark, that both snails, as well as locusts and %0a%3c grasshoppers, have eyes. %0a%3c 8* Lumbricus. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Chap. 54.] %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c tBe theoet or sight. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 51 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c very great distance, while there are others, again, -who can only %0a%3c distinguish objects when brought quite close to them. The %0a%3c vision of many stands in need of the rays of the sun ; such %0a%3c persons cannot see on a cloudy day, nor yet after the sun has %0a%3c set. Others, again, have bad sight in the day-time, but a %0a%3c sight superior to that of others by night. Of persons having %0a%3c double pupils, or the evil eye, we have already spoken'^ at %0a%3c sufficient length. Blue^* eyes are the best for seeing in the %0a%3c dark. %0a%3c %0a%3c It is said that Tiberius Caesar, like no other human being, %0a%3c was so endowed by Nature, that on awaking in the night** he %0a%3c could for a few moments distinguish objects just as well as %0a%3c in the clearest daylight, but that by degrees he would find %0a%3c his sight again enveloped in darkness. The late Emperor %0a%3c Augustus had azure eyes like those of some horses, the white %0a%3c being larger than with other men ; he used to be verj' angry %0a%3c if a person stared intently at them for this peculiarity. Claudius %0a%3c Caesar had at the corners of the eyes a white fleshy substance, %0a%3c covered with veins, which would occasionally become sufi'used %0a%3c with blood ; with the Emperor Caius* they had a fixed, steady %0a%3c gaze, while Nero could see nothing distinctly without wink- %0a%3c ing, and having it brought close to his eyes. The Emperor %0a%3c Caius had twenty pairs of gladiators in his training-school, %0a%3c and of all these there were only two who did not wink the %0a%3c eyes when a menacing gesture was made close to them : hence %0a%3c it was that these men were invincible. So difficult a matter is %0a%3c it for a man to keep his eyes from winking : indeed, to wink is %0a%3c so natural to many, that they cannot desist from it ; such per- %0a%3c sons we generally look upon as the most timid. %0a%3c %0a%3c No persons have the eye all of one colour ; that of the %0a%3c middle of the eye is always different from the white which %0a%3c surrounds it. In all animals there is no part^in the whole %0a%3c body that is a stronger exponent of the feelings, and in man %0a%3c more especially, for it is from the expression of the eye that %0a%3c we detect clemency, moderation, compassion, hatred, love, %0a%3c sadness, and joy. From the eyes, too, the various characters %0a%3c of persons are judged of, according as they are ferocious, me- %0a%3c %0a%3c 93 B. vii. c. 2. 9* " Caesii." %0a%3c %0a%3c ^ The same has been said also of Cardan, the elder Scaliger, Theodore %0a%3c Beza, the French physician Mairan, auJ tlie republican Camille Desmoulins. , %0a%3c s** Caligula. %0a%3c %0a%3c E 2 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 52 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c PLINr's NATUKAl HTSTOBT. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [Book XI. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c iiacing, sparkling, sedate, leering, askance, downcast, or Ian- %0a%3c guishing. Beyond a doubt it is in the eyes that the mind has %0a%3c its abode : sometimes the look is ardent, sometimes fixed and %0a%3c steady, at other times the eyes are humid, and at others, again, %0a%3c half closed. From these it is that the tears of pity flow, and %0a%3c when we kiss them we seem to be touching the very soul. It %0a%3c is the eyes that weep, and from them proceed those streams %0a%3c that moisten our cheeks as they trickle down. And what is %0a%3c this liquid that is always so ready and in such abundance in %0a%3c our moments of grief, and where is it kept in reserve at other %0a%3c times ? It is by the aid of the mind that we see, by the aid %0a%3c of the mind that we enjoy perception ; while the eyes, like so %0a%3c many vessels, as it were, receive its visual faculties and trans- %0a%3c mit them. Hence it is that profound thought renders a man %0a%3c blind for the time, the powers of sight being withdrawn fi'om %0a%3c external objects and thrown inward : so, too, in epilepsy, the %0a%3c mind is covered with darkness, while the eyes, though open, %0a%3c are able to see nothing. In addition to this, it is the fact %0a%3c that hares, as well as many human beings, can sleep with %0a%3c the eyes open, a thing which the Greeks express by the term %0a%3c zopy^avriav. Nature has composed the eye of numerous mem- %0a%3c branes of remarkable thinness, covering them with a thick coat %0a%3c to ensure their protection against heat and cold. This coat she %0a%3c purifies from time to time by the lachrymal humours, and she %0a%3c has made the surface lubricous and slippery, to protect the eye %0a%3c against the efi'ects of a sudden shock. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 55. THE NATUEE OF THE PUPIL EXES WHICH DO KOT %0a%3c %0a%3c SHUT. %0a%3c %0a%3c In the midst of the cornea of the eye Nature has formed a %0a%3c window in the pupil, the small dimensions of which do not %0a%3c permit the si^ht to wander at hazard and with uncertainty, %0a%3c but direct it as straight as though it were through a tuhe, %0a%3c and at the same time ensure its avoidance of all shocks com- %0a%3c municated by foreign bodies. The pupils are surrounded by a %0a%3c black circle in some persons, while it is of a yellowish cast with %0a%3c others, and azure again with others. By this happy combina- %0a%3c tion the light is received by the eye upon the white that lies %0a%3c around the pupU, and its reflection being thus tempered, it %0a%3c fails to impede or confuse the sight by its harshness. So %0a%3c complete a mirror, too, does the eye form, that the pupil, %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Chap. 55.] %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c THE NATtrnE OF THE PUPIL. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 53 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c small as it is, is able to reflect the entire image of a man. %0a%3c This^ is the reason why most birds, when held in the hand %0a%3c of a person, will more particularly peck at his eyes ; for seeing %0a%3c their own likeness reflected in the pupils, they are attracted to %0a%3c it by what seem to be the objects of their natural affection. %0a%3c %0a%3c It is only some few beasts of burden that are subject to %0a%3c maladies of the eyes towards the increase of the moon : but it %0a%3c is man alone that is rescued from blindness by the discharge %0a%3c of the humours* that have caused it. Many persons have %0a%3c had their sight restored after being blind for twenty years ; %0a%3c while others, again, have been denied this blessing from their %0a%3c very birth, without there being any blemish in the eyes. Many %0a%3c persons, again, have suddenly lost tneir sight from no apparent %0a%3c cause, and without any preceding injury. The most learned %0a%3c authors say that there are veins which communicate from the %0a%3c eye to the brain, but I am inclined to think that the communi- %0a%3c cation is with the stomach ; for it is quite certain that a person %0a%3c never loses the ej'e without feeling sickness at the stomach. It %0a%3c is an important and sacred duty, of high sanction among the %0a%3c Romans, to close the eyes of the dead, and then again to open %0a%3c them when the body is laid on the funeral pile, the usage %0a%3c having taken its rise in the notion of its being improper - that %0a%3c the eyes of the dead should be beheld by man, Avhile it is an %0a%3c equally great offence to hide them from the view of heaven. %0a%3c Man is the only living creature the eyes of which are subject %0a%3c to deformities, from which, in fact, arose the family names of %0a%3c " Strabo"^ and " Psetus." ^ The ancients used to call a man %0a%3c who was born with only one eye, "codes," and " ocella," a %0a%3c person whose eyes were remarkably small. " Luscinus" was %0a%3c the surname given to one who happened to have lost one eye %0a%3c by an accident. %0a%3c %0a%3c The eyes of animals that see at night in the dark, cats, for %0a%3c instance, are shining and radiant, so much so, that it is impos- %0a%3c sible to look upon them ; those of the she-goat, too, and the %0a%3c wolf are resplendent, and emit a light like fire. The eyes of %0a%3c the sea-calf and the hy£ena change successively to a thousand %0a%3c %0a%3c ^ Hardouin