WHAT ANIMALS AEE %0a%3c WITHOUT THEM. ANIMALS WHICH CAN SEE ON ONE SIDE ONLY. %0a%3c %0a%3c Man has lashes on the eye-lids on either side ; and women %0a%3c even make it their daily care to stain them ;'' so ardent are they %0a%3c in the pursuit of beauty, that they must even colour their %0a%3c very eyes. It was with another view, however, that Nature %0a%3c had provided the hair of the eyelids — they were to have acted, %0a%3c so to say, as a kind of rampart for the protection of the sight, %0a%3c and as an advanced bulwark against the approach of insects %0a%3c or other objects which might accidentally come in their way. %0a%3c It is not without some reason that it is said that the eye- %0a%3c lashes^ fall off' with those persons who are too much given to %0a%3c venereal pleasures. Of the other animals, the only ones that %0a%3c have eyelashes are those that have hair on the rest of the %0a%3c body as well ; but the quadrupeds have them on the upper %0a%3c %0a%3c 3 B. viii. c. 45. * B. viii. c. 51. %0a%3c %0a%3c 5 See B. XXV. c. 50. 6 Or crustaceous covering. %0a%3c %0a%3c ' Kohl is still used in the east for the same purpose. %0a%3c %0a%3c 8 Aristotle says so, Hist. Anim. B. iii. c. 10. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Chap. 59.] %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c THE NOSTEILS. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 55 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c eyelid only, and the birds on the lower one : the same is the %0a%3c case also with those which have a soft skin, such as the serpent, %0a%3c and those among the quadrupeds that are oviparous, the lizard, %0a%3c for instance. The ostrich is the only one among the birds %0a%3c that, like man, has eyelashes on either side. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAT. 57. ANIMALS WHICH HATE NO EYELIDS. %0a%3c %0a%3c All birds, however, have not eyelids: hence it is, that %0a%3c those which are viviparous have no nictation of the eye. %0a%3c The heavier kinds of birds shut the eye by means of the %0a%3c lower eyelid, and they wink by drawing forward a mem- %0a%3c brane which lies in the corner of the eye. Pigeons, and other %0a%3c birds of a similar nature, shut the two eyelids ; but the quad- %0a%3c rupeds which are oviparous, such, for instance, as the tortoise %0a%3c and the crocodile, have only the lower eyelid moveable, and %0a%3c never wink, in consequence of the hardness of the eye. The %0a%3c edge of the upper eyelid was by the ancients called " cilium," %0a%3c from which comes our word " supercilia.^" If the eyelid %0a%3c happens to be severed by a wound it will not reunite,'" which %0a%3c is the case also with some few other parts of the human body. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 58. — THE CHEEKS. %0a%3c %0a%3c Below the eyes are the cheeks, a feature which is found %0a%3c in man only. From the ancients they received the name of %0a%3c " gense," and by the laws of the Twelve Tables, women were %0a%3c forbidden to tear them." The cheeks are the seat of %0a%3c bashfulness ; it is on them more particularly that blushes are %0a%3c to be seen. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 59. THE NOSTEILS. %0a%3c %0a%3c "Within the cheeks is the mouth, which gives such Btrong %0a%3c indications of the feelings of joyousness and laughter; and %0a%3c above it, but in man only, is the nose, which modem notions %0a%3c have stamped as the exponent of sarcasm and ridicule.''^ In %0a%3c no other animal but man, is the nose thus prominent ; birds, %0a%3c serpents, and fishes, have no nostrils, but apertures only for %0a%3c the purpose of smell. It is from the peculiarity of the nose %0a%3c %0a%3c 9 " The eyebrows." %0a%3c %0a%3c 10 This is not the fact. %0a%3c %0a%3c 1' With their nails when mourning for the dead. %0a%3c %0a%3c 12 Hence the word "nasutus," a sneering, captious, or sarcastic man. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c flint's natural histoet. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [Book XI. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c that are derived the surnames of " Simus" " and " Silo." %0a%3c Children born in the seventh month often have the ears and %0a%3c the nostrils imperforate. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP, 60. — THE MOUTH ; THE LIPS ; THE CHIN ; AND THE %0a%3c JAW-BONE. %0a%3c %0a%3c It is from the " labia," or lips, that the Brocchi " have re- %0a%3c ceived the surname of Labeo. All animals that are viviparous %0a%3c have a mouth that is either well-formed, or harshly defined, %0a%3c as the case may be. Instead of lips and mouth, the birds %0a%3c have a beak that is horny and sharp at the end. With birds %0a%3c that live by rapine, the beak is hooked inwards, but with those %0a%3c which gather and peck only, it is straight : those animals, %0a%3c again, which root up grass or puddle in the mud, have the %0a%3c muzzle broad, like swine. The beasts of burden employ the %0a%3c mouth in place of hands in gathering their food, while those %0a%3c which live by rapine and slaughter have it wider than the %0a%3c rest. No animal, with the exception of man, has either chin %0a%3c or cheek-bones. The crocodile is the only animal that has the %0a%3c upper jaw-bone'^ moveable; among the land quadrupeds it is %0a%3c the same as with other animals, except that they can move it %0a%3c obliquely. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 61. — THE TEETH ; THE VARIOUS KINDS OF TEETH ; IN WHAT %0a%3c ANIMALS THEY ARE NOT ON BOTH SIDES OF THE MOUTH : ANIMALS %0a%3c WHICH HAVE HOLLOW TEETH. %0a%3c %0a%3c Teeth are arranged in three different ways, serrated, in one %0a%3c continuous row, or else protruding from the mouth. When %0a%3c serrated they unite together, just like those of a comb, in order %0a%3c that they may not be worn by rubbing against one another, as %0a%3c in serpents, fishes, and dogs,^^ for instance. In some creatures %0a%3c they are set in one continuous row, man and the horse, %0a%3c for instance; while in the wild boar, the elephant, and the %0a%3c hippopotamus, they protrude from the mouth," Among those %0a%3c set in one continuous row, the teeth which divide the food %0a%3c are broad and sharp, while those which grind it are double ; %0a%3c the teeth which lie between the 