th, that the food may not %0a%3c fall out, the animal itself having no other means of retaining %0a%3c it there. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 62. THE TEETH OF SERPENTS ; THEIR POISON. A BIRD %0a%3c %0a%3c WHICH HAS TEETH. %0a%3c %0a%3c The asp also, and other serpents, have similar teeth ; but in %0a%3c the upper jaw, on the right and left, they have two of extreme %0a%3c length, which are perforated with a small tube in the interior, %0a%3c %0a%3c 1* The morse and the dugong are instances to the contrary. %0a%3c %0a%3c " The females of the elephant, morsev dugong, chevrotin, and muntjac %0a%3c have them, and they are equally as useful as with the male, only, perhaps, %0a%3c not so strong. %0a%3c %0a%3c ^ This is incorrect, unless he merely means ranged in one continuous %0a%3c line ; and even then he is in error. %0a%3c %0a%3c ^1 See B. ix. c. 29. This is called the parrot-fish, from the resemblance %0a%3c of its upper and lower jaws to the beak of a parrot. %0a%3c %0a%3c 2- They present this appearance from being worn away at the surface. %0a%3c Eondelet would read " gula," the throat. This, though repudiated %0a%3c by Hardouin, is approved of by Cuvier, who justly looks upon the ordinary %0a%3c reading as an absurdity. Many fish, he says, and more especially the %0a%3c osseous ones, have teeth in the pharynx. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 58 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c PLUrr's NATURAL HISTOET. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [Book XI. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c just like the sting of the scorpion, and it is through those that %0a%3c they eject their venom. The writers who have made the most %0a%3c diUgent enquiries on the subject, inform us that this venom is %0a%3c nothing but the gall of the serpent, and that it is convoyed %0a%3c to the mouth by certain veins which run beneath the spine; %0a%3c indeed, there are some who state that there is only one poison- %0a%3c fang, and that being barbed at the end, it is bent backwards %0a%3c when the animal has inflicted a bite. Other