3c CHAP. 64. HOW AN ESTIMATE IS FORMEI) OF THE AGE %0a%3c %0a%3c OF ANIMALS FROM THEIK TEETH. %0a%3c %0a%3c The age, in beasts of burden,*' is indicated by the teeth. In %0a%3c the horse they are forty in number. At thirty months it %0a%3c loses the two fore-teeth in either jaw, and in the following year %0a%3c the same number next to them, at the time that the eye-teeth** %0a%3c come. At the beginning of the fifth year the animal loses two %0a%3c teeth, which grow again in the sixth, and in the seventh it has %0a%3c all its teeth, those which have replaced the others, and those %0a%3c "which have never been changed. If a horse is gelded^^ before %0a%3c it changes its teeth, it never sheds them. In a similar manner, %0a%3c also, the ass loses four of its teeth in the thirtieth month, and %0a%3c the others from six months to six months. If a she-ass hap- %0a%3c pens not to have foaled before the last of these teeth are shed, %0a%3c it is sure to be barren.** Oxen change their teeth at two years %0a%3c old: with swine they are never changed." When these %0a%3c several indications of age have been lost in horses and other %0a%3c beasts of burden, the age is ascertained by the projecting of %0a%3c the teeth, the greyness of the hair in the eyebrows, and the %0a%3c hollow pits that form around them ; at this period the animal %0a%3c is supposed to be about sixteen*^ years old. In the human %0a%3c %0a%3c 38 This is not very uncommon. %0a%3c %0a%3c 2' Not at all an uncommon occurrence. %0a%3c %0a%3c *" Of the second set. %0a%3c %0a%3c *i It is only in the horse and the ass that these indications can be re- %0a%3c lied upon. « Columellares. %0a%3c %0a%3c *3 This has no such effect. %0a%3c %0a%3c The contrary is the case : it will be more prolific. %0a%3c %0a%3c *5 Swine change them just the same as other animals. %0a%3c %0a%3c « By certain appearances in the incisors, the age of ' a horse up to ite %0a%3c twenty-fourth year, or even beyond, may be judged of : the other sigus %0a%3c cannot be so positively relied upon. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Chap. Co.] %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c THE TONGUE. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 61 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c teeth there is a certain venom ; for if they are placed uncoyered %0a%3c before a mirror, they will tarnish its brightness, and they will %0a%3c kill young pigeons while yet unfledged. The other parti- %0a%3c culars relative to the teeth have been already*' mentioned %0a%3c under the head of the generation of man. When teething %0a%3c first commences, the bodies of infants are subject to certain %0a%3c maladies. Those animals which have serrated teeth inflict the %0a%3c most dangerous bites.** %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 65. THE TONGUE ; ANIMALS "WHICH HAVE NO %0a%3c %0a%3c TONGUE. THE NOISE MADE BY FKOGS. THE PALATE. %0a%3c %0a%3c The tongue is not similarly formed in all animals. Ser- %0a%3c pents have a very thin tongue, and three-forked,*'* which they %0a%3c vibrate to and fro : it is of a black colour, and when drawn %0a%3c from out of the mouth, of extraordinary length. The tongue %0a%3c of the lizard is two-forked, and covered with hair.* That of %0a%3c the sea-calf also is twofold,*' but with the serpents it is of the %0a%3c thinness of a hair ; the other animals employ it to lick the %0a%3c parts around the mouth. Fishes have nearly the whole of the %0a%3c tongue adhering to the palate, while in the crocodile the whole %0a%3c of it does adhere thereto : but in the aquatic animals the palate, %0a%3c which is fleshy, performs the duty of the tongue as the organ %0a%3c of taste. In lions, pards, and all the animals of that class, %0a%3c and in cats as well, the tongue is covered with asperities,*^ %0a%3c which overlap each other, and bear a strong resemblance to a %0a%3c rasp. Such being its formation, if the animal licks a man's skin, %0a%3c it will wear it away by making it thinner and thinner ; for %0a%3c which reason it is that the saliva of even a perfectly tame %0a%3c animal, being