ing %0a%3c to -its kind, it is always perfectly at liberty, with man, and %0a%3c him alone, it is often found so strongly tied down by certain %0a%3c veins, that it becomes necessary to cut them. "We find it %0a%3c stated that the pontiff Metellus had a tongue so ill adapted for %0a%3c articulation, that he is generally supposed to have voluntarily %0a%3c submitted to torture for many months, while preparing to %0a%3c pronounce the speech which he was about to make on the de- %0a%3c dication of the temple of Opifera.*" In most persons the %0a%3c tongue is able to articulate with distinctness at about the %0a%3c seventh year ; and many know how to employ it with such re- %0a%3c markable skill, as to be able to imitate the voices of various %0a%3c birds and other animals with the greatest exactness. The other %0a%3c animals have the sense of taste centred in the fore-part of the %0a%3c tongue ; but in man it is situate in the palate as well. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 66. THE TONSILS ; THE UVA ; THE EPIGLOSSIS ; THE %0a%3c %0a%3c AETEKY ; THE GULLET. %0a%3c %0a%3c In man there are tonsils at the root of the tongue ; these in %0a%3c swine are called the glandules. The uvula, which is suspended %0a%3c between them at the extremity of the palate, is found only %0a%3c in man. Beneath this lies a smaller tongue, known by the %0a%3c %0a%3c 5* "Criers." %0a%3c %0a%3c 55 One of the titles of the goddess Fortuna. %0a%3c " Uva," or " grape." %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Chap. 67.] %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c THE NECK. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 63 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c name of " epiglossis,""' but it is wanting in animals that are %0a%3c oviparous. Placed as it is between two passages, the functions %0a%3c of the epiglottis are of a twofold nature. The one of these %0a%3c passages that lies more inward is called the [tracheal] artery %0a%3c and hjads to the lungs and the heart : the epiglottis covers it %0a%3c during the action of eating, that the drink or food may not go %0a%3c