mperor Augustus was sacrificing at Spoletum, upon the first %0a%3c day of his entering on the imperial dignity, in six diff'erent %0a%3c victims the liver was found rolled over within itself, from the %0a%3c very lowest lobe ; and the answer that was given by the diviners %0a%3c was to the effect that, in the course of the j-ear, he would gain %0a%3c a twofold sway. It is of evil omen to find an incision in the %0a%3c head of the entrails, except on occasions of disquietude and %0a%3c alarm ; for then it is significant of cutting all cares, and so %0a%3c putting an end to them. The hares that are found in the %0a%3c vicinity of Briletum ®^ and Thame, and in the Chersonnesus %0a%3c on the Propontis, have a double liver; but, what is very %0a%3c singular, if they are removed to another place, they will lose %0a%3c one of them. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 74. THE GALL ; AVHEEE SITUATE, AND IN WHAT ANIMALS %0a%3c %0a%3c IT IS DOUBLE. ANIMALS WHICH HAVE NO GALL, AND OTHERS %0a%3c IN WHICH IT IS NOT SITUATE IN THE LIVES. %0a%3c %0a%3c In the liver is the gall, which, however, does not exist in %0a%3c every animal. At Chalcis, in Euboea, none of the cattle have %0a%3c it, while in the cattle of the Isle of Naxos, it is of extraordi- %0a%3c nary size, and double, so that to a stranger either of these facts %0a%3c would appear as good as a prodigy. The horse, the mule, the %0a%3c ass, the stag, the roe-buck, the wild boar, the camel, and the %0a%3c dolphin have no gall, but some kinds of rats and mice have it. %0a%3c %0a%3c Plutarch says that it was the "caput," or "head" of the liver that %0a%3c was wanting. M. Marcellus was slain while reconnoitring the Carthaginian %0a%3c camp by night. %0a%3c %0a%3c SI Caligula. 81. of January. %0a%3c %0a%3c ^' By his niece and wife, Agrippina, the mother of Nero. %0a%3c %0a%3c f See B. iv. c. 11. Thame does not seem to he known. Of course, %0a%3c this story about the hares is fabulous. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Chap. 75.] THE PliOPEETIES OF THE GALL. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 69 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Some few men are without it, and such persons enjoy robust %0a%3c health and a long life. There are some authors who say that %0a%3c the gall exists in the horse, not in the liver, but in the paunch, %0a%3c and that in the stag it is situate either in the tail or the %0a%3c intestines ; and that hence it is, that those parts are so bitter %0a%3c that dogs will not touch them. The gall, in fact, is nothing %0a%3c else but the worst parts of the blood purged off, and for this %0a%3c reason it is that it is so bitter : at all events, it is a well-known %0a%3c fact, that no animal has a liver unless it has blood as well. %0a%3c The liver receives the blood from the heart, to which it is %0a%3c united, and then disperses it in the veins. %0a%3c %0a%3c CnAP. 75. THE PKOPEKTIES OF THE GALL. %0a%3c %0a%3c A^Tien the gall is black, it is productive of madness in man, %0a%3c and if it is wholly expelled death will ensue. Hence it is, too, %0a%3c that the word " bile" has been employed by us to characterize %0a%3c a harsh, embittered disposition; so powerful are the effects %0a%3c of this secretion, when it extends its influence to the mind. %0a%3c In addition to this, Avhen it is dispersed over the whole of %0a%3c the body, it deprives the eyes, even, of their natural colour ; %0a%3c and when ejected, will tarnish copper vessels even, rendering %0a%3c everything black with which it comes in contact ; so that no %0a%3c one ought to be surprised that it is the gall which constitutes %0a%3c the venom of serpents. Those o,nimals of Pontus which feed %0a%3c on wormwood have no gall : in the raven, the quail, and the %0a%3c pheasant, the gall-bladder is united to the renal parts, and, on %0a%3c one side only, to the intestines. In many animals, again, it %0a%3c is united onlj' to the intestines, the pigeon, the hawk, and the %0a%3c murena, for example. In some few birds it is situate in the %0a%3c liver ; but it is