llent eating, while those of an animal %0a%3c that has miscarried are very inferior. The ancients called this %0a%3c part by the name of " abdomen," before it grew hard, and %0a%3c were not in the habit of killing swine while in a state of %0a%3c pregnancy. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 85. ANIMALS WHICH HAVE STTET : ANIMALS WHICH DO NOT %0a%3c %0a%3c GKOW FAT. %0a%3c %0a%3c Those among the homed animals which have teeth in one %0a%3c %0a%3c 2 Or bag. %0a%3c %0a%3c 5 "The (principal) place." %0a%3c %0a%3c * Ajasson renders tbis passage : " The effects are fatal when this organ, %0a%3c becoming displaced, absorbs the air." The test is probably corrupt. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 76 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Pliny's natueal histoet. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [Book IX. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c jaw only, and pastern bones on the feet, produce tallow or %0a%3c suet. Those, on the other hand, which are cloven-footed, or %0a%3c have the feet divided into toes, and are without horns, have %0a%3c simple fat only. This fat becomes hard, and when quite %0a%3c cold turns brittle, and is always found at the extremity of the %0a%3c flesh ; while, on the other hand, the fat which lies between the %0a%3c skin and the flesh forms a kind of liquid juice. Some animals %0a%3c naturally do not become fat, such as the hare and the par- %0a%3c tridge, for instance. All fat animals, male as well as female, %0a%3c are mostly barren ; and those which are remarkably fat become %0a%3c old the soonest. All animals have a certain degree of fatness %0a%3c in the eyes. The fat in all animals is devoid of sensation, %0a%3c having neither arteries nor veins. With the greater part of %0a%3c animals, fatness is productive of insensibility ; so much so, %0a%3c indeed, that it has been said, that living swine have been %0a%3c gnawed even by mice. ® It has been even asserted that the fat %0a%3c was drawn off from the body of a son of L. Apronius, a man of %0a%3c consular rank, and that he was thus relieved of a burden which %0a%3c precluded him from moving. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 86. THE MAEKOW : ANIMALS WHICH HAVE NO MAEEOW, ' %0a%3c %0a%3c The marrow seems also to be formed of a similar material ; %0a%3c in the young it is of a reddish colour, but it is white in the %0a%3c aged. It is only found in those bones which are hollow, and %0a%3c not in the tibiae of horses or dogs ; for which reason it is, that %0a%3c when the tibia is broken, the bone will not reunite, a process %0a%3c which is effected ^ by the flow of the marrow. The marrow is %0a%3c of a greasy nature in those animals which have fat, and suetty %0a%3c in those with horns. It is full of nerves, and is found only in %0a%3c the vertebral column' in those animals which have no bones, %0a%3c fishes, for instance. The bear has no marrow ; and the %0a%3c lion has a little only in some few bones of the thighs and %0a%3c the brachia, which are of such extraordinary hardness that %0a%3c sparks may be emitted therefrom, as though from a flint-stone. %0a%3c %0a%3c ' Varro, De Re Eust. B. ii. c. 4, says that he saw an instance of this in %0a%3c Arcadia. %0a%3c %0a%3c s This is not the case. %0a%3c %0a%3c ■I There is no similarity whatever between the spinal marrow and that %0a%3c which is found in the other bones. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Cliap. 88.] %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c THE NEBTES. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 77 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 87. BONES AND FISH-BONES: ANIMALS WHICH HAVE %0a%3c %0a%3c NEITHER. CABTIXAGES. %0a%3c %0a%3c The bones are hard, also, in those animals ^ which do not %0a%3c grow fat ; those of the ass are used by musicians for making %0a%3c flutes. Dolphins have bones, and not ordinary fish-bones ; for %0a%3c they are viviparous. Serpents, on the other hand, have bones %0a%3c like those of fish. Among aquatic animals, the mollusks %0a%3c have no bones, but the body is surrounded with circles of %0a%3c flesh, as in the ssepia and the cuttle-fish, for instance ; insects, %0a%3c also, are said to be equally destitute of bones. Among aquatic %0a%3c animals, those which are cartilaginous have marrow in the %0a%3c vertebral column ; the sea-calf has cartilages, and no bones. %0a%3c The ears also, and the nostrils in all animals, when remarkably %0a%3c prominent, are made flexible by a remarkable provision of %0a%3c Nature, in order that they may not be broken. When cartilage %0a%3c is once broken, it will not unite ; nor will bone, when cut, grow %0a%3c again, except in beasts of burden, between the hoof and the %0a%3c pastern. %0a%3c %0a%3c Man increases in height till his twenty-first year, after %0a%3c which he fills out ; bul^ it is more particularly when he first %0a%3c arrives at the age of puberty that he seems to have untied a %0a%3c sort of knot in his existence, and this especially when he has %0a%3c been overtaken by illness. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 88. — THE NEEVE : ANIMALS WHICH HAVE NONE. %0a%3c %0a%3c The nerves ^ take their rise at the heart, and even surround %0a%3c it in the ox ; they have the same nature and principle as the %0a%3c marrow. In all animals they are fastened to the lubricous %0a%3c surface of the bones, and so serve to fasten those knots in the %0a%3c body which are known as articulations or joints, sometimes %0a%3c lying between them, sometimes surrounding them, and some- %0a%3c times running from one to another ; in one place they are %0a%3c long and round, and in another broad, according as the ne- %0a%3c cessity of each case may demand. When cut, they will not %0a%3c %0a%3c * The hare and the partridge, for instance. %0a%3c %0a%3c ' There is considerable doubt what the ancients exactly meant by tlie %0a%3c "ncrvi ;" and wliether, in fact, they had any definite idea of " nerves," in %0a%3c our acceptation of the word. Pliny here expresses the opinions entertained %0a%3c by Aristotle. " Tendons," or " sinews," would almost appear to be the proper %0a%3c translation of the word. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 78 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c PLIirr'S NATUEAL HISTOET. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [Book XI %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c reunite, and if wounded, it is wonderful what excruciating %0a%3c pain they cause ; though, if completely cut asunder, they are %0a%3c productive of none whatever. Some animals are destitute of %0a%3c nerves, fish, for instance, the bodies of which are united by %0a%3c arteries, though even these are not to be found in_ the mol- %0a%3c lusks. Wherever there are nerves found, it is the inner ones %0a%3c that contract the limb, and the outer ones that extend it. %0a%3c %0a%3c Among the nerves lie concealed the arteries, which are %0a%3c so many passages for the spirit ; and upon these float the veins, %0a%3c as conduits for the blood. The pulsation of the arteries is %0a%3c more especially perceptible on the surface of the limbs, and %0a%3c afford indications of nearly every disease, being either statio- %0a%3c nary, quickened, or retarded, conformably to certain measures %0a%3c and metrical laws, which depend on the age of the patient, and %0a%3c which have been described with remarkable skill by Hero- %0a%3c philus, who has been looked upon as a prophet in the wondrous %0a%3c art of medicine. These indications, however, have been %0a%3c hitherto neglected, in consequence of their remarkable subtilty %0a%3c and minuteness, though, at the same time, it is by the observa- %0a%3c tion of the pulse, as being fast or slow, that the health of the %0a%3c body, as regulating life, is ascertained. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 89. THE AETERIES; THE VEINS: ANIMALS WITHOTTr %0a%3c %0a%3c AETEEIES OE VlilNS. THE BLOOD AND THE SWEAT. ' %0a%3c %0a%3c The arteries are destitute of sensation, for they are devoid of %0a%3c blood. They do not, all of them, however, contain the vital %0a%3c spirit, and when one of them has been cut, it is only that part %0a%3c of the body that is reduced to a torpid state. Eirds have %0a%3c neither veins nor arteries, which is the case also with serpents, %0a%3c tortoises, and lizards ; and they have but a very small propor- %0a%3c tion of blood. The veins, which are dispersed beneath the %0a%3c whole skin in filaments of extreme thinness, terminate with %0a%3c such remarkable fineness, that the blood is able to penetrate no %0a%3c further, or, indeed, anything else, except an extremely subtle %0a%3c humour which oozes forth from the skin in innumerable small %0a%3c drops, and is known to us as " sweat." The knot, and place %0a%3c of union of the veins, is the navel. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 90. (38.) — ANIMALS, THE BLOOD OV WHICH COAGULATES %0a%3c WITH THE GEEATEST EAPIDITT : OTHEE ANIMALS, THE BLOOD %0a%3c OF WHICH DOES NOT COAGULATE. ANIMALS WHICH HAVE THE %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Chap. 91.] %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c ANIMALS SOMETIMES WITHOUT BLOOD. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 79 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c THICKEST BLOOD : THOSE THE BLOOD OP WHICH IS THE THIN- %0a%3c NEST : ANIMALS WHICH HAVE NO BLOOD. %0a%3c %0a%3c Those animals in whicti the blood is more abundant and of %0a%3c an unctuous nature, are irascible ; it is darker in males than %0a%3c in females, and in the young than in the aged : the blood of the %0a%3c lower extremities is the thickest. There is great vitality, too, %0a%3c in the blood, and when it is discharged from the body, it %0a%3c carries the life with it : it is not sensible, however, of touch. %0a%3c Those animals in which the blood is the thickest are the most %0a%3c courageous, and those in which it is the thinnest the most %0a%3c intelligent; while those, again, which have little or no blood are %0a%3c the most timorous of all. The blood of the bull coagulates and %0a%3c hardens the most sjjeedily of all, and hence it is so particu- %0a%3c larly deadly when drunk. On the other hand, the blood of %0a%3c the wild boar, the stag, the roe-buck, and oxen of all kinds, %0a%3c does not coagulate. Blood is of the richest quality in the ass, %0a%3c and the poorest in man. Those animals which have more than %0a%3c four feet have no blood. In animals which are very fat, the %0a%3c blood is less abundant than in others, being soaked up by the %0a%3c fat. Man is the only creature from which the blood flows at %0a%3c the nostrils ; some persons bleed at one nostril only, some at %0a%3c both, while others again void blood by the lower " parts. %0a%3c Many persons discharge blood from the mouth at stated periods, %0a%3c such, for instance, as Macrinus Viscus, lately, a man of prae- %0a%3c torian dignity, and Volusius Saturninus,'- the Prefect of the %0a%3c City, who every year did the same, and yet lived to beyond %0a%3c ninety. The blood is the only substance in the body that is %0a%3c sensible of any temporary increase, for a larger quantity will %0a%3c come from the victims if they happen to have drunk just %0a%3c before tliey arc sacrificed. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 91. ANIMALS WHICH ARE WITHOUT BLOOD AT CEKTAIN %0a%3c %0a%3c PEKIODS Oli" THE YEAR. %0a%3c %0a%3c Those animals which conceal themselves'^ at certain periods %0a%3c of the year, as already mentioned, have no blood at those times, %0a%3c with the exception, indeed, of some very small drops about the %0a%3c %0a%3c See B. xxviii. c. 41. %0a%3c " 111 allusion, probably, to hgemorilioids, or piles. %0a%3c 1^ See B. vii. c. I'i. ^■^ Bears, dormice, serpents, &c. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 80 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c flint's NATtTEAL HISTOET. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [Book XI, %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c heart. A marvellous dispensation of Nature ! and very similar %0a%3c to that witnessed in man, where the blood is sensible of various %0a%3c modifications from the slightest causes ; for not only, similarly %0a%3c to the bile, does it rush upwards to the face, but it serves also %0a%3c to indicate the various tendencies of the mind, by depicting %0a%3c shame, anger, and fear, in many ways, either by the paleness %0a%3c of the features or their unusual redness ; as, in fact, the red- %0a%3c ness of anger and the blush of modesty are quite different %0a%3c things. It is a well-known fact, that when a man is in fear, %0a%3c the blood takes to flight and disappears, and that many per- %0a%3c sons have been pierced through the body without losing one %0a%3c drop of blood ; a thing, however, which is only the case with %0a%3c man. But as to those animals which we have already men- %0a%3c tioned as changing'* colour, they derive that colour from the %0a%3c reflection'^ of other objects ; while, on the other hand, man is %0a%3c the only one that has the elements which cause these changes %0a%3c centred in himself. All diseases, as well as death, tend to %0a%3c absorb the blood. %0a%3c %0a%3c OHAP. 92. (39.) — WHETHER THE BLOOD IS THE PEINOIPLE OP %0a%3c %0a%3c LIFE. %0a%3c %0a%3c There are some persons who are of opinion that the fineness %0a%3c of the wit does not depend upon the thinness of the blood, but %0a%3c that animals are more or less stupid in proportion to the skin %0a%3c or other coverings of the body, as the oyster and the tortoise, %0a%3c for instance : that the hide of the ox and the bristles of the hog, %0a%3c in fact, ofler a resistance to the fine and penetrating powers of %0a%3c the air, and leave no passage for its transmission in a pure %0a%3c and liquid state. The same, they say, is the case, too, with %0a%3c men, when the skin is very thick or callous, and so excludes %0a%3c the air. Just as if, indeed, the crocodile was not equally re- %0a%3c markable for the hardness of its skin and its extreme cunning. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 93. THE HIDE OF ANIMALS. %0a%3c %0a%3c The hide, too, of the hippopotamus is so thick, that lances," %0a%3c even, are turned from it, and yet this animal has the intelligence %0a%3c to administer certain medicaments to itself. The hide, too, of %0a%3c %0a%3c The polypus and the chameleon. %0a%3c See B. viii. cc. 51, 52. %0a%3c 16 Walking-sticks are still made of it. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Chap. 94.] %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c TUE IIAiE; ETC. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 81 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c the elephant makes bucklers that are quite impenetrable, and %0a%3c yet to it is ascribed a degree of intelligence superior to that of %0a%3c any quadruped. The skin itself is entirely devoid of sen- %0a%3c sation, and more particularly that of the head ; wherever it %0a%3c is found alone, and unaccompanied with flesh, if wounded, it %0a%3c will not unite, as in the cheek and on the eyelid,'* for %0a%3c instance. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 94. THE HAIR AND THE COVERING OF THE SKIN. %0a%3c %0a%3c Those animals which are viviparous, have hair ; those which %0a%3c are oviparous, have feathers, scales, or a shell, like the tor- %0a%3c toise ; or else a purple skin, like the serpent. The lower part %0a%3c of all feathers is hollow : if cut, they will not grow again, but if %0a%3c pulled out, they will shoot afresh. Insects fly by the aid of a %0a%3c frail membrane ; the wings of the fish'" called the "swallow" are %0a%3c moistened in the sea, while those of the bat which frequents %0a%3c our houses are dry ; the wings of this last animal have certain %0a%3c articulations as well. The hairs that issue from a thick skin %0a%3c are rough, while those on females are of a finer quality. Those %0a%3c found on the horse's mane are more abundant, which is the %0a%3c case also with the shoulders of the lion. The dasypus has %0a%3c hair in the inside of the mouth even and under the feet, two %0a%3c features Avhich Trogus has also attributed to the hare ; from %0a%3c Avhich the same author concludes that hairy men are the most %0a%3c prone to lust. The most hairy of all animals is the hare. %0a%3c Man is the only creature that has hair as the mark of puberty ; %0a%3c and a person who is devoid of this, whether male or female, %0a%3c is sure to be sterile. The hair of man is partly born with %0a%3c him, and in part produced after his birth. The last kind of hair %0a%3c will not grow upon eunuchs, though that which has been born %0a%3c with thera does not fall ofl"; Avhich is the case also with %0a%3c women, in a great degree. Still however, there have been %0a%3c women known to be afflicted Avith falling off' of the hair, just %0a%3c as some are to be seen with a fine down on the face, after the %0a%3c cessation of the menstrual discharge. In some men the hair %0a%3c that mostly shoots forth after birth will not grow spontane- %0a%3c ously. The hair of quadrupeds comes off every year, and %0a%3c %0a%3c '■^ As ah-cadv mentioned, this is not the fact. %0a%3c " See B. ix. c. 43. %0a%3c %0a%3c VOL. 111. O %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 82 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Flint's natur^ll uistort. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [Book XI. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c grows again. That of the head in man grows the fastest, and %0a%3c next to it the hair of the beard. When cut, the hairs shoot, %0a%3c not from the place Avhere they have been cut, as is the case %0a%3c with grass, but at the root. The hair grows quickly in cer- %0a%3c tain diseases, phthisis more particularly ; it grows also with %0a%3c rapidity in old age, and on the body after death. In persons %0a%3c of a libidinous tendency the hair that is produced at birth falls %0a%3c off more speedily, while that which is afterwards produced %0a%3c grows with the greatest rapidity. In quadrupeds, the hair %0a%3c grows thicker in old age ; but on those with wool, it becomes %0a%3c thinner. Those quadrupeds which have thick hair on the %0a%3c back, have the belly quite smooth. From the hides of oxen, %0a%3c and that of the bull more especially, glue is extracted by %0a%3c boiling. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 95. THE PAPS : BIRDS THAT HAVE PAPS. EEMABKABLK %0a%3c %0a%3c FACTS CONNECTED WITH THE DUGS OF ANIMALS. %0a%3c %0a%3c Man is the only male among animals that has nipples, all %0a%3c the rest having mere marks only in place of them. Among %0a%3c female animals even, the only ones that have mammae on the %0a%3c breast are those which can nurture their young, l^o oviparous %0a%3c animal has mammae, and those only have milk that are vivi- %0a%3c parous ; the bat being the only winged animal that has it. As %0a%3c for the stories that they tell, about the screech-owl ejecting milk %0a%3c from its teats upon the lips of infants, I look upon it as utterly %0a%3c fabulous : from ancient times the name " strix,"^° I am aware, %0a%3c has been employed in maledictions, but I do not think it is %0a%3c well ascertained what bird is really meant by that name. %0a%3c %0a%3c (40.) The female ass is troubled with pains in the teats %0a%3c after it has foaled, and it is for that reason that at the end of %0a%3c six months it weans its young ; while the mare suckles its %0a%3c young for nearly the whole year. The solid-hoofed animals %0a%3c do not bear more than two young ones at a time : they all of %0a%3c them have two paps, and nowhere but between the iiind legs. %0a%3c Animals with cloven feet and with horns, such as the cow, for %0a%3c instance, have four paps, similarly situate, sheep and goats two. %0a%3c %0a%3c 20 It is not improbable that, under this name, some kind of large vam- %0a%3c pire bat was meant ; but, as Pliny says, it is impossible to arrive at any %0a%3c certain knowledge on the subject. 'I'he best account given of the strix is %0a%3c that in Ovid's Fasti, B. vi. The name was given opprobiously to supposed %0a%3c witches, the "foul and midnight hags" of Shakspeare. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Chap. 96.] %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c THE MILK. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 83 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Th ose which, produce a more nunierous progeny, and those %0a%3c which have toes on the feet, have a greater number of paps dis- %0a%3c tributed in a double row all along the belly, such as the %0a%3c sow, for instance ; the better sorts have twelve, the more %0a%3c common ones two less : the same is the case also with tlie %0a%3c female of the dog. Other animals, again, have four paps situate %0a%