bly corrupt. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c S6 PLTJJ^'S NATUnAL niSTOUT. [Book XI. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 98. (43.) — DIFFERENCES OF THE MEMBEES OP MAN FKOil %0a%3c THOSE OF OTHEE ANIMALS. %0a%3c %0a%3c Of all the terrestrial animals, man is the only biped : he is %0a%3c also the only one that has a throat, and shoulders, or " hu- %0a%3c meri," parts in other animals known by the name of " armi." %0a%3c Man, too, is the only animal that has the " ulna," or elbow. %0a%3c Those animals which are provided with hands, have flesh %0a%3c only on the interior of them,- the cater part consisting of sinews %0a%3c and skin. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 99. THE FINGEES, THE AEMS. %0a%3c %0a%3c Some persons have six fingers on the hands. "We read that %0a%3c C. Horatius, a man of patrician rank, had two daughters, who %0a%3c for this reason had the name of " Sedigitaj and we find %0a%3c mention made of Volcatius Sedigitus,^* as a famous poet. %0a%3c The fingers of man have three joints, the thumb only two, %0a%3c it bending in an opposite direction to all the other fingers. %0a%3c Viewed by itself, the movement of the thumb has a sidelong %0a%3c direction, and it is much thicker than the rest of the fingers. %0a%3c The little finger is equal in length to the thumb, and two others %0a%3c are also equal in length, the middle finger being the longest %0a%3c of all. Those quadrupeds which live by rapine have five toes %0a%3c on the fore feet, and four on the hinder ones. The lion, the %0a%3c wolf, and the dog, with some few others, have five claws %0a%3c on the hind feet, one of which hangs down near the joint of the %0a%3c leg. The other animals, also, which are of smaller size, have %0a%3c five toes. The two arms are not always equal in length : it %0a%3c is a well-known fact, that, in the school of gladiators belong- %0a%3c ing to Caius Cassar,^* the Thracian Studiosus had the right %0a%3c arm longer than the left. Some animals also use their fore- %0a%3c paws to perform the duties of hands, and employ them in %0a%3c conveying food to the mouth as they sit, the squirrel, for in- %0a%3c stance. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 100. (44.) EESEMBLANCE OF THE APE TO MAN. %0a%3c %0a%3c As to the various kinds of apes, they ofier a perfect resem- %0a%3c %0a%3c He wrote a poem, in which the principal Latin (Iramatists are enume- %0a%3c rated, in the order of merit. A. Gellius, B. xt. c. 24, has preserved a por- %0a%3c tion of it. %0a%3c 25 Germanicus. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Chap. 102.] THE KNEES AND THE HAMS. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 87 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c y)lancc to man in the face, the nostrils, the ears, and the eye- %0a%3c lids ; being the onl)' quadrupeds, in fact, that have eyehishes on %0a%3c the lower eyelid. They have mammee also on the breast, arms %0a%3c and legs, which bend in opposite directions, and nails upon %0a%3c the hands and fingers, the middle finger being the longest. %0a%3c They differ somewhat from man in the feet ; which, like the %0a%3c hands, are of remarkable length, and have a print similar to %0a%3c that of the palm of our hand. They have a thumb also, and %0a%3c articulations similar to those in man. The males differ from %0a%3c man in the sexual parts only, while all the internal viscera %0a%3c exactly resemble those of man. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 101. (45.) THE NAILS. %0a%3c %0a%3c It is generally supposed that the nails are the terminations %0a%3c of the sinews. All animals whicli have fingers luive nails us %0a%3c well. In the ape they are long and overlapping,^'* like a tile, %0a%3c while in man they are broad : they will grow even after death. %0a%3c In the beasts of prey they are hooked, Avhile in others, such %0a%3c as the dog, for instance, they are straight, with the exception, %0a%3c indeed, of the one which is attached to the leg in most of %0a%3c them. All the animals which have feet [and not hoots], have; %0a%3c toes as well, except the elephant ; he, also, wouhl appear to %0a%3c have toes, five in number, but rudely developed, undivided, %0a%3c and hardly distinct from one another, bearing a nearer resem- %0a%3c blance, in fact, to hoofs than to claws. In the elephant the %0a%3c fore-feet are the largest, and in the hind-feet there are sliort %0a%3c joints. This animal is able, also, to bend the hams inward %0a%3c like a man, while in all the others the joints of the hinder %0a%3c legs bend in a contrary direction to those of the fore ones. %0a%3c Those animals which are viviparous bend the fore-leg forward, %0a%3c while the joint of the hind-leg is directed backward, %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 102.^ — THE KNEE^ AND THE HAMS. %0a%3c %0a%3c In man the knee and the elbow bend contrary ways ; tho %0a%3c same is the case, too, with the bear and the ape, and it is for %0a%3c this reason that they are not so swift of foot as other ani- %0a%3c mals. Those quadrupeds which are oviparous, such as the %0a%3c crocodile and the lizard, bend the knee of the fore-leg back- %0a%3c s'' This seems to be the meaning of " imbricatus." %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c PLtNi' S NAIU'RAL IllSIOIiV. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [liuuk XI. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c v.-avds, and that of the hind-L^g forwards ; their thighs art- %0a%3c placed on them obliquely, in a similar manner to a man's %0a%3c thumb; which is the case idso with the multipede insects, the %0a%3c liind-legs only excepted of such as leap. Birds, like quadru- %0a%3c peds, have the joints of the wings bending forwards, but tlioso %0a%3c of the legs backwards. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 103. PARTS OF TnK HtniAN BODY TO WUICri CEItTAIX %0a%3c %0a%3c KELIGIOUS IDEAS ARE ATTACHED. %0a%3c %0a%3c In accordance with the usages of various nations, certain %0a%3c religious ideas have been attached to the knees. It is thu %0a%3c knees that suppliants clasp, and it is to these that they extend %0a%3c their hands ; it is the knees that they worship like so many %0a%3c altars, as it were ; perhaps, because in them is centred the %0a%3c vital strength. For in the joint of eitlier knee, the right %0a%3c as well as the left, there is on the fore-side of each a certain %0a%3c empty space, which bears a strong resemblance to a mouth, and %0a%3c through which, like the throat, if it is once pierced, the vital %0a%3c powers escape.^'' There are also certain religious ideas at- %0a%3c tached to other parts of che body, as is testified in raising tlie %0a%3c hack of the right hand to the lips, and extending it as a token %0a%3c of good faith. It was the custom of the ancient Greeks, when %0a%3c in the act of supplication, to touch the chin. The seat of the %0a%3c memorj' lies in the lower part of the ear, which we touch %0a%3c when we summon a witness to depose upon memory to an %0a%3c arrest.''® The seat, too, of Xemesis^" lies behind the right ear, a %0a%3c goddess which has never yet found a Latin name, no, not in tlio %0a%3c Capitol even. It is to this part that we apply the finger next %0a%3c the little finger, after touching the mouth with it, Avhen we %0a%3c silently ask pardon of the gods for having let slip an indiscreet %0a%3c word. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 104. VARICOSE VEINS. %0a%3c %0a%3c ilen only, in general, have varicose veins in the legs, wo- %0a%3c men but very rarely. "We are informed by Oppius, that %0a%3c %0a%3c 3'' Though wounds in the knee are highly dangerous, death does not ««- %0a%3c eessarily ensue. %0a%3c %0a%3c "'8 Of another person, who had thus forfeited his bail. It was the cus- %0a%3c tom to touch the car of the attesting witness. %0a%3c %0a%3c S3 The god(iess of retribution. See R. xxviii. c. o, where he makes fur- %0a%3c ther mention of her statue in the Capitol, %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Chap. 106.]. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c HOOFS. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 89 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c C. ifarius, who was seven times consul, was the only man ever %0a%3c known to be able to have them extracted in a standing- po- %0a%3c sition. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 105. THE GAIT, THE FEET, THE LEGS. %0a%3c %0a%3c All animals take a right-hand direction when they first %0a%3c begin to walk, and lie down on the left side. While the other %0a%3c animals walk just as it may happen, the lion only and the %0a%3c camel walk foot by foot, or in such a way that the left foot %0a%3c never passes the right, but always comes behind it. Men have %0a%3c the largest feet ; in every kind of animal the female has the %0a%3c smallest. Man only" has calves, and flesh upon the legs : we %0a%3c find it stated by authors, however, that there was once an %0a%3c Egyptian who had no calves on his legs. All men, too, with %0a%3c some few exceptions, have a sole to the foot. It is from these %0a%3c exceptional cases that persons have obtained the names of %0a%3c Plancus,'" Plautus, Punsa, and Scaurus ; just as, from the mal- %0a%3c formation of the legs, we find persons called Varus,^^ Vacia, and %0a%3c Vatinius, all which blemishes are to be seen in quadrupeds %0a%3c also. Animals which have no horns have a solid hoof, from %0a%3c which circumstance it is used by them as a weapon of off'ence, %0a%3c in place of horns ; such animals as these are also des- %0a%3c titute of pastern bones, but those which have cloven hoofs %0a%3c have them ; w'hile those, again, which have toes have none, %0a%3c nor are they ever found iu the fore-feet of animals. The %0a%3c camel has pastern bones like those of the ox, but somewhat %0a%3c smaller, the feet being cloven, with a slight line of division, %0a%3c and having a fleshy sole, like that of the bear : hence it is, %0a%3c that in a long journey, the animal becomes fatigued, and the %0a%3c foot cracks, if it is not shod. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. lOG, (46.) HOOFS. %0a%3c %0a%3c The horn of the hoof grows again in no animals except %0a%3c beasts of burden. The swine in some places in lUyricum %0a%3c have solid hoofs. Nearly all the horned animals are cloven- %0a%3c footed, no animal having solid hoofs and two horns. The %0a%3c Indian ass is only a one-horned animal, and the oryx is both %0a%3c %0a%3c The frog is, in some measure, an exception. %0a%3c %0a%3c Or "flat-foot," "splay-foot," "large-foot," and "club-footed." %0a%3c %0a%3c Words meaning " kuock-kneed," "bow-legged," and "wry-legged." %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 90 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c PLlXl's KATDEAL niiSTOKY. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [15ook XI. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c one-horned and cloven-footed. The Indian ass^' is the %0a%3c only solid-hoofed animal that has pastern-bones. As to %0a%3c swine, they are looked upon as a sort of mongrel race, with a %0a%3c mixture of both kinds, and hence it is that their ankle-bones %0a%3c are so misshapen. Those authors who have imagined that %0a%3c man has similar pastern-bones, are easily to be confuted. The %0a%3c Ij-nx is the only one among the animals that have the feet %0a%3c divided into toes, that has anything bearing a resemblance %0a%3c to a pastern-bone ; while with the lion it is more crooked %0a%3c still. The great pastern-bone is straight, and situate in the %0a%3c joints of the foot; it projects outwards in a convex protube- %0a%3c rance, and is held fast in its vertebration by certain liga- %0a%3c ments. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 107. (47.) THE FEET OF BIEDS. %0a%3c %0a%3c Among birds, some have the feet divided into toes, while %0a%3c others, again, are broad and flatfooted — in others, which par- %0a%3c take of the intermediate nature of both, the toes are divided, %0a%3c with a wide space between them. All birds, however, have %0a%3c four toes — three in front, and one on the heel ; this last, how- %0a%3c ever, is wanting in some that have long legs. The iynx*' is %0a%3c the only bird that has two toes on each side of the leg. This %0a%3c bird also protrudes a long tongue similar to that of the serpent, %0a%3c and it can turn the neck quite round and look backwards ; if %0a%3c has great talons, too, like those of the jackdaw. Some of the %0a%3c heavier birds have spurs also upon the legs; but none of %0a%3c those have them which have crooked talons as well. The %0a%3c long-footed birds, as they fly, extend the legs towards the tail, %0a%3c while those that have short legs hold them contracted close to %0a%3c the middle of the body. Those authors who deny that there %0a%3c is any bird without feet, assert that those even which are %0a%3c called apodes,^* are not without them, as also the oce, and the %0a%3c drepanis,** which last is a bird but very rarely seen. Ser- %0a%3c pents, too, have been seen with feet like those of the goose. %0a%3c %0a%3c The rhinoceros. %0a%3c " Or wryneck. « See B. x. c. 5. %0a%3c %0a%3c Supposed to be the Hirundo apiisof Linnaeus. Of the "oce" nothing %0a%3c is known ; indeed, ths reading is very doubtful. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Chap. 100.] %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c THE SEXUAL PAKTS. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 91 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 108. (48.) THE FEET OF ANIMALS, FROM TTirSE HATING %0a%3c %0a%3c TWO FEET TO THOSE WITH A HUNDUED. DWAHFi. %0a%3c %0a%3c Among insects, those which have hard eyes have the fore- %0a%3c feet long, in order that from time to time they may rub the %0a%3c eyes with their feet, as we frequently see done by flies. The %0a%3c insects which have long hind-feet are able to leap, the locust, %0a%3c for instance. All these insects have six feet : and some of the %0a%3c spiders have two very long feet in addition. They have, all %0a%3c of them, three joints. We have already" stated that marine %0a%3c insects have eight feet, such as the polypus, the ssepia, the %0a%3c cuttle-fish, and the crab, animals which move their arms in a %0a%3c contrary direction to their feet, which last they move around %0a%3c as well as obliquely : they are the only animals the feet of %0a%3c which have a rounded form. Other insects have two feet to %0a%3c regulate their movements ; in the crab, and in that only, these %0a%3c duties are performed by four. The land animals which exceed %0a%3c this number of feet, as most of the worms,*® never have fewer %0a%3c than twelve feet, and some, indeed, as many as a hundred. %0a%3c The number of feet is never uneven in any animal. Among %0a%3c the solid-hoofed animals, the legs are of their proper length %0a%3c from the moment of their birth, after which they may with %0a%3c more propriety be said to extend themselves than to increase %0a%3c in growth : hence it is, that in infancy they are able to scratch %0a%3c their ears with the hind feet, a thing which, when they grow %0a%3c older, they are not able to do, because their increase of growth %0a%3c affects only the superficies of the body. It is for the same %0a%3c reason also, that they are only able to graze at first by bending %0a%3c the knees, until such time as the neck has attained its proper %0a%3c length. %0a%3c %0a%3c (49.) There are dwarfs to be found among all animals, and %0a%3c among birds even. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 109. THE SEXTTAL PARTS. HERMAPHRODITES. %0a%3c %0a%3c "We have already spoken sufficiently** at length of those ani- %0a%3c mals, the males of which have the sexual parts behind. In %0a%3c the wolf, the fox, the weasel, and the ferret, these parts are %0a%3c bony ; and it is the genitals of the last-mentioned animal %0a%3c %0a%3c B. ix. c. 44. %0a%3c %0a%3c *8 He evidently means insects of the centipede class. See B. xxix. c. 39. %0a%3c " B. X. c. 83. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 92 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c pltkt's nattthal nisxonT. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [Book XI. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c that supply the principal remedies for calciilus in the human %0a%3c bladder. It is said also that the genitals of the bear are %0a%3c turned into a hornT substance the moment it dies. Among %0a%3c the peoples of the East the very best bow-strings are those %0a%3c which are made of the member of the camel. These parts also, %0a%3c among different nations, are made the object of certain usages'" %0a%3c and religious observances ; and the Galli/^ the priests of the %0a%3c Mother of the gods, are in the habit of castrating themselves, %0a%3c without any dangerous results. On the other hand, there is %0a%3c in some few w^omen a monstrous resemblance to the male con- %0a%3c formation, while hermaphrodites appear to partake of the %0a%3c nature of both. Instances of this last conformation were %0a%3c seen in quadrupeds in Nero's reign, and for the first time, I %0a%3c imagine ; for he ostentatiously paraded hermaphrodite horses %0a%3c yoked to his car, which had been found in the territory of %0a%3c the Treviri, in Gaul ; as if, indeed, it was so remarkably fine a %0a%3c sight to behold the ruler of the earth seated in a chariot dra^^-n %0a%3c by monstrosities ! %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 110. — rnE TESTES — THE THKEE CLASSES OP EUNUCHS. %0a%3c %0a%3c In sheep and cattle the testes hang down to the legs, while %0a%3c in the boar they are knit up close to the body. In the dolphin %0a%3c they are very long, and are concealed in the lower part of the %0a%3c belly. In the elephant, also, they are quite concealed. In %0a%3c oviparous animals they adhere to the interior of the loins: %0a%3c these animals are the most speedy in the venereal congress. %0a%3c Fishes and serpents have no testes, but in place of them they %0a%3c have two-veins, which run from the renal region to the genitals. %0a%3c The bird known as the " buteo,"*^ has three testes. Man is %0a%3c the only creature in which the testes are ever broken, either %0a%3c accidentally or by some natural malady ; those -who are thus %0a%3c afflicted form a third class of half men, in addition to her- %0a%3c maphrodites and eunuchs. In all species of animals the male %0a%3c is more courageous than the female, with the exception of the %0a%3c panther and the bear. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 111. (50.) THE TAILS OP ANIMALS. %0a%3c %0a%3c Nearly all the animals, both viviparous as well as oviparous, %0a%3c %0a%3c 5" Such as circumcision among the Jews. %0a%3c 51 See B. XXXV. c. 46. %0a%3c %0a%3c " Probably the buzzard; from this story also called the "triorchis." %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Chap. 112.] DIFFEEEKT VOICES OF ANIMALS. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 93 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c with the exception of man and the ape, have tails in propor- %0a%3c tion to the necessities of the body. In animals with bristles %0a%3c the tail is bare, as in the boar, for instance. In those that are %0a%3c shaggy, it is small, such as the bear ; while in those animals %0a%3c that have long hair, the tail is long also, the horse, for in- %0a%3c stance. The tail of a lizard or serpent, if cut off, wall grow %0a%3c again. The tail governs the movements of the fish like a %0a%3c rudder, and turning from side to side, to the right or to the %0a%3c left, impels it onwards, acting in some degree like an oar. %0a%3c A double tail is sometimes found in lizards. In oxen, the %0a%3c stalk of the tail is of remarkable length, and is covered with %0a%3c rough hair at the extremitj-. In the ass, too, it is longer than %0a%3c in the horse, but in beasts of burden it is covered with bristly %0a%3c hairs. The tail of the lion, at the extremity, is like that of %0a%3c the ox and the field-mouse ; but this is not the case with the %0a%3c panther. In the fox and the wolf it is covered with long %0a%3c luiir, as in sheep, in w^hich it is longer also. In swine, the %0a%3c tail is curled ; among dogs, those that are mongrels carry it %0a%3c close beneath the belly. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 112. (51.) — THE DIFFERENT VOICES OF ANIMALS. %0a%3c %0a%3c Aristotle^- is of opinion that no animal has a voice which %0a%3c does not respire, and that hence it is that there is no voice in %0a%3c insects, but only a noise, through the circulation of the air in %0a%3c the interior, and its resounding, by reason of its compression. %0a%3c 8ome insects, again, he says, emit a sort of humming noise, %0a%3c such as the bee, for instance ; others a shrill, long-drawn note, %0a%3c like the grasshopper, the two cavities beneath the thorax re- %0a%3c ceiving the air, which, meeting a moveable membrane within, %0a%3c emits a sound by the attrition. — Also that flies, bees, and %0a%3c other insects of that nature, are only heard while they are %0a%3c flying, and cease to be heard the moment they settle, and that %0a%3c the sound which they emit proceeds from the friction and the %0a%3c air within them, and not from any act of respiration. At all %0a%3c events, it is generally believed that the locust emits a sound %0a%3c by rubbing together the wdngs and thighs, and that among %0a%3c the aquatic animals the scallop makes a certain noise as it %0a%3c flies.** Mollusks, however, and the testaceous animals have no %0a%3c voice and emit no sounds. As for the other fishes, although %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c " Hist. Anim. B. iv. c. 9. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 53 See B. ix. c. 52. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 94 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c pliny's natural history. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Book XI %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c they are destitute of lungs and the tracheal artery, they are %0a%3c not entirely without the power of emitting certain sounds : it %0a%3c is only a mere joke to say that the noise which they makeij %0a%3c produced by grating their teeth together. The tish, too, that %0a%3c is found in the river Acheloiis, and is known as the boar-fish," %0a%3c makes a grunting noise, as do some others which we have pre- %0a%3c viously** mentioned. The oviparous animals hiss: in the %0a%3c serpent this hissing is prolonged, in the tortoise it is short and %0a%3c abrupt. Frogs make a peculiar noise of their own, as already %0a%3c stated;^ unless, indeed, this, too, is to be looked upon as a %0a%3c matter of doubt ; but their noise originates in the mouth, and %0a%3c not in the thorax. Still, however, in reference to this subject, %0a%3c the nature of the various localities exercises a very considerable %0a%3c influence, for in Macedonia, it is said, the frogs are dumb, and %0a%3c the same in reference to the wild boars there. Among birds, %0a%3c the smaller ones chirp and twitter the most, and more espe- %0a%3c cially about the time of pairing. Others, again, exercise their %0a%3c voice while figliting, the quail, for instance ; others before %0a%3c they begin to fight, such as the partridge ; and others M'hen %0a%3c they have gained the victory, the dunghill cock, for instance, %0a%3c The males in these species have a peculiar note of their own, %0a%3c while in others, the nightingale for example, the male has %0a%3c the same note as the female. %0a%3c %0a%3c Some birds sing all the year round, others only at certain %0a%3c times of the year, as we have already mentioned when speak- %0a%3c ing of them individually. The elephant produces a noise %0a%3c similar to that of sneezing, by the aid of the mouth, and in- %0a%3c dependently of the nostrils ; but by means of the nostrils it %0a%3c emits a sound similar to the hoarse braying of a trumpet %0a%3c It is only in the bovine race that the voice of the female is the %0a%3c deepest, it being in all other kinds of animals more shrill than %0a%3c that of the male ; it is the same also with the male of the %0a%3c human race when castrated. The infant at its birth is never %0a%3c heard to utter a cry before it has entirely left the uterus: %0a%3c it begins to speak at the end of the first year. A son of %0a%3c Croesus," however, spoke when only six months old, and, while %0a%3c yet wielding the child's rattle, afforded portentous omens, for %0a%3c %0a%3c 5* "Aper." 65 B. ix. c. 7. %0a%3c %0a%3c 6s See c. 65 of the present Book. %0a%3c %0a%3c *' Not the diimh son mentioned by Herodotus, who saved his father's %0a%3c life at the taking of Sardes. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Chap. 113.] %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c SUPEKFI.UOUS LIMBS. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 95 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c it was at the same period that his father's empire fell. Those %0a%3c children which begin to speak the soonest, begin to walk the %0a%3c latest. The human voice acquires additional strength at the %0a%3c fourteenth year ; but in old age it becomes more shrill again, %0a%3c and there is no living creature in which it is subject to more %0a%3c frequent changes. %0a%3c %0a%3c In addition to the preceding, there are still some singular %0a%3c circumstances that deserve to be mentioned with reference to %0a%3c the voice. If saw-dust or sand is thrown down in the orches- %0a%3c tra of a theatre, or if the walls around are left in a rough %0a%3c state, or empty casks are placed there, the voice is absorbed ; %0a%3c while, on the other hand, if the wall is quite straight, or if %0a%3c built in a concave fonn, tlie voice will move along it, and will %0a%3c convey words spoken in the slightest whisper from one %0a%3c end*^ to the other, if there is no inequality in the surface to %0a%3c impede its progress. The voice, in man, contributes in a great %0a%3c degree to form his physiognomy, for we form a knowledge of %0a%3c a man before we see him by hearing his voice, just as well^ %0a%3c as if we had seen him with our eyes. There are as many %0a%3c kinds of voices, too, as there are individuals in existence, and %0a%3c each man has his own peculiar voice, just as much as his own %0a%3c peculiar physiognomy. Hence it is, that arises that vast di- %0a%3c versity of nations and languages throughout the whole earth : %0a%3c in this, too, originate the many tunes, measures, and inflexions %0a%3c that exist. But, before all other things, it is the voice that %0a%3c serves to express our sentiments,'^" a power that distinguishes %0a%3c us from the beasts ; just as, in the same way, the various shades %0a%3c and differences in language that exist among men have created %0a%3c an equally marked difference between us and the brutes. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 113. (52.) SUPEKFLTJOUS LIMBS. %0a%3c %0a%3c Supernumerary limbs, when they grow on animals, are of %0a%3c no use, Avhich is the case also with the sixth finger,