y among the vulgar. Our own writer, %0a%3c Trogus, has in a similar manner set down the physiognomy as %0a%3c indicative of the moral disposition ; one of the very gravest of %0a%3c the Roman authors, whose own*" words I will here subjoin:— %0a%3c %0a%3c " Where the forehead is broad, it is significant of a dull and %0a%3c sluggish understanding beneath ; and where it is small, it in- %0a%3c dicates an unsteady disposition. A rounded forehead denotes %0a%3c an irascible temper, it seeming as though the swelling anger %0a%3c had left its traces there. Where the eye-brows are extended %0a%3c in one straight line, they denote effeminacy in ihe owner, and %0a%3c when they are bent downwards towards the nose, an austere %0a%3c disposition. On the other hand, when the eye-brows are bent %0a%3c towards the temples, they are indicative of a sarcastic dispo- %0a%3c sition ; but when they lie very low, thcj denote malice and %0a%3c envy. Long eyes are significant of a spiteful, malicious nature; %0a%3c and where the corners of the eyes next the nose are fleshy, it %0a%3c is a sign also of a wicked disposition. If the white of the eye %0a%3c is large, it bears tokens of impudence, while those who are %0a%3c incessantly closing the ej'elids are inconstant. Largeness of %0a%3c %0a%3c 61 But they are borrowed from Aristotle, Hist. Ar.im. E. i. c. 9. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Chap. 115.] %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c EESPIEA.TION AND KTTTEIMENT. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 97 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c the ears is a sign of loquacity and foolishness." Thus much %0a%3c of what Trogus says. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 115, (53.) — RESPIRATION AND NUTRIMENT. %0a%3c %0a%3c The hreath of the lion is fetid, and that of the bear quite %0a%3c pestilential ; indeed, no beast will touch anything with Avhich %0a%3c its breath has come in contact, and substances which it has %0a%3c breathed upon will become putrid sooner than others. It is %0a%3c in man only that Nature has willed that the breath should %0a%3c become tainted in several ways, either through faultiness in %0a%3c the victuals or the teeth, or else, as is more generally the case, %0a%3c through extreme old age. Our breath in itself was insensible %0a%3c to all pain, utterly devoid as it was of all powers of touch and %0a%3c feeling, without which there can be no sensation ; ever re- %0a%3c newed, it was always forthcoming, destined to be the last ad- %0a%3c junct that shall leave the body, and the only one to remain %0a%3c when aU is gone beside ; it drew, in fine, its origin from, %0a%3c heaven. In spite of all this, however, certain penalties were %0a%3c discovered to be inflicted upon it, so that the very substance %0a%3c by the aid of which we live might become a torment to us in %0a%3c life. This inconvenience is more particularly experienced %0a%3c among the Partliians, from their youth upwards, on account %0a%3c of the indiscriminate use of food among them ; and, indeed, %0a%3c their very excess in wine causes their breath to be fetid. The %0a%3c grandees, however, of that nation have a remedy for bad breath %0a%3c in the pips of the Assyrian citron,^- which they mix with their %0a%3c food, and the aroma of which is particularly agreeable. The %0a%3c breath of the elephant will attract serpents from their holes, %0a%3c while that of the stag scorches them. We have already made %0a%3c mention*^ of certain races of men who could by suction extract %0a%3c from the body the venom of serpents ; and swine will even eat %0a%3c serpents,*^ which to other animals are poisonous. All those %0a%3c creatures which we have spoken of as insects, can be killed by %0a%3c merely sprinkling them Avith oil.*^* Vultures, which are put %0a%3c to flight by unguents, are attracted by other odours : the beetle, %0a%3c too, is- attracted by the rose. The scorpion puts to death certain %0a%3c serpents. The Scythians dip their arrows in the poison of %0a%3c %0a%3c «2 See B. xii. c. 7. " B. vii. c. 2. %0a%3c %0a%3c " S