voured greedily, %0a%3c or in too large quantities. Food is also less easily digested in %0a%3c summer than in winter, and in old age than in youth. The %0a%3c vomits which man has invented, by way of remedy for this %0a%3c evil, render the body more cold, and are more particularly inju- %0a%3c rious to the eyes and teeth. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 118. FROM WHAT CAUSES CORPULENCE ARISES; %0a%3c %0a%3c HOW IT MAY BE REDUCED. %0a%3c %0a%3c Digestion during sleep is more productive of corpulence than %0a%3c strength. Hence it is, that it is preferable for athletes to %0a%3c «5 B. ix. c. 33. 67 Or Fish-eaters. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Chap. 119.] %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c BUMMAET. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 99 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c quicken digestion by walking. Watching, at night more es- %0a%3c pecially, promotes digestion of the food. %0a%3c %0a%3c (54.) The size of the body is increased by eating sweet and %0a%3c fatty substances, as well as by drinking, while, on the other %0a%3c hand, it is diminished by eating dry, acrid, or cold substances, %0a%3c and by abstaining from drink. Some animals of Africa, as %0a%3c well as sheep, drink but once every four days. Abstinence %0a%3c from food for seven days, even, is not of necessity fatal to man ; %0a%3c and it is a well-known fact, that many persons have not died till %0a%3c after an abstinence of eleven days. Man is the only animal %0a%3c that is ever attacked with an insatiate^ craving for food. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 119. — WHAT THINGS,- BT MEHELY TASTING OF THEM, %0a%3c ALLAY HtJNGEE AND THIEST. %0a%3c %0a%3c On the other hand, there are some substances which, tasted %0a%3c in small quantities only, appease hunger and thirst, and keen %0a%3c up the strength, such as butter, for instance, cheese made of %0a%3c mares' milk, and liquorice. But the most pernicious thing of %0a%3c all, and in every station of life, is excess, and more especially %0a%3c excess in food ; in fact, it is the most prudent plan to re- %0a%